<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-21 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's a hot tub doing at the Farm Science
Review?
   ``The farmer likes hot tubs just as much as anyone does. We have
a tendency to think the farmer is not a normal person. But of course
he is,'' said Craig Fendrick, manager of the farm equipment
exposition at the Molly Caren Agricultural Center, 20 miles west of
Columbus.
   Organizers of the three-day event say the 600-plus demonstrations
and displays have changed over the years.
   ``We sat back and thought, `How come we can attract the farmer
but not his wife, his family, his neighbors?''' Fendrick said
Wednesday.
   So along with tractor demonstrations and free samples of
pesticide, the review offered tips on how to remove chocolate stains
from linen, manage personal finances, update a wardrobe with
inexpensive accessories and eat at Pizza Hut without gaining much
weight.
   Information also was available on owning a bed-and-breakfast inn
and breeding a pet llama.
   Ten or 15 years ago, the typical visitor at the review was white,
male, between 50 and 60 years old, wore overalls and attended the
event by himself.
   ``Today he's wearing designer jeans, his wife is with him, and
she's usually pushing the stroller,'' Fendrick said. ``A lot of them
out there are in their 30s.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glasnost notwithstanding, there are still
some unknown details about Soviet leaders. Such as, how big is
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze's head?
   Wyoming officials wanted to know that before Shevardnadze's
scheduled arrival in Jackson Hole today for two days of talks with
Secretary of State James Baker. Officials from the Cowboy State
didn't want to cause an international embarrassment by presenting
the minister with an ill-fitting Stetson.
   ``We tried calling the Soviet Embassy in Washington. They said
it's just kind of average. We didn't really know what that meant,''
said Dennis Curran, spokesman for Gov. Mike Sullivan.
   So they rang up the State Department, counting on the
resourcefulness of the American intelligence network.
   It took two days of research to find an answer: 60 centimeters.
   ``We weren't quite sure what that meant,'' Curran said, adding
that officials think it corresponds to a size 7{.
   The cowboy hat is intended to help Shevardnadze fit in at a
western barbecue to be thrown by Baker on Saturday night at the end
of the two-day talks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan House members returned from summer
break to temporary quarters in a former print shop and went to work
on folding chairs and cafeteria-style tables instead of their usual
stately chairs and desks.
   The House is being housed in an office building so its Capitol
chamber can be restored during the next few months.
   Low ceilings made the noise level louder than usual Wednesday,
and legislators practically had to step over each other in crowded
aisles. One lawmaker said he couldn't find a bathroom.
   ``This wouldn't pass the inspection for a dairy barn,'' Rep. Carl
Gnodtke said, ``but I guess it's good enough for legislators.''
   Despite the tight space and the noise, most lawmakers gave good
reviews to their temporary chamber.
   ``I was all set to come here and gripe, but I want to make sure
the right people get complimented,'' said Rep. Michael Griffin.
   House Speaker Lewis Dodak said he hoped members would start using
their phones to call each other on the floor to cut down on traffic
and noise.
</TEXT>
