<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--YoungFund-raiser     09-21 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Young Fund-raiser,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>12-Year-Old Raises $587 for Bullet-Proof Vests for Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police thanked a 12-year-old boy for
raising $587 to buy them two bulletproof vests.
   Seventh-grader Thomas Flores said he learned of the dangers
facing police officers when he read a magazine article describing
how a bulletproof vest saved an officer's life.
   He visited the police department, where he learned that the
department had only enough of the $300 vests for about a third of
its officers.
   So, he placed jars for contributions in stores, raising about
$300.
   Thomas, whose father is a doctor, then got more than $200 from
doctors at Bristol Hospital.
   City Council voted Monday to let the police department buy two
vests with the $587 he raised.
   ``He did it on his own,'' Lt. Thomas Killiany said Tuesday.
``We're very appreciative of the efforts of this youth.''
   It wasn't Flores' first contribution to the city. He has
volunteered to help senior citizens and with clients of the Bristol
Association for the Retarded _ and now he's looking for more
volunteer work.
   ``I'll find something,'' he said.
</TEXT>
