<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-TeddyBear     09-21 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teddy Bear,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Most Expensive Teddy Bear Bought As Anniversary Gift</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JESSICA BALDWIN</HEAD>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's was surprised when a well-preserved,
67-year-old teddy bear sold for a record $86,000.
   So was the buyer.
   ``His first words were, `You're kidding','' Jack Wilson, who was
an intermediary in the deal, said Wednesday.
   However, Wilson said, his American friend was prepared to pay
even more and was delighted to bag the bear as a 42nd anniversary
present for his wife.
   Wilson refused to identify the buyer.
   The actual bidding was done by stockbroker James Fox, 26, of
Bristol, who was given a blank check and sent to Sotheby's in London
on Tuesday.
   ``I could tell from his voice he was ashen,'' Wilson said, ``and
he said ... the auction's just over and I've got the bear.'
   ``And I said `well done, James' and then he said `you'd better
sit down because I paid 50,000 (pounds).'
   ``And I said `You've done what?!'''
   Wilson said he waited a few hours before phoning his American
friend.
   ``I guess he might have figured on a third'' of that record
price, said Wilson, who is chairman of the House of Nisbet teddy
bear manufacturers in Weston-super-Mare in southwest England.
   ``He's is very pleased. He was determined to have it.''
   The buyer and his wife are avid teddy-bear collectors, Wilson
said, and both happen to be as old as the record-breaking bear.
   The price is nearly five times the previous highest price for a
teddy bear and 61 times its catalogue estimate, said Bunny Campione,
a valuer for Sotheby's.
   Wilson said his firm would like to do a replica of the bear.
``It's up to my friend, although it seems like we have the inside
track,'' he said.
   The previous highest auction price for a teddy bear was $19,000
paid at a Christie's auction in London on May 18 for a Steiff bear
made between 1906 and 1909 for Princess Xenia, a cousin of Czar
Nicholas II.
   Several bidders stayed in the race until the price reached
$38,000, Wilson said.
   ``The other bidder after 24,000 pounds ($38,000) was a telephone
bidder and the general impression was that the caller was from
Tokyo,'' Wilson said.
   ``Bears are an art form like paintings,'' Wilson said. ``People
are used to hearing about crazy figures like $400 million for
paintings and this is the same kind of price inflation. It is a very
rare bear.''
   The German-made teddy, Edward T. is thought to date from 1927.
The bear is 24 inches long, has dual-plush fur in blond and brown,
amber and black glass eyes measuring about 1 inch in diameter,
swivel joints, a humped back and widely spaced pricked ears.
   It is believed that it was part of a batch of a few thousand, but
Mrs. Campione said the bear was in unusually good condition.
   Before going to America, the bear will on display at the National
Teddy Bear Museum in Stratford-upon-Avon this weekend.
</TEXT>
