<SECOND>AM-USAir Crash-737 Glance,0127</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-USAir Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Thumbnail Sketch of the Boeing 737-400</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   LENGTH: 119 feet, 7 inches.
   WINGSPAN: 94 feet, 9 inches.
   ENGINES: Two turbofan jets built by CFM International, a joint
venture of General Electric Co. and the French industrial consortium
SNECMA.
   CAPACITY: Pilot, co-pilot and up to 146 passengers and flight
attendants in typical mixed-class configuration, or up to 168 in
charter configuration.
   RANGE: Up to 2,879 miles.
   HISTORY: Part of the 737 family of jets, the smallest jets made
by the Boeing Co. of Seattle.
   The first of the twin-engine, short-to-medium-range 737s flew on
April 9, 1967. Piedmont Airlines, which merged with USAir, was the
first customer to get the 737-400.
