<FIRST>r w PM-CatastrophicCare     09-21 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Care,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Administration Asks Congress to Keep Catastrophic Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is supporting efforts
to retain catastrophic medical insurance for retirees amid growing
indications that Congress may bow to pressure to repeal the program.
   ``Catastrophic meets a very real need in protecting senior
citizens against financial ruin'' as a result of an illness,
Secretary of Health and Human Services Louis Sullivan told the
Senate Finance Committee. Although some adjustments may be needed,
he added, ``repeal would be a big mistake.''
   But leaders of the House and Senate acknowledged Wednesday the
number of lawmakers who will vote to repeal the program outright is
growing. Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, an author of the program and
chairman of the Finance Committee, said the House probably will vote
for repeal.
   Democratic leaders of the House agreed to allow a repeal vote
next week when the House considers a Ways and Means Committee plan
for keeping catastrophic care but scaling the program back.
   The program, the largest expansion ever of Medicare, is under
attack from two groups of retirees: those who already are covered by
a catastrophic plan, including federal retirees; and higher-income
older Americans who object to paying for coverage for those at the
bottom of the economic ladder.
   Sullivan said that although the administration prefers no changes
in the program, it would support a modification backed by Senate
leaders of both parties.
   That proposal would eliminate coverage for most prescription
drugs; scale back coverage of physicians' fees, and reduce the
surtax on higher-income retirees that pays for most of the program.
   ``We want to do everything we can to preserve the core benefits''
in the program, Sullivan told the committee.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., said Congress should repeal the
program and consider a replacement as part of an overall national
health strategy.
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., said any discussion of repeal should
include recognition that ``people's lives are at stake.'' Repeal, he
said, would amount to ``denying somebody the right to get an
operation in a hospital and allow them to live ... without going
bankrupt.''
</TEXT>
