<FIRST>r w PM-CropInsurance     09-21 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crop Insurance,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Crop Insurance Most Equitable Way to Aid Farmers, Report
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal crop insurance program needs
improvements, but it is a better way to provide disaster aid to
farmers than emergency loans and direct payments, a congressional
report says.
   And a government commission says some changes could be made
immediately in the crop insurance program to boost farmer
participation beyond the current 25 percent.
   The program needs to be simplified and made more responsive, and
the administration could be improved, Ray Davis and Bill Classen,
co-chairmen of the Commission for the Improvement of the Federal
Crop Insurance Program, told a House subcommittee on Wednesday.
   A General Accounting Office report said the federal government
spent $17.6 billion between 1980 and 1988 assisting farmers who lost
crops because of drought or other natural causes.
   About $6.9 billion of that was direct assistance, $6.4 billion
came through emergency loan programs and $4.3 billion was spent to
subsidize crop insurance.
   However, the GAO said the crop insurance program is a more
equitable and efficient way to provide aid to farmers.
   The GAO said its investigation showed that most farmers don't buy
crop insurance because they are used to having Congress come to the
rescue with special assistance whenever there is a major crisis.
   For example, $4 billion in direct payments were made in 1988 by
emergency act of Congress because of the severe drought, said the
GAO.
   Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., who chairs the subcommittee on
conservation, credit and rural development, said 65 percent to 70
percent participation in the crop insurance program is needed to
make it work.
   ``We cannot continue to do this,'' English said, referring to
Congress' ad hoc approach to agricultural disasters. ``The costs are
too high.''
   John Harman, of the GAO, said that in examining disaster
assistance programs, his agency found that direct payments or
emergency loans can result in different treatment for similarly
affected disaster victims.
   ``In contrast, the terms of compensation under crop insurance are
determined before a disaster occurs and therefore, crop insurance
provides farmers equitable assistance more consistently,'' he said.
   The GAO also found that crop insurance, because it is
consistently available, allows farmers more flexibility in
long-range planning.
   ``We recognize that the crop insurance program has had a history
of management problems that, in the short term, makes it difficult
to justify the current crop insurance program as the sole source of
disaster assistance to farmers,'' said Harman.
   He said Congress should provide a transition period if it decides
to rely exclusively on crop insurance for disaster assistance.
   Davis and Classen testified before the House Agriculture
subcommittee on conservation, credit and rural development.
   ``The commission believes that many changes to effect immediate
administrative improvements in the program can be made under
existing law by the secretary of agriculture and the Federal Crop
Insurance Corp.,'' said Davis and Classen. ``These changes would
foster increased participation by farmers.''
</TEXT>
