<FIRST>r w PM-ArlingtonAshes     09-21 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arlington Ashes,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Burial of Ashes at Arlington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation advancing in the House would give
more veterans the opportunity to choose Arlington National Cemetery
as their final resting place.
   The national military cemetery, on a hillside directly across the
Potomac River from Washington, D.C., is expected to run out of
casket space in 2020. The columbarium, where urns are stored, is
expected to be full in 2029.
   But a bill approved by the House Veterans Affairs Committee
Wednesday would allow veterans who qualify for burial at Arlington
to choose an unmarked burial for their ashes. Although the
legislation doesn't specify the site, one proposal would have ashes
buried in one area with the names of all the deceased carved on a
large memorial stone.
   The problem of dwindling space at Arlington has been growing as
the average age of the veterans population has grown older. The
number of veterans over 65 years old total nearly 6 million now and
should be nearly 9 million by the turn of the century.
   Until restrictions were enacted in 1967, any honorably discharged
veteran could be buried at Arlington. Roughly 190,000 people are
buried in the 612-acre cemetery.
   The disposal of ashes in a common area would be strictly optional
and would not use any space that could be used for caskets, the bill
says.
   The ashes, which would not be placed in urns, would be buried
under sod or in small hole. An aide to Rep. Charles E. Bennett,
D-Fla., the bill's chief sponsor, said the Army would insist on a
fitting ceremony and interment to address concerns ``that it may
seem like a mass grave.''
   In another action, the committee approved legislation to create a
World War II memorial in or near the District of Columbia, paid for
by donations and taxes.
   No decisions have been made on size, location and design of the
memorial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
