<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-PowerPlay Bjt   09-21 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Power Play, Bjt,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Shows Renewed Strength in Politburo Shake-up'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's swift elimination of a
quarter of the ruling Politburo, including two leading
conservatives, demonstrates his political strength just as doubts
about his staying power were gaining currency in Washington.
   The dramatic power play, executed on the eve of Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze's meeting with President Bush at the White
House, served to counter suggestions that the Soviet president had
been weakened by increasing public frustration with worsening
economic conditions and heightened ethnic tensions.
   The shake-up could be seen as strengthening Shevardnadze's hand
as he seeks to revitalize the arms control process during talks with
Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III in Washington and
Wyoming.
   With successive moves during the last year to consolidate his
power, Gorbachev may now have broken high-level resistance and
opened the way for sweeping changes that reformers say are needed if
Gorbachev's program of economic restructuring is to shake the
country out of the doldrums.
   The party's Central Committee meeting that shuffled the makeup of
the party's Politburo also handed Gorbachev an early opportunity
next year to use a party congress to reach further down into the
party apparatus to shake out bureaucrats blamed for smothering
reform.
   The president and Communist Party chief successfully instituted
glasnost, which has brought more open criticism and debate.
   He overhauled the political system to encourage competitive
elections and representative oversight of government operations.
   And his ``new thinking'' in foreign policy has done much to
dispel what he called his country's ``enemy image'' abroad.
   But Gorbachev's reforms so far have failed to relieve the
grinding economic hardship that has left consumers frustrated by
barren cupboards and empty store shelves at a time when their own
media show them the practical pleasures of living in the
comparatively wealthy West.
   Outspoken reformists in and out of the recently elected Congress
of People's Deputies have said the transition from the old system of
central planning and control to a new market economy requires
radical stripping away of bureaucratic control over supplies and
prices. But Gorbachev so far has talked about such steps without
actually taking them.
   With the retirement of veteran Ukrainian party boss Vladimir V.
Shcherbitsky, 71, the 58-year-old Gorbachev is now the only member
of the Politburo elevated to the ruling body during the regime of
the late Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   Shcherbitsky has long been regarded as one of the most
conservative forces in the leadership but too entrenched in his home
republic for Gorbachev to unseat him.
   Former KGB chief Viktor M. Chebrikov, 66, another of those
retired Wednesday, also was regarded as a conservative anchor who
opposed many Gorbachev reforms.
   The departures left one prominent conservative, Yegor K.
Ligachev, in place. But both Gorbachev and Ligachev have taken pains
to express their support for each other while often disagreeing on
policy.
   Gorbachev installed two of his own men, Gen. Vladimir A.
Kryuchkov, the new KGB chief, and Yuri D. Maslyukov, who heads
economic planning, as full members of the Politburo, which now
numbers 11 men.
   The retirements also included non-voting member Yuri Solovyev,
who thus became the first member of the party's top leadership to
fall after being defeated at the polls.
   Solovyev, who was rejected by the voters of Leningrad when he ran
unopposed for a seat in the Congress, already had been removed as
Leningrad party chief.
   Gorbachev opened the way for graceful retirement from the top
echelons of Soviet power when he paid public tribute to Andrei A.
Gromyko as he relieved him of the presidency a year ago.
   He continued that practice Wednesday.
   When it was announced that Shcherbitsky, Chebrikov and Viktor P.
Nikonov were going out on pension, Tass said, Gorbachev thanked the
three Politburo members warmly for their ``many years of fruitful
activity'' in the party.
   Departures from the party leadership were once accomplished only
by death or abrupt ouster into instant obscurity or public disgrace.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Michael Putzel is chief of the AP's Moscow bureau.
</TEXT>
