<DOCNO> AP890921-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EducationRdp     09-21 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Rdp,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats, Republicans, Educators Vie for Piece of Summit Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With President Bush guaranteed a prominent role
in next week's education summit, Democrats and Republicans _ and to
a lesser extent educators _ already are jockeying for a piece of the
action.
   However, money is one key subject absent from most of the lofty
proposals and the flurry of activities before the two-day meeting
with the nation's governors.
   Democratic leaders of Congress stole the scene Wednesday by
announcing six national performance goals to upgrade American
education, including lower dropout rates, higher college-going rates
and early childhood education for all poor 4-year-olds by 1995 or
earlier.
   The Democrats, joined by Maryland state and local politicians,
assembled at a showcase school in a Washington suburb about 2 {
hours before Bush attended a private seminar with some of the
nation's best-known educators who offered advice for the summit in
Charlottesville, Va.
   Thirty minutes before Bush's seminar, the National Education
Association, the nation's largest teachers' union, released its own
``Classroom Agenda for the Education Summit.''
   NEA President Keith Geiger broached the politically volatile
issue of money and noted that for every $3 state and local
governments added to education in the 1980s, the federal government
took $1 away. He said the federal share of the school dollar for
elementary and secondary schools declined from 9.2 percent in 1981
to 6.3 percent in 1989.
   Geiger said money should be a key focus of the summit and added,
``The federal government must become a more active partner in
promoting progress.''
   Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, on hand to congratulate the Democrats
for their proposals, conceded ``there will be a lot of discussions
about federal funding'' at the summit.
   ``But I think the important thing is to note that the governors,
at the White House, committed to this process of goal-setting
because we know, first of all there's a big deficit; secondly, the
president made a commitment not to raise any money; thirdly, most of
the money being raised now ... is at the state and local level,''
Clinton said.
   ``I think the most important thing is to decide where the country
needs to go in education and then once you do that you can develop a
strategy to achieve those goals that assesses responsibility,''
Clinton said, who is co-leading summit preparations for the National
Governors Association.
   The Democrats also seek to raise students' basic skills
achievement levels, boost their performance in math, science and
foreign languages, and expand the pool of qualified teachers.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine called the list
``Democratic education goals for the nation,'' and said his party
``has long championed educational opportunity for all Americans. The
major federal education programs were Democratic initiatives.''
   While the Democrats gathered at Eleanor Roosevelt High School in
Greenbelt, Md., Bush sat down for private talks at the White House
with a dozen education leaders, assuring them that the deck was not
``stacked'' for the summit and that he was eager to hear their ideas.
   Dr. James P. Comer, a Yale University child psychiatrist and
expert on educating poor children, said afterward that he entered
the White House skeptical, but emerged ``relieved and impressed that
(Bush) does understand the complexity'' of the problems facing the
schools.
   Comer cautioned against putting ``more pressures on educators
without creating ... the circumstances that can support them and
make it possible for people to reach those goals.''
   But University of Tennessee President Lamar Alexander, the former
Republican governor of Tennessee, said, ``We need clear goals and
... brand-new school systems.''
   While the Democrats put no price tag on how much it would cost to
meet their education goals, the list clearly would entail major
increases in the $22 billion Education Department budget.
   Their policy statement promised that the Democrats ``will
continue to seek adequate funding for the major federal education
initiatives,'' especially efforts to improve opportunities for the
poor and handicapped, and aid for schools and college students.
</TEXT>
