<FIRST>r i PM-Soviets-Talks     09-21 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-Talks,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kremlin Dismayed at US Slowdown in Pace of Arms Control Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze's journey to
the United States for superpower negotiations comes at a time the
Soviets are dealing with complex internal difficulties and talking
as if the thrill is gone from relations with the United States.
   ``That the Bush administration is not consumed by the
enthusiastic wish to reach agreements with the Soviet Union is
recognized even here as an indisputable fact,'' Pravda wrote from
Washington, D.C., as Shevardnadze flew to the United States.
   Shevardnadze and Baker last met in Paris in July, and for the
Soviets, arms control remains the acid test of their relationship
with the United States.
   ``Successful development of U.S.-Soviet relations can hardly be
imagined without progress in the area of arms limitation and
reduction,'' the Tass news agency recently informed readers.
   Shevardnadze and Baker will meet over the weekend in Jackson
Hole, Wyo.
   The Kremlin's outward mood has shifted from elation to dismay as
President Bush has presided over a slowdown in the pace of arms
control talks, an area which gave Mikhail S. Gorbachev his first
tangible policy achievement with the signing of a treaty with former
President Reagan to eliminate medium- and shorter-range nuclear
missiles.
   For Soviets, whose dreary, shortage-plagued lot has failed to
improve and in many cases worsened under Gorbachev's economic
reforms, the 1987 treaty and Reagan's visit to Moscow seemed to
presage a new and safer world, with a good share of credit going to
their own leader.
   But with President Bush, the Soviets are dealing with a president
who said this week he's in no hurry for a summit meeting with
Gorbachev.
   This time the Soviets have dropped heavy hints that Shevardnadze
will unveil a new offer in Washington, where he pays a call on Bush
today, or later in Wyoming.
   Exactly what Shevardnadze is carrying remains under wraps, but
Tass quoted him upon departure from Moscow as saying he has a
personal message from Gorbachev to Bush on disarmament.
   ``It's a deep and constructive document'' designed to spur the
talks in the United States, Shevardnadze said without giving details.
   Superpower negotiations aside, Shevardnadze's activities before
he boarded a special Washington-bound jetliner give a glimpse of how
daunting the problems facing his country are.
   According to Gennady Gerasimov, his spokesman, the snowy-haired
member of the ruling Politburo attended a Kremlin meeting charged
with finding a way out of the spasms of violence between Soviet
ethnic groups in which 200 people have died in the last 19 months.
   In addition, entrenched portions of the Soviet bureaucracy,
fearful of losing position and privilege, have resisted movement
toward a more market-oriented economy with its attendant risks.
   Official press accounts assert the superpowers are within reach
of an accord to boost a worldwide ban on chemical weapons, and
Gerasimov on Wednesday welcomed Baker's statement that the Americans
may withdraw their proposal for a ban on mobile ICBMs, one sticking
point in the Geneva talks on long-range weapons.
   Yet the Soviets have expressed dissatisfaction with the pace of
arms control talks under the Bush administration.
   Usually smiling and debonair, Shevardnadze earlier this month
denounced the ``constraint and timidity'' of the officials in charge
of Washington's new arms reduction policy. It was another signal of
the Kremlin's frustration at the latest turn taken by U.S.-Soviet
relations.
   Putting superpower talks for a 50 percent reduction of strategic
weapons on a faster track is a major concern of the Soviets, and
they've all but openly accused Bush and Baker of neglecting the
parleys.
   ``The Geneva negotiations and the American delegation's stance
there call for a powerful political impetus,'' Tass said. ``Only the
U.S. president and the secretary of state are able to provide it.''
   ``When creating the atmosphere around the forthcoming political
contacts, the Soviet side would like to concentrate primarily on
recent positive statements by President George Bush and Secretary of
State James Baker,'' Tass said. Among those statements is Bush's
professed support for Gorbachev's domestic reform agenda, Tass said.
   Whatever the course of the talks, Shevardnadze should feel right
at home in the mountain air of Jackson Hole. His native Georgia in
the Soviet south lies in the Caucasus range, and its tallest peak,
Mount Elbrus, tops Grand Teton by almost a mile.
</TEXT>
