<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-WinnersandLosers     09-21 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Winners and Losers,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Politburo Strongly Pro-Gorbachev ^With PM-Soviet-Power Play,
Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The makeup of the Soviet Politburo has shifted
sharply and now reflects strong support of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms.
   The Communist Party's ruling body Wednesday retired its last
Brezhnev man, die-hard conservative Ukrainian party leader Vladimir
V. Shcherbitsky, and the first Kremlin leader to lose a public vote
of confidence, former Leningrad party chief Yuri F. Solovyov.
   Key Gorbachev supporters also joined the Politburo: Yuri D.
Maslyukov, the man appointed to decentralize economic planning;
Vladimir A. Kryuchkov, a KGB chief who spent his career in the
secret police force's foreign operations rather than in repression
of domestic dissent; and Gorbachev's Mideast and Far East adviser,
Yevgeny M. Primakov, who also is a leader in the new Soviet
legislature.
   The Politburo also lost one KGB general and gained two with the
retirement of former KGB chief Viktor Chebrikov and the promotion of
Kryuchkov and Boris K. Pugo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WINNERS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Promoted to full Politburo membership</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri D. Maslyukov, 52, named last year to transform the Soviet
central planning agency, Gosplan, from a vast bureaucracy trying to
control the production and distribution of every nut and bolt to a
smaller agency that only sets general economic goals. He is a
Russian born in Tadzhikistan who held jobs in engineering and the
defense industry for 26 years. He took on the decentralization of
the Soviet economy in 1988, replacing Nikolai V. Talyzin, who lost
his non-voting status on the Politburo on Wednesday.
   Vladimir A. Kryuchkov, 65, a career spy promoted to run the KGB
last year and the first KGB chairman to face a public confirmation
hearing this summer. He is a Russian schooled in law and diplomacy
and ran foreign spy operations for years. As KBG chairman he has
launched a publicity campaign emphasizing the agency's role in
capturing foreign spies and terrorists while playing down its role
in repressing dissidents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Promoted to non-voting Politburo membership</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Yevgeny M. Primakov, 59, a Middle East and Far East expert
elected chairman of one of the houses of the Soviet legislature in
June. He could play an important role in pushing Gorbachev's reforms
through the legislislature. He is a Russian who started his career
as a government official overseeing broadcasting. He has worked in
government think tanks since 1970.
   Boris K. Pugo, 52, the youngest member of the Politburo. He is a
Latvian KGB general whose Bolshevik father is believed to have been
imprisoned by Josef Stalin in the purges of the 1930s. He served as
head of the Latvian KGB before becoming party chief in Latvia in
1984. Many Latvian activists were happy to see him replaced last
year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LOSERS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Retired from full membership on the Politburo</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, 71, Ukrainian party chief. Many
Ukrainian reformers blame him for stifling dissent and holding back
Gorbachev's economic reforms in the nation's breadbasket.
Shcherbitsky lost his first three attempts to win nomination to the
new Congress of People's Deputies in his capital, Kiev. He is
Ukrainian, an engineer and lifelong party bureaucrat.
   Viktor M. Chebrikov, 66, the former KGB chief who last year was
promoted to the Politburo and given the job of running the criminal
justice system. A Russian, he worked as an engineer for two years
before moving to party jobs in the Ukraine. He was deputy chairman
and then chairman of the KGB from 1968 to 1988 during two decades of
crackdowns on dissidents.
   Viktor P. Nikonov, 60, a agricultural and party bureaucrat. He is
a Russian who moved to Moscow as deputy minister of agriculture in
1979. In last year's Politburo shake-up, he became Yegor K.
Ligachev's deputy in the party commission on agriculture.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Retired from non-voting membership on the Politburo</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Yuri F. Solovyov, 65, the Leningrad regional party chief who
despite running unopposed lost election to a seat in the Congress
last spring when more than 50 percent of the voters crossed his name
off the ballot. Reformers in the Leningrad Communist Party
successfully demanded his removal from the party leadership. A
Russian, he spent 22 years as a subway construction engineer in
Leningrad before moving to party work in 1974.
   Nikolai V. Talyzin, 60, Gorbachev's first choice for planning
chief in 1985, who was demoted last year when the Kremlin opted for
more radical decentralization of the economy. The Russian engineer
who moved into government through the Ministry of Communications has.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Four long-time party bureaucrats also were promoted to
secretaries of the Communist Party Central Committee:
   _Yegor S. Stroyev, regional party secretary in Orel, Russia. Born
Feb. 25, 1937. Russian, noted agricultural expert.
   _Yuri A. Manayenkov, regional party secretary in Lipetsk, Russia.
Born Aug. 2, 1936. Russian, journalist, agricultural expert.
   _Gumer I. Usmanov, regional party secretary in Tartar region of
Russia. Born in 1932. Tatar, agricultural administrator who spoke
publicly against the political rehabilitation of maverick Communist
Boris Yeltsin.
   _Andrei N. Girenko, regional party secretary in the Crimea. Born
March 16, 1936. Ukrainian mining engineer.
</TEXT>
