<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Evacuees     09-21 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Evacuees,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evacuees Return to U.S. Mainland from Devastated Virgin Islands</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panicked residents and tourists who scrambled to the
first evacuation plane out of St. Croix told tales of horror after
arriving back on the U.S. mainland.
   Hurricane Hugo's devastation of the popular Caribbean tourist
retreat was followed by a swarm of gun-wielding looters, prompting
President Bush to dispatch military police and arrange for
evacuations.
   ``We just got lucky,'' said Bob McManus of West Point, Conn.,
about being among 145 passengers on a special Pan Am evacuation
flight arranged by U.S. marshals Wednesday night. He said the sight
of the plane at the St. Croix airport touched off a stampede of
those trying to flee.
   ``The looters were everywhere there,'' said McManus, still
gripping the 4-iron golf club he used for protection.
   ``They said, `We're in charge now.' At one grocery store, they
just rolled up trucks and loaded them up.''
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Brotman of Camden, N.J., who was on
temporary assignment in St. Croix, said he first had to protect
himself from the storm, then the looters.
   ``It was the most devastating experience of my life,'' Brotman
said. ``We had three originally in our condomimium, and after the
storm there were 18 in one room with mattresses up against every
wall and rope to hold the shutters closed.''
   Nadine Gregg, owner of an art gallery in St. Croix, said she fled
to protect her 5-month-old son from violence several evacuees said
was tinged with racism.
   ``White people are scared. It's totally a racial thing,'' she
said. ``They need martial law down there.''
   ``The younger blacks are going crazy,'' McManus said. ``They're
shouting racial slurs at the whites.''
   Pan Am planned four more evacuation flights today and the U.S.
Coast Guard dispatched cutters to aid those requesting evacuation.
</TEXT>
