<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-21 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar remained sharply lower against the
Japanese yen Thursday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose.
   The dollar closed at 145.00 yen, down 1.25 yen from Wednesday's
close of 146.25 yen. It started trading lower at 144.90 yen and
moved between 144.82 yen and 145.25 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shot up 274.44 points, or 0.80
percent, ending the day at 34,745.02. It had lost 0.49 points the
previous day.
   The index rose as market players were reassured by the yen's
rebound against the dollar, and buying orders for a variety of
issues were given since the opening, said Masahiro Umemori, a stock
analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``Participants were buying supermarket issues considering that
reorganization and easing regulations on large-scale retail stores
could be positive steps to improve U.S.-Japan structural problems,''
he said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's drop followed an overnight
downswing on overseas markets over speculation that West Germany may
raise the country's interest rates.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said Japanese market players were
watching closely whether the West German Bundesbank will take action
on its interest rates during its scheduled meeting Thursday.
   Although institutional investors and trading houses bought the
dollar as it fell, the majority of participants slowed down their
dollar-buying ahead of the monetary talks in Washington this weekend
among the Group of Seven industrialized nations, which might come up
with some measure to stem the dollar's strength, said the dealer,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Participants in the G-7 meeting are Japan, the United States,
West Germany, Britain, Italy, France and Canada.
</TEXT>
