<FIRST>u a AM-USAirCrash 7thLd-Writethru a0478 09-21 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir Crash, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0478,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>USAir Plane Down After Aborted Takeoff, At Least Three Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, 6th graf, `At least ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
police now say only two confirmed dead; picks up 8th graf pvs: `Two people
...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY15,16,18, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A USAir 737 carrying 61 people skidded off a
runway at LaGuardia Airport and splashed into the East River late
Wednesday, killing at least two people, after the pilot tried to
abort the takeoff, authorities said.
   ``The pilot seemed to be accelerating but didn't have enough
power to get the plane up,'' said survivor Larry Martin of New York
City, who huddled in blankets with his wife, Valerie.
   ``Something happened and he put on the brakes. The plane took a
dip and the next thing I knew all hell broke loose,'' Martin said.
``People were on top of each other. People were screaming. There was
the smell of gas. Everyone was saying `Get out! Get out! Get out!'''
   Witnesses said the aircraft split into two pieces, with part of
the jetliner suspended out of the water. Some survivors crawled onto
the wing to await their rescue, and some ended up in the water.
   ``They were hanging from the pier, hanging on the wing, hanging
from the front of the plane,'' said police Lt. Larry Johnston.
   Sgt. Jack Casey, a police diver at the crash site, said he
removed two bodies from the plane and heard of a third fatality. But
51 people escaped from the plane unhurt, said Mayor Edward I. Koch,
who was on the scene.
   Stephen Berger, executive director of the Port Authority, said he
knew of only two deaths in the crash.
   Two people were taken to Jamaica Hospital in critical condition,
said Port Authority spokesman Bill Cahill. A third person was in
stable condition at another hospital after suffering a heart attack.
   The pilot tried to abort the takeoff for an unknown reason, said
Kathleen Bergen, spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation Administration
in New York.
   The pilot aborted the takeoff at 11:29 p.m. and the plane skidded
off runway into 25 to 40 feet of water in Bowery Bay, about 50 to
100 feet from the end of the runway built on pilings in the water,
officials said.
   ``The first third of the airplane is resting on the approach
lights,'' said Ms. Bergen. ``The rest of the plane is in the river.''
   Some people were trapped in the plane's tail section and were
removed, said Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Paul Milligan.
   Milligan said the plane skidded off the runway during takeoff and
landed in the water, about 2,000 feet from the end of the runway, at
11:35 p.m. EDT.
   Fire officials said survivors were being taken to the Pan Am
Shuttle terminal at LaGuardia. Coast Guard small boats and planes
were on the scene, as well as scores of police and emergency
vehicles.
   A USAir spokeswoman in Arlington, Va., Susan Young, said Flight
5050, a Boeing 737-400, was bound for Charlotte, N.C. She said the
plane carried 55 passengers and a crew of six.
   ``The evacuation of the aircraft was completed at 12:30 a.m. by
raft,'' she said.
   The airplane was scheduled to leave for North Carolina at 7:27
p.m. EDT, but was delayed three hours by heavy rain, as were all
flights into and out of the New York area.
   The plane's engines were apparently cut off halfway down the
runway and went into reverse thrust, said David Hawthorne, a CBS
News producer, who was on the plane.
   ``At that time no one thought there was going to be real
trouble,'' Hawthorne told CBS News via cellular telephone. Hawthorne
said he was sitting near the front of the plane, which split into
two or three pieces.
   ``I was able to get up and start going toward the back,'' he
said. ``A lot of women and children were screaming that they
couldn't swim, they couldn't swim.''
   Rescuers and crew members were trying to keep people calm, he
said.
   ``Most people were pretty calm after we got out onto the wing of
the plane,'' he said. ``And they waited for boats to come pick us up
and the rescuers also arrived and I have to say they did a pretty
good job of keeping everybody calm and getting them safely off.''
</TEXT>
