<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ForeignAid     09-21 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Aid,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Readies Poland Aid Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate is ready to dispatch beefed-up U.S.
economic aid to Poland's first non-communist government in four
decades.
   In addition, the Democrats who control both the Senate and House
are signaling their willingness to fight for an aid package far more
potent than anything President Bush has so far proposed or than the
$45 million initiative in the pending aid bill.
   The Senate readied the $14.4 billion appropriations measure for
certain passage in a series of votes on amendments Wednesday. Final
action was postponed pending agreement on an unrelated anti-drug
package.
   The Senate Appropriations Committee included the bolstered aid
for Poland in the bill after contending that $10 million in economic
aid initially proposed by Bush was ``totally inadequate'' to
demonstrate U.S. support for Poland's surging economic and political
reform movement.
   Democrats on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee raised the
hackles of GOP members Wednesday as they contended the Bush aid
proposal is ``pathetically timid.''
   With all but one Republican member boycotting, and ignoring
arguments that the money is not available, the committee voted 10 to
1 to authorize spending nearly $1.2 billion over three years in
economic assistance for both Poland and Hungary.
   The keystone of the Democratic initiative is the creation of
economic development funds for both countries. The Polish fund would
be authorized at $300 million for each of the three years; the fund
for Hungary at $75 million a year.
   House Democrats also indicated their willingness on Wednesday to
substantially increase aid to Poland.
   ``I believe we should give the administration everything it has
asked for _ and then do more,'' Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., told the
House Foreign Affairs Committee. ``If we do not come to Poland's
aid, how can we expect others to make the sacrifices necessary to
obtain freedom and democracy?''
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., the House majority leader, said
Congress must find ways to rise above the nation's budget crunch and
provide assistance to Poland and Hungary equal to the historic
nature of their apparent transformation from communist rule.
   ``Now is not the time for the niceties of bookkeeping; now is the
time for imagination and innovation,'' Gephardt said. ``Visionaries
do not wear green eyeshades.''
   Acting on amendments to the overall foreign aid bill, the Senate
voted Wednesday to boost aid to El Salvador to $90 million after
appeals to give the country's new president ``a chance to succeed.''
   Voting 67-33, the legislators removed from the bill a provision
that would have cut the aid into three installments to be made
available at four-month intervals, with Congress given virtual veto
power over the last installment.
   The Senate then voted to peg U.S. military aid to El Salvador at
$90 million, a $5 million boost.
   Opponents of the restrictions contended that they represented an
unwarranted slap at the government of Salvadoran President Alfredo
Cristiani at a time when there is a chance to end a ten-year civil
war.
   Cristiani was sworn in June 1 as the victorious candidate of the
rightist Arena party.
   ``It will be a blow to him politically, at the very moment _ the
very hour _ when we ought to be encouraging him to go forward,''
said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who joined a rare
liberal-conservative alliance to oppose the restrictions.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., and other senators contended that the
Arena Party has been linked to death-squad activity in the past and
has failed to totally stamp out human rights abuses.
   The annual foreign aid spending bill pays for programs to bolster
the military forces of friendly nations and to support economic
development in poor countries.
</TEXT>
