<FIRST>r w PM-ShevardnadzeStatement     09-21 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shevardnadze Statement,430</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze's remarks to reporters on arriving at Andrews
Air Force Base on Wednesday. Shevardnadze's remarks were translated
by his interpreter.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q: Can you tell us what you're bringing?
   Shevardnadze: Well, I am bringing a lot of paper. But they are
interesting papers.
   Q: Are they surprises?
   Shevardnadze: I would not call them surprises, but we have
serious proposals. I've brought a letter from Mikhail Gorbachev to
President Bush and I would like to say that we have come to
Washington at a very important stage in the development of
Soviet-U.S. relations, also at a time when major very important,
fundamental changes are taking place in the Soviet society and when
many things are changing in the East-West relationship.
   And we have to state that to a large extent those changes in the
East-West relationship result from the changes from the positive
developments in Soviet-U.S. relations. But we believe that we should
not stand still. We should not mark time. We should move forward.
The experience that we have gained thus far permits us to hope that
there will be further movement.
   President Bush has mentioned the possibility of a new closeness
between the Soviet Union and the U.S. and I would add that we have
to move from a level of mutual understanding to a level of working
together to a level of partnership wherever this is possible. So
this is what we are bringing with us to Washington. My meeting with
the president is tomorrow. We shall begin discussions with the
secretary of state.
   Mikhail Gorbachev's letter contains some very important
proposals, specifically, mostly on arms control and on reducing the
military standoff between our two countries. And those proposals, I
have no doubt, serve to remove most of the obstacles holding up
progress and an agreement in Geneva, in Vienna at conventional arms
discussions, also at the negotiations on a convention banning
chemical weapons and nuclear testing talks and so on. And of course,
we will be reporting to you more specifically during the talks and
after them.
   Q: Mr. Shevardnadze, are you going to tell the president that you
wish the pace, the progress of U.S.-Soviet relations would quicken?
Has he been too cautious?
   Shevardnadze: Well, I do believe that we have reason to say that
the pace of the development of Soviet-American relations has to
quicken. That would serve the interest of our two countries, the
Soviet Union and the U.S., and the interests of the world. Thank you.
</TEXT>
