<FIRST>r w PM-TroopsDispute     09-21 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troops Dispute,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virgin Islands Governor Says He Did Not Request Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virgin Islands Gov. Alexander Farrelly says he
didn't ask for the troops sent by President Bush to his islands in
the wake of looting related to Hurricane Hugo.
   Interviewed by AP Network News from his offices in Charlotte
Amalie, Farrelly said his office had spoken to officials in
Washington about the possibility of requesting troops, ``and we got
the impression that if we asked for help we would get it.''
   But asked whether he had in fact sought federal help in restoring
order, Farrelly said, ``We have not done so yet.''
   White House spokesman Steve Hart, informed of Farrelly's remarks,
said, ``That's contrary to the information I have.'' Hart said the
White House would stand by its earlier statement, which said that
Farrelly had requested the federal troops.
   Bush ordered two military police battalions and a headquarters
unit totaling about 1,100 men to the islands to restore order. There
have been unconfirmed reports that National Guard troops joined
looters in the islands.
   Regarding reports of looting and rioting, the governor said:
``There is some looting, no doubt about that. But there is no near
state of anarchy. And I should know. I'm in the streets every day
and I'm the governor of this territory.''
