<FIRST>r w PM-WorldBank     09-21 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Bank,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Leaders to Face Soviets, Chinese Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Requests from the Soviet Union for membership
and from China for more money were facing members of the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund at the beginning of their annual
meetings.
   Financial leaders from 152 countries were opening the meetings of
the twin organizations today, with representatives from 24
debt-strapped developing nations planning to meet behind closed
doors to discuss their concerns.
   President Bush is scheduled to address all the leaders next week.
   High on the agenda this year is the request by the Soviet Union
for membership in the two lending organizations, which would bring
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's government a greater role in
world affairs outside his nation's allies. The United States has
opposed membership for Moscow.
   There have been suggestions recently that the IMF and World Bank
should concentrate in the next decade on bringing the Soviet Union
into the economic framework of the non-communist world.
   Membership would also allow the Soviet Union to claim loans from
the twin organizations.
   In advance of the Washington meetings, World Bank President
Barber Conable announced Wednesday that he intends to resume new
loans to China in the near future, but refused to name a date.
   China, the bank's largest borrower after India, has been getting
$2 billion in loans a year. But Conable suspended consideration of
$780 million in new loans after the Chinese government's bloody
crackdown on pro-democracy forces in June. The bank has continued to
disburse loans granted to China in the past.
   In addition to the Soviet and Chinese matters, delegates were
expected to discuss:
   _the Third World's $1.3 trillion debt, and the progress of
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady's plan for reducing the burden.
Agreements have been tentatively reached for Mexico and the
Philippines, but the problem of Brazil, the Third World's biggest
debtor, has not yet been tackled. Brady will be the chief U.S.
representative at the meetings.
   _how to deal financially with the worsening state of the
environment, especially in developing countries.
   _Conable's bid for $14.5 billion in contributions to make easy
loans over three years to about 35 countries where the average
income is only about $1 a day or less.
   ``These are the poorest of the poor,'' he told reporters
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
