<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Bennett,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Threat Doesn't Stop Drug Czar From Delivering Message</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CD2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST CLEVELAND, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug czar William Bennett
went outside with a bullhorn to give his anti-drug message to
schoolchildren after a bomb threat forced police to evacuate an
elementary school.
   No bomb was found and Police Chief Richard Vaughn said he
believed the threat was a prank. Bennett didn't consider it a
laughing matter.
   ``It's a sad thing. This is what drugs have done to this
country,'' Bennett said after Wednesday afternoon's assembly at
Chambers Elementary School.
   Anyone who would make such a threat to harm children is ``small
and petty and wicked,'' he said.
   Bennett spoke to more than 700 pupils and 45 faculty members at
the school. It was the last in a series of meetings with Ohio
mayors, ministers and officials in which Bennett outlined the Bush
administration's four-pronged, $7.9 billion proposal to fight drug
abuse.
   Bennett said he plans to carry his anti-drug message to all 50
states before Thanksgiving.
   Funding for police departments in poor neighborhoods must be
increased to protect the majority of residents who are not drug
users, he said.
   ``Good education, rehabilitation and job training programs are
not going to fluorish if the bad guys control the streets,'' Bennett
said. ``We need as a matter of national policy to build more
prisons.''
