<FIRST>r w PM-Pierce-HUD     09-21 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pierce-HUD,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce Faces Subpoena to Testify in HUD Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for Samuel R. Pierce Jr. says the
former HUD secretary is deciding whether he will testify as demanded
by a subpoena from a congressional panel.
   ``We are forced to review each and every option,'' including
whether to the refuse to answer questions by invoking his Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination, said attorney Paul L.
Perito.
   A House Government Operations subcommittee voted unanimously
Wednesday to subpoena Pierce to testify about alleged
influence-peddling and mismanagement at the Housing and Urban
Development Department he once headed.
   Pierce was ordered to appear on three separate occasions _ the
first before the employment and housing subcommittee. He faces
contempt of Congress proceedings if he does not appear.
   Pierce provoked anger among the panel members when he demanded a
third delay on the eve of his scheduled voluntary testimony last
Friday.
   ``I think the subcommittee had no option,'' said subcommittee
Chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif. ``The subcommittee had an agreement
with Mr. Pierce ... That agreement was broken unilaterally by Mr.
Pierce.''
   Perito, said Pierce _ who appeared voluntarily before the panel
in May _ was willing to testify but needed another two weeks' time
for preparation.
   In a letter to the panel received before the vote, he said: ``We
believe the subcommittee's vindictive and punitive actions in
denying Mr. Pierce adequate time to obtain and review pertinent
documents and in insisting on use of subpoenas are taken in
retaliation against Mr. Pierce's exercise of his constitutional
right.''
   Republicans and Democrats alike rejected that claim, saying
Pierce had months of time for preparation _ even though Pierce said
he only hired a lawyer this month.
   ``Rather than coming forth and clearing the record ... he is
toying with the subcommittee in order to evade or avoid his
responsibility,'' said Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y.
   Congressional staff attorneys said refusal by a former Cabinet
official to testify could appear to invite efforts to appoint a
special prosecutor under the law providing for a court-appointed
independent counsel to handle investigations of current or former
top executive branch officials.
   Already, some House members are calling for a special prosecutor
or suggested one would be needed if the Justice Department does not
clarify whether it is investigating possible criminal violations by
former HUD officials who are principals in the subcommittee's
investigation.
   The subpoenas call for Pierce to appear next Tuesday, followed by
other appearances on Oct. 27 and Nov. 3. Lantos said the dates could
be changed at his discretion, and he raised the possibility that
further testimony by Pierce could be required.
   Lantos said because of Pierce's actions, he no longer felt bound
by their previous agreement to limit the scope of the subcommittee's
questioning to three matters: Pierce's previous voluntary testimony
of May 25; his actions involving a Durham, N.C., housing project;
and the case involving DRG Corp., which conducted mortgage
coinsurance business with HUD and left the government with huge
defaults.
   Since Pierce appeared before the panel in May, subcommittee
members say inconsistencies and contradictions in his testimony have
emerged.
</TEXT>
