<DOCNO> AP890921-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0548EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Relief     09-21 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Relief,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Priests to Bankers, New Yorkers Aid Hugo Victims in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's Puerto Rican community, which is
larger than San Juan's, is reaching out to its hurricane-shattered
homeland with medicine, supplies and money.
   Hurricane Hugo caused hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
destruction and damaged the homes of 50,000 people when it swept
through the island Sunday, according to Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon
of Puerto Rico.
   In New York _ home to about 1.5 million people of Puerto Rican
descent _ churches, city officials, pop music stars and others are
collecting money and supplies to send. About 1.1 million of the
island's 3.7 million residents live in the capital of San Juan.
   ``My office has been inundated by the calls and visits. People
just want to help,'' Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer said
Wednesday.
   Ferrer had tried in vain to reach his grandmother, aunts and
uncles in Puerto Rico after the storm. They finally called Wednesday.
   ``All is well,'' Ferrer said. ``But now there are a lot of other
aunts and uncles who need some help.''
   The Department of Puerto Rican Community Affairs, a Manhattan
office of the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, is coordinating the
relief effort.
   The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York asked its churches to
collect money this weekend for relief work throughout the Caribbean.
The hurricane struck the U.S. Virgin Islands, Montserrat, Guadeloupe
and Antigua as well as Puerto Rico.
   Branches of Banco Popular de Puerto Rico, Banco de Ponce and
Manufacturers Hanover Trust are accepting donations for disaster aid
in Puerto Rico. Banco Popular also will do the accounting for a
telethon to be broadcast Sunday over two local Spanish-language
television channels.
   Drummer Tito Puente and singers Lisa Lisa and Iris Chacon are
scheduled to perform at a benefit concert at Nassau Coliseum in the
New York City suburb of Uniondale Sunday to raise $250,000 for the
hurricane victims.
   St. Barnabas Hospital in the Bronx plans to send two doctors and
three nurses to Puerto Rico to provide medical services and seek out
relatives of staff members. Hospital employees already have raised
$20,000.
   ``We're a community hospital and we have a large Hispanic
population and many of our employees have families there,'' said
Maria Zito, a hospital spokeswoman.
   Parishioners from Our Lady Queen of Angels in Spanish Harlem
started a food drive and took to the streets for donations.
   Rev. Michael Sevigny, the pastor, said many parishioners are
worried about relatives.
   ``Some are still waiting for information,'' Sevigny said.
``People have been gathering in front of the church after liturgies
and talking about what they have learned.''
   The Rev. Nicanor Lana, pastor of Spanish Harlem's Holy Rosary
Church, also has held masses and collected canned food and money.
The cash and goods will go directly to churches run by the
Augustinian Order, which runs Holy Rosary.
   ``We have our own men there,'' Lana said. ``They know much better
the situation there. We are going to deliver them into the right
hands.''
   Ferrer said among the items he was asked to find for the relief
effort are 200 chainsaws.
   ``I don't know where I'm going to find them,'' he said, ``but
I'll try.''
</TEXT>
