<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-21 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Confirms Perkins to be Foreign Service Director General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted early today to confirm
President Bush's nomination of Ambassador Edward J. Perkins to be
director general of the Foreign Service.
   Perkins, 61, who has served as U.S. ambassador to South Africa
since 1986, will be the first black Foreign Service officer to hold
the director general's post, one of the State Department's most
prestigious diplomatic assignments.
   He previously served as U.S. ambassador to Liberia.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Report Says Fighter Defects Undermine Combat Readiness</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Test equipment the Air Force uses to determine
the effectiveness of radar-warning receivers and other electronics
on tactical fighters has been faulty and unreliable, a new report
says.
   The General Accounting Office, an investigative arm of Congress,
said Wednesday that the problems with the test equipment undermine
the combat readiness of the aircraft and the ability of the planes
to fly combat missions.
   The aircraft are equipped with electronic warfare systems
consisting of a radar-warning receiver that alerts the pilot when
his airplane is being tracked by enemy radar and a jammer that
transmits signals to deceive enemy radar.
   The GAO study found that at five tactical units in the United
States, Europe and Asia, almost half of about 455 jammers the Air
Force deemed ready for combat had undetected defects.
   ``The cost for this kind of carelessness can be staggering,''
said Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., the chairman of the House
Government Operations subcommittee on legislation and national
security, which had requested the GAO report. ``And the risk it
poses to our national security and to the lives of our pilots is
simply unacceptable.''
   The study attributed the problems to the Air Force's acquisition
process. In one instance, the Air Force purchased 72 test sets at a
cost of $272 million before testing them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Panel Says Tests Of Genetically-Modified Plants, Microbes Safe</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Field testing of genetically modified plants
and microorganisms ``will not pose any hazard'' to the environment
if done carefully under existing laws, says a National Academy of
Sciences panel.
   Genetically engineered plants and microbes are ``not
intrinsically dangerous,'' the panel concluded in a study released
Wednesday. But the experts said field tests should be allowed only
after evaluating the effect on the environment if the modified
organism were to ``escape'' from the test area.
   ``We feel fairly confident that if this thing is done right, it
will not pose any hazard,'' said Robert H. Burris, an emeritus
professor of biochemistry from the University of Wisconsin. ``We
hope that this will be reassuring to the public.''
   Jeremy Rifkin of the Foundation on Economic Trends, a longtime
opponent of field testing of genetically-altered organisms, called
the report ``irresponsible public policy.'' He said science has no
way to evaluate the risks of releasing such organisms into the
environment.
   Burris, who was chairman of the academy's committee on evaluation
of introduction of gene-modified microorganisms and plants, that
some 80 modified plants and microbes have been tested in the
environment and ``we haven't had any accidents as yet.''
</TEXT>
