<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms Along Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms fell on the Atlantic coast today as
Hurricane Hugo moved slowly toward the U.S. mainland.
   A cold front extending from Minnesota into Wyoming and Colorado
produced some rain and wind in the high plains.
   Hugo, whose winds were clocked at 105 mph, was well offshore
early today. But its leading edge brought rain from North Carolina
to Florida.
   On Wednesday, showers and thunderstorms struck along the Atlantic
coast from South Carolina to New England. More than 1{ inches of
rain fell in New York city and similar amounts were reported in
Newark, N.J., and near Philadelphia.
   Elsewhere, flooding continued Wednesday along the Wabash and
White rivers in Indiana, with rivers up to 6 feet above flood stage.
   A cold front in the Plains produced scattered rain, and 1 to 4
inches of snow was expected to fall overnight in the Wind River
Mountains of Wyoming.
   The front brought winds up to 64 mph Wednesday at Fort Morgan,
Colo., where the temperature plunged from the 80s to the mid-50s in
just an hour.
   Temperatures Wednesday reached into the 80s across the southern
and central Plains, the 90s in south-central Texas and the 80s and
90s across Florida and the desert Southwest. Clouds and rain kept
temperatures in the 60s in the upper Mississippi valley and in the
northern Atlantic states.
