<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-21 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against the Japanese yen
today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose.
   The dollar closed at 145.00 yen, down 1.25 yen from Wednesday's
146.25-yen finish. It opened at 144.90 yen and ranged between 144.82
yen and 145.25 yen.
   It had gained 0.52 yen on Wednesday but opened sharply lower in
Tokyo today after declining overnight on overseas markets on
speculation that West Germany's central bank might raise interest
rates.
   As the Tokyo market awaited the Bundesbank's scheduled meeting
later today, exchange dealings were slow, said Toru Kanai, a foreign
exchange analyst with New Japan Securities Co.
   Spot volume was estimated at $5.6 billion.
   ``Participants slowed their dollar buying only temporarily prior
to the West German Bundesbank meeting and the G-7,'' Kanai said,
referring to the meeting of the Group of Seven industrialized
nations. ``After all, the dollar will remain strong.''
   At the G-7 meeting, market players are watching for any measures
to curb the dollar's strength.
   The weekend meeting in Washington will bring together the finance
ministers of Japan, the United States, West Germany, Britain, Italy,
France and Canada.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 274.44
points today, or 0.80 percent, closing at 34,745.02. It had lost
0.49 points the previous day.
   The index began rising soon after the market opened as investors
were reassured by the yen's overnight jump against the dollar,
dealers said.
   It rose further in the afternoon on investment trusts' buying of
small amounts of a wide variety of issues, but institutional
investors remained reluctant to make major moves ahead of the
international monetary talks, said a dealer with a major securities
firm in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Masahiro Umemori, a stock analyst with Nomura Securities, said,
``Participants were buying supermarket issues considering that
reorganization and easing regulations on large-scale retail stores
could be positive steps to improve U.S.-Japan structural problems.''
   Trading was thin, with first-section volume estimated at 650
million shares, up from 600 million Wednesday. Among gainers were
supermarket, department store, bank and shipbuilding shares.
