<SECOND>PM-Stayner Death,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Remembers Trauma of Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN BARRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MERCED, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 people overflowed a church
for the funeral of former child abduction victim Steven Stayner,
killed in a motorcycle crash four months after a TV movie depicted
his seven-year ordeal.
   His abduction by a convicted child molester left Stayner scarred,
family and friends said at Wednesday's service.
   ``Steven had a hard time getting his feet back on the ground,
too, because of all the experiences he had. And even when everything
was going well, something would kick him back,'' said Bishop Steve
Tucker, Stayner's minister. ``His dad says, though, that Steven did
the best that he could.''
   Stayner, 24, was killed Saturday when he hit a car that pulled in
front of his motorcycle.
   The motorist, Antonio Loera, 28, fled, but surrendered at the
Mexican border Tuesday night, authorities said. He was arraigned
Wednesday on charges of felony hit-and-run driving and manslaughter.
   Stayner was snatched at age 7 from a Merced street in 1972 by
Kenneth Parnell, 53, and held with lies that his family couldn't
care for him anymore. He resurfaced in March 1980 when he took
another kidnap victim, Timmy White, then 5, to the Ukiah police
station 200 miles north of Stayner's hometown.
   ``When he came home, it was like we had known him all of our
lives, just as though he had never gone. He brought our
broken-hearted family together,'' Stayner's sister, Jody, told
mourners who filled a small Mormon church and adjoining gymnasium.
   But life never again was entirely normal for young Stayner or his
family because of the publicity his case attracted.
   ``When Steven returned after seven years, he was not just mom and
pop's son,'' Tucker said. ``They had to share him with the rest of
the nation. This was hard for them.''
   Stayner's story was depicted in May in an NBC-TV movie, ``I Know
My First Name is Steven.'' But Tucker said the character portrayed
``wasn't the real Steven Stayner. He wasn't rude to his parents. He
was a loving son.''
   Stayner finished high school, married in 1985 and had two
children, now ages 3 and 2.
   Parnell, who had been convicted of child molestation before
Steven's abduction, spent five years in prison for the two
kidnappings before he was released on parole in 1985. He faced no
sex charges in either case, though Steven testified during an 18-day
trial that he was regularly sexually abused.
