<HEAD>Neighborhood Rejoices in Conviction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Night Stalker, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST LOS ANGELES, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people who wrestled convicted
``Night Stalker'' killer Richard Ramirez to the ground and held him
for police expressed gratitude at his conviction as they relived
that fateful day.
   ``I feel really good, like it is all over now,'' said Faustino
Pinon, one of those who struggled with Ramirez when the killer tried
to steal his daughter's car on Aug. 31, 1985.
   A jury Wednesday convicted Ramirez of 13 murders and 30 felonies.
Jurors also found circumstances that made Ramirez eligible for the
death penalty. A sentencing hearing is pending.
   ``The verdict brought back a lot of memories of that day and I'm
glad it's ended,'' said Pinon, who watched the news of the
conviction on the television in his small wood and stucco home.
   Daughter Gloria watched the news at work, on a small television
set she hid under her desk. ``I just yelled out, `yeah!' when I
heard what's going to happen to him. I think he got what he had
coming,'' she said.
   One neighborhood resident who wasn't watching the television news
was Jose Burgoin, 59, who captured Ramirez with the help of his
sons, Julio, 26, and Jaime, 22.
   He learned of the convictions from a daughter, who called from
work, and several neighbors who stopped by to chat on his wooden
porch.
   ``Well, I knew he was guilty and that he had done many bad
things, and if the court found him guilty, well, that's the way it
is,'' said Burgoin. ``Now he'll have to pay the price.''
   The day of his arrest, Ramirez had been spotted in several nearby
places by people who had recognized his picture from news reports.
   Witnesses called police and officers were sent to the East Los
Angeles areas where he had been sighted.
   On Hubbard Street, Ramirez struggled with Pinon for the Mustang
before giving up and trying to take another car, occupied by Angie
de la Torre.
   Burgoin, who said he was mowing his lawn at the time, saw Mrs. De
la Torre struggling with Ramirez and ran to help. He pulled Ramirez
from the car and he and his sons held him until sheriff's deputies
arrived minutes later.
   Burgoin said he learned after Ramirez' arrest that he had been
sought for a string of slayings that had terrorized California
during the summer of 1985.
   ``It's me! It's me! It's me! I'm lucky the cops caught me,''
Ramirez reportedly shouted in Spanish as he was arrested.
   Word of the arrest spread quickly, and by the time Ramirez
arrived at the police station for questioning, 500 people had
gathered outside shouting, ``Kill him! Kill him!''
</TEXT>
