<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike     09-21 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW Planning Encore to Plant Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking miners ended a four-day occupation of
a coal processing plant hours after a court-imposed deadline, but
the union said it would use the tactic again to increase pressure on
Pittston Coal Group Inc.
   ``We're going to hurt this company economically,'' Cecil Roberts,
vice president of the United Mine Workers, said after leading the
occupying strikers to a rally outside the plant gates Wednesday
night.
   ``We're going to cut off their production until they wake up and
we're going to do it peacefully,'' he said, adding that the union
could attempt to occupy another Pittston plant as early as next week.
   Ninety-five of Pittston's striking miners along with three union
officials and a religious leader voluntarily ended their occupation
of the seven-story building after ignoring a federal judge's
deadline for a little more than two hours.
   ``We got a lot of miles per gallon out of this effort and we've
got a lot more gas in the tank,'' said Eddie Burke, the union's
southeast regional coordinator and one of those who occupied the
plant.
   A human barricade of 3,000 supporters outside the plant protected
the occupying team. The supporters joined miners and other union
members from throughout Appalachia and the Midwest at a rally in
front of the plant as darkness fell.
   Some state troopers drove off at dusk and law enforcement
authorities let the deadline pass without trying to get inside the
plant.
   The troopers withdrew a short distance down the road ``to let
them have the rally without any interference,'' said Sgt. Mike
Frank, a state police spokesman. He said no specific time had been
set for removing the occupiers.
   Roberts said the union proved its strength without forcing a
confrontation.
   ``We stood the state on its head,'' he said. ``We shocked
Pittston and totally cut off their production at their most
productive processing plant for four days and we did that
non-violently. Everybody stood in the road and locked arms in
solidarity and nobody could do anything with that power.''
   Earlier, U.S. District Judge Glen Williams said the miners would
face no penalties if they left the plant before the deadline.
Otherwise, he said they would lose their $200 a week in UMW strike
benefits and face contempt charges while the union would be fined
$600,000 for each day of the occupation.
   It wasn't clear if they would face penalties for not leaving by
the deadline.
   The unarmed demonstrators stormed the plant Sunday when only a
dozen security officers were on the grounds.
   They barricaded themselves inside the control room and shut down
production at the plant, where coal is cleaned, sorted and shipped.
Replacement workers had been operating the plant since the strike
began in April, although production has been about half of normal.
   Union leaders said they wanted to make a dramatic public
statement about what they consider unfair treatment by the company,
which they contend is trying to break the union.
   Massive fines have taken away all other avenues of peaceful
protest, such as sit-down demonstrations and mass picketing, they
said.
   Pittston Coal President Michael Odom called the demonstrators
terrorists and said Wednesday, ``We will seek full prosecution under
the law.''
   Pittston's 1,695 UMW employees from Virginia, West Virginia and
Kentucky have been on strike over wages and working conditions.
Union members at other coal companies staged wildcat strikes in June
and July.
   Although Williams offered the demonstrators and the union
amnesty, UMW attorney Mike Passino said they still could face state
penalties.
   A state judge already has fined the union nearly $17 million
based on charges of illegal strike activities brought by the company.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said his Senate Labor
Committee was launching an investigation of the labor dispute. He
did not give a timetable.
</TEXT>
