<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     09-21 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Parliament Member Assassinated in West Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Sunni Moslem member of
Parliament and his driver in Syrian-controlled west Beirut today,
police said.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified in line with
regulations, said Nazim Kadri, 74, ``died instantly from bullet
wounds in the head and chest.''
   No group claimed responsibility for the assassination of Kadri,
the third Sunni public figure slain in 27 months.
   The police spokesman said three men got out of a red
Mercedes-Benz and fired AK-47 automatic rifles at Kadri's brown
Mercedes sedan this morning a few yards from the nine-story
apartment building where the lawmaker lived.
   Kadri's police driver, Sgt. Sami Suleiman, also was killed in the
attack and a bystander, Samir Itani, was slightly wounded in the
left arm, the spokesman said.
   ``Immediately after emptying about two clips of 30 bullets each
into Kadri's car, the gunmen jumped into their Mercedes and sped
away while shooting in the air,'' the police spokesman said.
   He said a police car rushed Kadri and Suleiman to the American
University Hospital but they were already dead.
   Witnesses said Kadri was gunned down shortly after having a
haircut at a barber's shop across the street from his home.
   One witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Kadri's car
was intercepted by the gunmen minutes after he left the barber's
shop.
   Syrian soldiers rushed to the area, sealed off the murder scene
and took several witnesses for questioning, ``including the
barber,'' the witness added.
   Kadri, survived by a wife and seven daughters, represented the
central Bekaa Valley in Lebanon's one-chamber parliament since 1972.
   Since Lebanon's civil war began 14 years ago, 26 seats of the
99-member Parliament have been left vacant by deaths, many by
natural causes.
   The war has prevented parliamentary elections but the remaining
members periodically have voted for renewal of its four-year mandate
since 1976, a year after the war began.
   The other prominent Sunni Moslems killed in the past 27 months
were Grand Mufti Sheik Hassan Khalid and Prime Minister Rashid
Karami.
   Khalid was killed in a car bomb explosion in west Beirut May 16,
and Karami died in a bomb blast aboard an army helicopter that was
flying him from northern Lebanon to Beirut June 1, 1987.
   The economically powerful Sunni community is not involved in the
current six-month confrontation pitting the predominantly Christian
troops of Gen. Michel Aoun against Syrian and allied forces.
   Since the fighting began March 8, 926 people have been killed and
2,725 wounded, by police count.
</TEXT>
