<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0628EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     09-21 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Nurse's Aide Found Guilty of Killing Five Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury found a former nursing home
aide guilty of killing five incapacitated patients in a pact with a
lesbian lover, and families of the victims celebrated the verdict
outside the court.
   ``My mother can finally rest in peace,'' said Jan Hunderman,
daughter of victim Marguarite Chambers. ``The scars will always be
there, but it helps knowing the truth.''
   A jury deliberated about five hours Wednesday before finding
Gwendolyn Graham guilty on five counts of first-degree murder and
one count of conspiracy to commit first-degree murder in the deaths
at Alpine Manor Nursing Home in Walker.
   Graham, 26, looked down and showed no emotion as the verdicts
were read.
   She faces a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment without
parole. No sentencing date was set.
   Linda Engman, daughter of victim Mae Mason, said she was thrilled
with the verdict. ``I didn't have any doubts at all,'' she said. ``I
wish we had the death penalty.''
   With a lack of hard evidence, the case rested largely on the
testimony of Catherine Wood, Graham's accomplice and former lover.
   Wood, who already has pleaded guilty to second-degree murder,
testified that Graham smothered patients with washcloths because it
``relieved tension.''
   Wood, also a nurse's aide at Alpine Manor, said the two had
formed a love pact, each agreeing to kill patients so they would be
bound to one another for life.
   The victims were Chambers, 60; Mason, 79; Belle Burkhard, 74;
Edith Cook, 97; and Myrtle Luce, 95. The women, all severely
incapacitated and many suffering from Alzheimer's disease, were
killed between January and April 1987.
   Defense attorney James Piazza said he planned to ask the judge to
set aside the verdict.
   ``I'm surprised and disappointed,'' Piazza said. ``There was no
physical evidence whatsoever.''
   Graham, testifying Tuesday, denied that any murders had occurred
at the home and said the murder plot was nothing more than a joke
made up by Wood that had gotten out of hand.
   Graham said a jealous Wood went to police with the story after
Graham left her for another lover and moved to her hometown of
Tyler, Texas.
   Her denials contradicted testimony of several former co-workers
and friends who said she admitted suffocating patients at Alpine
Manor.
   Graham's former lover, Heather Baragar, testified that Graham
often confessed to her and would ``joke around about it.''
   Another woman testified Graham and Wood had shown her
``souvenirs,'' such as an anklet and a balloon, they said they had
taken from their victims.
   Wood testified that she stood watch while Graham suffocated one
patient, but lacked the nerve to kill any of the patients herself.
   The deaths had been ruled natural, and no autopsies were
performed. Police began investigating last October after Wood's
ex-husband told them she had confessed her part in the murder plot.
   Autopsies were performed on the only two bodies that were not
cremated, but no definitive evidence of suffocation was found.
   ``Even though we still find it difficult to believe that any of
this actually happened ... we will continue to place our trust in
our system of justice,'' said a statement from the nursing home.
   In his closing arguments, Assistant Kent County Prosecutor David
Schieber speculated that Graham herself may not know why she killed
the women.
   ``It was murder for its own pleasure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
