<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-21 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against all major currencies in
nervous European trading early today amid signs West Germany will
not raise interest rates before a weekend meeting of the world's
leading industrialized nations.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow
range before today's scheduled meeting of the Bundesbank Central
Bank Council.
   Many market players expected the West German central bank to take
no immediate action on interest rates, despite signs of rising
inflation, before monetary talks open Saturday in Washington among
the Group of Seven industrialized nations.
   The absence of Bundesbank President Karl Otto Poehl from the
meeting also reduced the chances of a rate hike, dealers said.
   The G-7 nations are the United States, Japan, West Germany,
France, Britain, Italy and Canada.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell to a closing 145.00 Japanese yen from 146.25 yen at
Wednesday's close. Later, in London, it edged back up to 145.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.9442 West German marks, up from 1.9400
   _1.6835 Swiss francs, up from 1.6800
   _6.5717 French francs, up from 6.5585
   _2.1903 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1890
   _1,402.00 Italian lire, up from 1,399.50
   _1.1825 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1824
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.5795 from $1.5820 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $363.65 a troy ounce, up
from $363.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $362.95.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.35, down from $363.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.69 to a closing bid of
$364.11.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.13 troy ounce,
up from $5.09 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
