<FIRST>r a PM-NYCSchoolChancellor     09-21 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC School Chancellor,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Superintendent to Head New York's Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph A. Fernandez, who grew up in a Harlem
housing project and dropped out of a New York high school, never
dreamed he would lead the nation's largest public school system.
   Fernandez, currently the Miami school superintendent, said the
New York City job was the farthest thing from his mind when he was
growing up in ``rough areas'' on Manhattan's west side.
   ``I didn't think I'd leave New York alive, much less come back to
lead the school system,'' he said at a news conference in Miami.
   On Wednesday, the New York Board of Education voted unanimously
to approve Fernandez as the next chancellor of the New York City
public schools.
   ``He will stand as a splendid role model,'' board President
Robert Wagner Jr. said of 53-year-old Fernandez.
   Wagner praised Fernandez for lowering the dropout rate in
Miami-Dade County schools while increasing parent and student
involvement in individual schools.
   Fernandez will face a daunting list of problems in New York,
including overcrowded schools, a high dropout rate and a
decentralized system which has been stung by patronage and
corruption scandals.
   ``I like a challenge,'' said Fernandez. ``If you put
well-intentioned people together, people with their hearts in the
right place, I think they can do something for the kids.''
   Wagner said Fernandez would start in January or February and
would be paid $195,000 a year under an 18-month contract. The salary
is $40,000 more than Fernandez receives in Miami and $45,000 more
than the previous chancellor, the late Richard Green, was paid.
   The United Federation of Teachers, which represents 102,000
teachers, assistants, counselors, psychologists and secretaries in
the city's schools, praised Fernandez for emphasizing ``school-based
management and shared decision making.''
   Wagner said that before Fernandez took over Miami's schools,
there were two applicants for each teaching vacancy. Now there are
six.
   Fernandez was one of three finalists in the search that began
after Green died of an asthma attack in May.
   Robert R. ``Bud'' Spillane, superintendent of schools in Fairfax
County, Va., was interviewed by the board Tuesday and Matthew W.
Prophet, school superintendent of Portland, Ore., withdrew from
consideration.
   In 1987, during the search that was to lead to Green's
appointment, the board had asked Fernandez to apply for the job. But
Fernandez said the timing was wrong because he had just been named
to head the Miami system, the nation's fourth biggest.
   Asked why he said yes this time, Fernandez said, ``Because it is
the number one system in the country. ... Maybe we can turn some of
the larger school systems in the country around by replicating what
we've done in Miami.''
   Eighty percent of the 940,000 children in New York's public
schools are minorities. Green was the first black chancellor. His
two immediate predecessors had been Hispanic. Fernandez is of Puerto
Rican heritage.
   While a student at the old High School of Commerce in Manhattan,
Fernandez dropped out and joined the Air Force. He received a high
school equivalency diploma while in the service and later attended
Columbia University.
   He joined the Miami school system as a math teacher in 1962 and
within 10 years became the city's first Hispanic principal.
   He and his wife, Lily, have four grown children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
