<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0703EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChinaCourses     09-21 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China Courses,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Professors Incorporate Events of Tiananmen Square into Courses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many American professors are including
the recent democracy protests in China and subsequent army crackdown
in their courses, and they're finding that the Beijing massacre has
boosted student interest in those courses sharply.
   Some professors already have begun to teach the lessons of
Tiananmen Square this fall while others plan to wait until spring to
review the already rich literature spawned by the protests.
   ``Five or six years after our students graduate, many of them are
in positions to make a difference,'' said Andrew Walder, a professor
of sociology at Harvard University. Walder usually teaches a
graduate seminar focusing on post-1949 events in China but plans
this year to examine the years just since 1979.
   Gordon Bennett, a professor of government at the University of
Texas, Austin, said the demonstrations for democracy that occupied
Beijing's Tiananmen Square until the army crackdown in early June
will form the ``centerpiece'' of a survey of Chinese politics he
plans to teach next spring.
   ``It relates to every thesis of political change in China,''
Bennett said, ``That is, whether Chinese authoritarianism was
capable of significant economic reform while suppressing political
change or alternatively, whether the decade of economic reform in
China was forced.''
   Roderick MacFarquhar, professor of government at Harvard, plans
to teach a seminar in Chinese politics to juniors this semester and
said that the June protests will take up at least one week of the
course.
   MacFarquhar said he heard from colleagues at Beijing University
when he taught a course on the Cultural Revolution several years ago
that Chinese officials ``wondered why someone at Harvard was giving
a course on it and they weren't. It caused a lively debate.''
   As a result, MacFarquhar said the current regime may well be
apprised of professors at American universities teaching about
Tiananmen Square ``but since they are antagonistic, the reaction at
the official level will be negative.''
   Thomas Gold, associate professor of sociology and vice-chairman
of the Center for Chinese Studies at the University of California,
Berkeley, said the number of students enrolled in his undergraduate
course on contemporary Chinese society has doubled to more than 120
students since he last offered it two years ago.
   But while Gold expects that the student protests will dominate
the course, he said recent events in Beijing reflected a pattern in
Chinese government and society that has existed for centuries.
   ``It's part of a dichotomy, between a tightening up and a
loosening, that goes back thousands of years,'' Gold said.
   ``But Tiananmen Square meant a temporary victory for those people
who want to clamp down. What happened in Tiananmen Square has
happened many times. Part of the tragedy is how little is new,'' he
said.
   Gold said the events in Beijing ``caught the imagination'' of
American students.
   ``It brought out our respect for human rights and democracy that
most people don't think of very often,'' he said. ``When they saw
this in China it was sort of an ennobling experience. People are
trying to understand what happened and once they do it will have a
larger impact.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
