<FIRST>r a PM-Niger-Crash-Americans     09-21 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Niger-Crash-Americans,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Americans Killed Included Peace Corps Volunteer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Niger-Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven Americans aboard the French jetliner that crashed in
northern Africa included the wife of the U.S. ambassador to Chad, a
U.S. Peace Corps volunteer and four oil workers, authorities said.
   ``You always think it's going to happen to someone else,'' said
Janice Huff, whose son, Pat, was among 171 passengers aboard the UTA
DC-10 flight from the Congo to Chad to Paris. All aboard the plane
died.
   A radical Shiite group Wednesday claimed responsibility for the
downing of a jetliner, the airline UTA said. The airline said a bomb
most likely caused the crash of the jetliner, which exploded Tuesday
shortly after taking off from Chad for Paris.
   One passenger was Bonnie Barnes Pugh, who decided to travel ahead
of her husband, Robert L. Pugh, the U.S. ambassador to Chad.
   Mrs. Pugh was to help plan the October wedding of her daughter
Anne Pugh, 26, of suburban Washington, D.C., said Mrs. Pugh's
sister, Sally Johnson.
   ``It's been pretty devastating for all of us,'' said Ms. Johnson,
of Brawley, Calif. ``It's hard, particularly when you think of it as
a bombing.''
   Margaret Schutzius, 23, another American passenger, had completed
a two-year stint with the Peace Corps in Chad and was en route to
Paris to begin two months of travel in Europe, her mother said.
   ``She gave her heart and soul to her job and even recommended
that I join the Peace Corps when I retire,'' said Mary K. Hassett, a
bookstore owner in Fredericksburg, Texas. ``She told me how Jimmy
Carter's mother joined the Corps showing that age was not a factor.''
   Ms. Schutzius taught English to elementary school children and
worked with members of Chad's government to develop an English
curriculum in the country's schools, said Jim Flanigan, a spokesman
for the Peace Corps in Washington.
   ``Even though it was a terrible tragedy, and her life was short,
she stood for a lot while she was with us,'' said Ms. Hassett.
   Exxon Corp. spokeswoman Sara Johnson in New York said two
Americans working in southern Chad for the company's Esso
Exploration &amp; Production Chad Inc. subsidiary also were on the UTA
flight.
   They were petroleum geologist Mark Corder, 35, of Houston, and
senior operation supervisor James Turlington, Sr., 48, of Bellville.
   Miss Johnson said an Esso Resources Canada employee on loan to
Exxon was also on the flight. Russell O. Jordan Jr, 29, a senior
projects engineer, is Canadian, but listed his hometown as Houston,
she said.
   The Tulsa, Okla.-based Parker Drilling Co. said four of its
employees were aboard the French airliner, including two Americans.
They were returning home from a 28-day work rotation.
   Parker Drilling spokesman Tim Colwell said the four men worked at
a rig in southern Chad that Parker owns and operates under a
contract with Exxon.
   He identified the Parker employees as Pat Huff, 38, of Franklin,
Texas; Donald Warner, 25, of Terry, Mont.; David Middleton, 38, of
Rowland Gill, England; and a Bolivian truck driver, whose name was
not released pending notification of relatives.
   A camp medic, Warner had been with the company for a month. Huff
was a rig manager.
   The State Department identified the seventh American as Mihai Ali
Manestianu, but no further information was immediately available.
</TEXT>
