<FIRST>r i PM-Stars-and-Stripes 1stLd-Writethru a0535 09-21 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stars-and-Stripes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0535,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Head Denies Censorship at Pacific Stars and Stripes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECT style on Stars and Stripes, which does not have an ampersand.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military head of the Pacific edition of Stars
and Stripes today rejected allegations of censorship and personnel
abuse under his editorship of the newspaper for U.S. armed forces in
the Far East.
   ``The paper is not censored,'' said Air Force Col. Edwin
Montgomery. ``I've never had anyone, no flag officer or bureaucrat,
tell me what stories to write or how they are to run.
   ``I've been here three years and no one has told me anything like
that.''
   But a civilian journalist at the newspaper, Dewey Brackett, said
he was preparing a list of serious problems to be given to the
paper's management and to ombusdman Philip M. Foisie, who is to
arrive Sunday.
   The Pentagon appointed Foisie ombudsman in June for the European
and Far East editions of Stars and Stripes, with authority to
monitor their performance and argue with military brass over
decisions about news coverage.
   He is a former editor with The Washington Post and a former
executive editor of the Paris-based International Herald Tribune.
   ``The issue is not simply censorship. It is also abuse of
personnel and editorial mismanagement,'' Brackett said in a
telephone interview.
   Brackett, who testified before Congress last winter about
conditions at the newspaper, declined to give details before the
list is submitted.
   Montgomery, who also testified before Congress on the dispute,
said in a telephone interview that he felt Foisie also will
represent him.
   ``Mr. Foisie will have the opportunity to speak with whomever he
wishes, and I'm confident he will come to the conclusion we're not
censoring the paper,'' he said.
   The editorial staff consists of 17 U.S. civilians and 21 military
people, Montgomery said.
   Montgomery disputed Brackett's claim that Brackett had been
disciplined for testifying to Congress.
   Brackett has been only temporarily relieved as Pacific editor and
assigned to be a supervising editor, Montgomery said, ``while we can
analyze the latest series of allegations.''
   He said it was normal for civilian employees of the government to
be relieved of normal duties during an investigation.
   Brackett said, however, ``I feel my relief is harassment and
definitely retribution for having testified to Congress.''
   Brackett, 49, said he was a retired U.S. Air Force officer with
about 20 years experience in journalism and in the Far East.
   There have been a series of disputes involving Stars and Stripes
in recent years and they predate the arrival of Montgomery, who
previously was a staff officer in Washington.
   Reporters who have worked for Star and Stripes say their
reporting of the news sometimes suffers because military commanders
worry about the sensitivities of host countries.
   The two editions of the paper, published in Japan and West
Germany, are edited separately and are supposed to be ``hometown
newspapers'' for U.S. service personnel.
   The Pentagon describes them as ``authorized, but unofficial
publications'' and their charter says they are to provide ``a free
flow of news and information ... without censorship or news
management.''
   But last year an investigation by the General Accounting Office,
an arm of the U.S. Congress, found evidence of censorship and
improper managament. The Society of Professional Journalists, Sigma
Delta Chi, assisted in that investigation.
   Democratic Reps. Barbara Boxer of California and Earl Hutto of
Florida have written to Adm. Huntington Hardisty, commander of U.S.
forces in the Pacific, asking him to look into continued allegations.
   ``What we have here is harassment of whistle-blowers and
censorship,'' Ms. Boxer said in an interview in Washington. ``It's
bad enough to censor the news. Our men and women in uniform deserve
the news as all of us get it, as harsh as it is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
