<FIRST>u a PM-USAirCrash-Survivors 2ndLd-Writethru a0487 09-21 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir Crash-Survivors, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0487,a0489,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Take Rescue Slide, Land in Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Flight 5050...' to UPDATE with passenger number
revised to 63, sted 61, all accounted for.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-USAir Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers aboard a USAir jet that crashed into
the East River said they were surprised when they landed in the
water after sliding down chutes from the plane, and clung to
driftwood until being rescued.
   ``Everyone was saying, `Get out! Get out! Get out!' So we started
helping each other get out,'' said Larry Martin, a social worker
from Brooklyn who was on the Boeing 737 with his wife, Valerie.
   ``They told us to get of the plane and go out the door. I thought
we were going to go down the slide and onto the runway. When we got
off the slide we were in the water.''
   Flight 5050, from LaGuardia Airport to Charlotte, N.C., was
carrying 63 people when it skidded off a runway into the East River,
killing two people, the airline said.
   ``It wasn't a violent crash,'' said Frank O'Brien, 25, of
Manhattan. ``We went out the emergency exit. There was some
driftwood'' in the water that several people clung to.
   He said police came by in a boat and picked them up. ``We were
just hanging on to each other. We decided the only thing to do was
to be calm.''
   David Hawthorne, a CBS News producer who was on the flight, said
via a cellular telephone that the engines apparently were cut
halfway down the runway and went into reverse thrust.
   ``At that time no one thought there was going to be real
trouble,'' he said.
   ``The pilot seemed to be accelerating but didn't have enough
power to get the plane up,'' Martin said as he and his wife huddled
in blankets inside an airport terminal.
   ``And it seemed something happened and he put on the brakes,'' he
said. ``The plane took a dip and the next thing I knew all hell
broke loose.''
   Hawthorne said he managed to get out onto a wing, where he waited
with several other people to be rescued.
   ``A lot of women and children were screaming that they couldn't
swim, they couldn't swim,'' he said.
   ``Most people were pretty calm after we got out onto the wing of
the plane,'' he said. ``And they waited for boats to come pick us up
and the rescuers also arrived and I have to say they did a pretty
good job of keeping everybody calm and getting them safely off.''
   Some people were trapped in the tail section of the plane, he
said, and rescuers and crewmembers tried to keep them calm.
   Jerry Murtha, a fire department scuba diver, said it took him
about 45 minutes using a metal cutter to rescue one woman trapped in
the tail section between collapsed seats, behind a woman who had
died.
   ``Water started coming into the tail section,'' he said. ``When
we started it was at 6 inches and when we finished there was 3 feet.
And it (the fuselage) was rocking.''
   He said firefighters placed the unidentified woman, who was not
seriously injured, into a basket and took her to a boat.
   ``She hugged us, kissed us. She wanted to know our names. She
thanked us a million times,'' Murtha said.
   Martin said a stranger helped him after they hit the water.
   ``I started to panic,'' he said. ``There was a guy. ... He
grabbed me, he maneuvered me over to the driftwood. If it wasn't
there I don't know what would have happened.''
</TEXT>
