<FIRST>r i PM-Duarte     09-21 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duarte,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Salvadoran Leader Reported Near Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jose Napoleon
Duarte is losing his battle with liver cancer and could be near
death, his doctors say.
   ``I thought he was going to die last night (Tuesday). But we were
able to stabilize him, and I don't think he'll die within the next
24 hours,'' said Dr. Jose Luis Sacasaid on Wednesday.
   Duarte was in ``serious but stable'' condition Wednesday, the
doctor said, but ``Even so, he probably will not recover from this
crisis.''
   Duarte, 63, led this country for five years until he stepped down
June 1 and was Washington's staunchest ally in the Western
Hemisphere.
   He handed power to elected successor Alfredo Cristiani, of the
rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance.
   The cancer was diagnosed in June 1988 in Washington's Walter Reed
Army Medical Center. Two-thirds of his stomach was removed and
chemotherapy was applied to help slow the disease's advance.
   However, last month the treatment was stopped because Duarte was
judged too weak to survive its debilitating side-effects.
   He was bedridden Wednesday at his home in the fashionable San
Benito neighborhood. A source close to the family said he did not
want to be taken to the hospital.
   Saca said the former president has low blood pressure and
difficulty breathing.
