<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-ColombianCoffee     09-21 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Colombian Coffee,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Rejects Coffee Quota Appeal From Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is refusing a request by
Colombian President Virgilio Barco to reinstate a one-year Colombian
coffee export that has been beneficial to Colombian farmers, the
White House says.
   Colombia's coffee earnings have slumped at the same time that the
Bush administration is seeking Barco's help in cracking down on
cocaine exports.
   Colombian officials have suggested they will have an even harder
time persuading hard-pressed Colombia farmers to grow coffee instead
of coca if coffee export prices continue to slip.
   Colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74-nation
International Coffee Agreement (ICA) _ to which both the United
States and Colombia belonged _ collapsed in July after the United
States pulled out in a dispute over prices with coffee-producing
nations.
   The Agreement set quotas for member nations' exports aimed at
supporting prices of beans at $1.20 per pound or more. Some Central
American and others, supported by the United States, wanted larger
quotas.
   After suspension of the quotas in early July, prices fell quickly
to around 85 cents per pound, give or take a few pennies. Colombia
has said this will cost $500 million a year in export revenue.
   Barco, whose nation relies on coffee as a major source of export
earnings, had appealed to Bush to reconsider the coffee decision and
to support reinstating the quotas for at least one year.
   Bush, in a letter to Barco, said the United States was ready to
negotiate for a new quota system but was unwilling to adhere to the
now-defunct agreement, presidential press secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said Wednesday.
   Fitzwater said that Bush's letter to Barco was one ``expressing
appreciation of the importance of coffee to the economies of
Colombia and other developing countries.''
   The letter, Fitzwater continued, ``expressed his (Bush's)
disappointment that the members of the ICA were unable to settle ...
two fundamental problems.''
   The United States wanted an increase in export quotas for
higher-quality coffees enjoyed by American consumers, and tough
penalties against countries secretly selling coffee surpluses to
Eastern Bloc nations at prices below those charged the United States.
   ``President Bush expresses his confidence that a lasting solution
which is acceptable to other major members and respects market
trends can be found,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
