<FIRST>r i PM-NaziInvestigation     09-21 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nazi Investigation,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>German Prosecutor to Check British Documents on Former Nazi General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUEBECK, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor's office said today
it is sending a lawyer to Britain next week to study evidence
against a former Nazi SS general suspected in the deaths of 85
British war prisoners in 1940.
   The Luebeck prosecutor's office opened a new investigation of
ex-Gen. Wilhelm Mohnke, 78, in June 1988 after the British Defense
Ministry said it had discovered more survivors of the massacre.
   ``One of our prosecutor's will be in London early next week to
evaluate documents held there as part of the on-going Mohnke
investigation,'' prosecutor's spokesman Joachim Boettcher said in a
telephone interview. He identified the prosecutor being sent as
Hartwig Nigendank.
   Boettcher said Mohnke remains free in West Germany pending
results of the investigation.
   Mohnke allegedly gave orders in 1940 for 85 unarmed British
prisoners being held in a barn to be shot by SS troops at Wormhoudt,
near Dunkirk in France. A similar investigation of Mohnke was
dropped in 1973 for lack of evidence.
   Earlier probes of Mohnke's alleged involvement in the 1944
execution of 75 unarmed U.S. prisoners of war at Malmedy, in the
French Ardennes, and Canadians in Normandy the same year, also were
dropped for lack of evidence.
   Mohnke, a retired businessman who lives in the town of Stemwarde,
near Hamburg, repeatedly has denied any connection with the
massacres.
</TEXT>
