<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru   09-21 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0567,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Bombs Explode, Damaging Political Offices and a Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with party publishing names of
officials denied U.S. visas. Pickup 14th pvs, `As part...' Minor editing
thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Barrio Escobar, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten bombs exploded early today in Bogota,
causing heavy damage to nine offices of Colombia's main political
parties and to one bank, police said. At least two people were
reported injured.
   Bombings have occurred almost daily since the government declared
a crackdown on Colombia's powerful cocaine traffickers on Aug. 18.
   The explosions came hours after lawmakers urged the government to
publicize reported ``black lists'' of corrupt politicians and
officials.
   Colombian newspapers today published the names of 25 lawmakers
and politicians, including a Liberal Party presidential candidate,
who the papers said had their U.S. visas denied or canceled.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Pablo Urutia today said he did not know if
the visas were withheld because of links with traffickers. He
refused further comment.
   Police said the bombs went off around 3 a.m.
   They damaged offices of the Liberals and Conservatives,
Colombia's two main political parties, in several neighborhoods of
the capital of 6 million people. Another blast ripped through a
bank. Banks have been a favorite target of the cocaine cartels.
   Police said the two injured people were taken to hospitals. There
were no other details immediately available.
   ``This shows the total decadence we are living in in this
country. It's a senseless war,'' said Emilio Barguch,
secretary-general of the Conservative Party. He said one blast
destroyed national party headquarters.
   Liberal Party leader Julio Cesar Sanchez, a former Bogota mayor,
called for an emergency meeting of the Congress to discuss
additional security measures.
   Liberal Party presidential candidate Alberto Santofimio Botero
said today his U.S. visa was canceled in March in Miami because he
met Medellin cartel leader Pablo Escobar eight years ago, when both
were congressmen.
   ``I barely knew him and met him only during a political rally,''
the Liberal politician told Radio Caracol, a private radio chain. He
accused the United States of retaliating for his criticism of
``American intervention in Nicaragua and Panama and other parts of
Latin America.''
   On Wednesday, the Senate asked the government for a U.S. list
with names of politicians denied visas because of suspected drug
connections.
   It also passed a resolution urging the government to make public
other lists with names of politicians and government leaders alleged
to have links with the cartels. Barco has said he's not aware of any
such lists.
   Also Wednesday, the head of the country's criminal investigation
office said British and Israeli mercenaries smuggled weapons through
Panama to train assassination squads for drug cartels, teaching them
tactics used in political killings and bombings.
   Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez, head of the Department of
Administrative Security, told the Senate that the mercenaries,
working for the drug cartels since 1987, ``can't escape
responsibility'' for the bank bombings and political assassinations.
   The slaying Aug. 18 of Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, a popular
presidential candidate and anti-drug crusader, led to the government
crackdown.
   As part of the crackdown, President Virgilio Barco revived
Colombia's extradition treaty with the United States, where the top
traffickers are wanted. So far, one person has been extradited, but
the drug barons on the nation's most-wanted list have eluded capture.
   Maza said foreign military trainers smuggled weapons from
neighboring Panama to train four paramilitary groups. Squads of 50
to 80 men each received up to four months of training, Maza said.
   He said at least nine Israelis trained the squads. It's unknown
how many British mercenaries were involved, but the British Embassy
has acknowledged trainers were in Colombia.
   Maza said his information was based in ``intelligence
investigations,'' but he charged that many in the military and
government, in an attempt to discredit him, and have been slow to
act on his reports.
   Maza, who has had at least four recent attempts on his life,
headed the investigation that led to the government issuing an
arrest warrant Monday for Yair Klein, a former Israeli army colonel
accused of training paramilitary squads for drug cartels.
   Mercenary training for both the Cali and Medellin cocaine cartels
consisted of supplying weapons and martial arts and explosives
training, Maza said.
</TEXT>
