<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Thatcher     09-21 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Thatcher,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Urges Western Support for Soviet Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain called
today for strong Western support for Soviet economic and political
reforms, saying they are in the interest of liberty.
   Mrs. Thatcher, in Japan for an international conference of
conservative parties, also said she is confident that trade issues
raised in meetings with Japanese leaders and business executives
will be resolved satisfactorily.
   The British leader has frankly criticized what she called Japan's
unfair trade barriers and urged fast action to open its markets to
foreign goods.
   In a meeting with former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and
later in comments to reporters, Mrs. Thatcher stressed Japan's
responsibility to contribute to global economic growth and called
for stronger support for reforms spearheaded by Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``This is the most bold and courageous leader the Soviet Union
has had while it's been under Communism. What Mr. Gorbachev is
attempting to do ... is in the interests of liberty as a whole and
in the interest of all other nations who believe in the cause of
democracy as well.
   ``We should do, therefore, everything we can to support this
great, historic movement ... and do all we can to see that it is
successful.''
   Mrs. Thatcher will visit Moscow for talks with Gorbachev when she
leaves Tokyo on Friday.
   She noted a trend in favor of Western democratic political and
economic views but cautioned against relaxing defenses, predicting a
period of instability in East-West relations and elsewhere.
   ``A time of great uncertainty is no time to reduce your
defenses,'' she said. ``You don't prevent wars by disarmament. You
prevent wars by quietly being prepared and having a sure defense.''
   Mrs. Thatcher pointed to China as an area where unexpected
political developments had created great uncertainty, and she urged
Japan to provide increased investment and support to Hong Kong.
   Confidence in the future of that British colony, which reverts to
Chinese rule in 1997, was shaken severely by Beijing's military
assault on pro-democracy demonstrators in China in June and an
ensuing crackdown on political dissent.
   ``It is absolutely vital we should do everything we can to keep
up the confidence of the people in Hong Kong,'' she said.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who arrived Tuesday in Tokyo to attend a
conference of the International Democratic Union, a grouping of
right-of-center political parties, called her visit ``timely.''
   ``With so many changes taking place in the world, it is very
important that the great democracies, and particularly the economic
summit seven countries, should consult very closely with each
other,'' she said.
   She said she hoped to create an ``unprecedented partnership''
with Japan in the 1990s and to resolve lingering trade problems.
</TEXT>
