<FIRST>r a PM-SpyTrial     09-21 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spy Trial,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turk Sentenced to Life in Spy Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Turkish mechanic who schemed with an Army
intelligence officer to sell U.S. military secrets to the East Bloc
has been sentenced to life in prison.
   Huseyin Yildirim, 61, was convicted July 20 of conspiring with
Warrant Officer James W. Hall to funnel the material to East German
and Soviet agents.
   U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield on Wednesday ordered that
Yildirim be ``banished from the United States, never to return'' if
he is paroled.
   Yildirim, of Belleair, Fla., did not testify at his trial but
told the judge Wednesday: ``In the reality, I am not guilty. I
protected America.''
   Prosecutors contended Yildirim, a civilian Army mechanic
stationed in West Berlin, carried military secrets from Hall and
returned with money from 1982 to 1988.
   Evidence indicated that Hall had access to all levels of
intelligence during tours at the Army's Field Station Berlin
listening post and in Frankfurt, West Germany; Fort Monmouth, N.J.,
and Fort Stewart, Ga.
   Hall was sentenced by a military judge to 40 years in prison.
   Edenfield rejected a plea to give Yildirim a comparable sentence.
   ``The only proper sentence for Mr. Hall would have been death at
a firing squad,'' Edenfield said.
</TEXT>
