<FIRST>r a PM-SentencingBill     09-21 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sentencing Bill,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Signs Law Requiring Judges to Explain Lenient Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges won't be able to let violent criminals off
without prison unless they explain their sentences in writing under
a new state law.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, who signed the legislation Wednesday
along with a bill increasing aid to victims of violent crime,
acknowledged the law would probably lead to more crowded prisons.
But he said he is committed to expanding prison space.
   ``If a judge is not going to sentence someone to prison for a
crime of violence, he should have very good reasons _ reasons that
will hold up to public scrutiny,'' Dukakis said. ``We're going to
expect judges in this state to be accountable.''
   Judges ``are fallible and make mistakes occasionally,'' he said,
adding that that would be much less likely to happen under the new
law because judges will be forced to think carefully about their
rulings.
   Chief Justice Paul Liacos said through a spokeswoman that he
isn't against the concept but is worried it will require more work
of judges without providing extra staff.
   The other bill signed by Dukakis at least doubles the fine
imposed on criminals to help victims.
   A sponsor said the legislation would raise $5 million a year for
services such as translation and counseling as well as $1.5 million
toward direct compensation to victims.
</TEXT>
