<HEAD>Italy's U.N. Ambassador, Giovanni Migliuolo, Dead at 62</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's permanent representative to the
United Nations, Giovanni Migliuolo, has died at the age of 62,
according to officials at the Italian U.N. Mission.
   Migliuolo died Wednesday night of a brain tumor at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York, they said.
   Migliuolo was one of the Italian government's experts on
East-West politics and was a scholar of Slavic languages and culture.
   He was Italy's ambassador to Moscow from 1981 to 1985, also
serving as ambassador to Mongolia. From 1985 to 1988, he was the
ambassador to Cairo. He became the senior U.N. ambassador a year ago.
   Migliuolo was married and had four children.
