<FIRST>u i PM-Hugo-GuadeloupeCrash 2ndLd-Writethru   09-21 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Guadeloupe Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0555,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescue Helicopter Crashes Into Sea; 6 Dead, 8 Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with six dead, report of loud noises from
helicopter during takeoff. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French air force helicopter aiding in rescue
efforts near the hurricane-stricken island of Guadeloupe crashed
into the sea, and officials said five bodies were recovered today.
   The body of a sixth man, who was being evacuated from the
outlying island of Desirade, was recovered shortly after the
helicopter went down Wednesday night, said officials from the
Guadeloupe capital, Point-a-Pitre. Three other people remained
missing.
   Chances were fading that searchers in helicopters and fishing
boats would find them alive, the officials said.
   The twin-engine Puma plunged into the Caribbean about a half-mile
southeast of the outlying island of Desirade while evacuating
Bernard Berchel, who had suffered head injuries when Hurricane Hugo
hit on Sunday, officials said.
   Also on the helicopter were Berchel's son, four medical workers
and the helicopter's crew of three, the officials said.
   The cause of the accident was unknown, but witnesses today
reported hearing unusually loud mechancial noises as the helicopter
lifted off from Desirade, about six miles east of Guadeloupe.
   The helicopter was part of ongoing rescue efforts involving about
3,000 French servicemen assisting civil authorities cope with the
aftermath of Hugo.
</TEXT>
