<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0490 09-21 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0490,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 4 grafs to include Carter comment after Bush meeting,
picks up 2nd graf pvs, Bush was...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today won the support of former
President Jimmy Carter for spending $9 million to aid the
anti-Sandinista opposition in Nicaragua's elections next year as a
way to ``make the playing field level.''
   Carter, who as head of the Atlanta-based Council of Freely
Elected Heads of State will lead an observer delegation to the
Nicaraguan elections, said as long as the money is used in
accordance with Nicaraguan law, it will benefit the political
process. He spoke with reporters after meeting with the president.
   The Nicaraguan election law requires that half of any money
coming into the political process from outside the country be given
to the country's electoral council that runs the elections.
   Carter reiterated his opinion that indications are the elections
will be fair, although some in the administration remain wary of the
leftist Sandinistas' sincerity.
   Bush was expected to send a formal request for the aid to Capitol
Hill as early as today, according to congressional sources. The aid
is intended to help long shot opposition candidate Violeta Chamorro
get a fairer shot in the presidential election scheduled for
February.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has been sounding out
prospects for the measure with congressional leaders, and one Senate
GOP source who spoke on condition of anonymity said responses had
been encouraging.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., a critic of past administration
efforts to aid opponents of the leftist Managua regime, said late
Wednesday his initial reaction to the package was favorable.
   The money _ to be funneled both directly to the opposition
political coalition and indirectly through the quasi-governmental
National Endowment for Democracy and United Nations election
observers _ would meet an estimated 80 percent or more of Chamorro
election budget, according to administration estimates.
   The endowment is a private foundation created by Congress in 1982
to support democratic elections worldwide, using money appropriated
by Congress.
   Proponents of the aid package said the administration believes it
would lend credibility to the opposition and make it easier for
Chamorro's coalition to raise additional money from other countries
and individuals.
   It also would help level the playing field for the fledgling
opposition coalition against the ruling Sandinista party, which has
held power since a 1979 revolution.
   Administration officials and many in Congress believe the
elections, while an uphill battle for the opposition, offer the best
opportunity in a decade to oust the Sandinistas and President Daniel
Ortega, who are closely linked to the Soviet Union.
   Most of the aid, some $5 million, would go to NED for use in
non-partisan efforts at voter registration, voter turnout and
election organizing, said sources in both parties and both houses of
Congress, all of whom spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The administration believes those efforts can be at least
indirectly helpful to Chamorro, the publisher of the opposition
newspaper La Prensa and the candidate of the opposition coalition
known as UNO.
   The move would require no change in NED's charter, which
prohibits direct partisan political activities.
   Another $2 million would go directly to UNO, but under Nicaraguan
law would have to be split 50-50 with the country's electoral
commission, which will run the elections.
   The remaining $2 million would help fund the activities of
election observer groups such as one to be sent by the United
Nations, the sources said.
   In visits to Washington last week, UNO representatives asked for
overt U.S. aid for ``the electoral process'' in Nicaragua, despite
what they said was the certainty that the Sandinistas would seek to
use American support as a propaganda weapon against them.
   Earlier this month, the Bush administration had considered asking
for $3 million for an open, direct donation to Chamorro's campaign,
but modified that approach in the face of congressional opposition.
</TEXT>
