<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     09-21 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Parliament Member; Syrian-Christian Clashes Kill One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men armed with AK-47 rifles opened
fire Thursday on a Sunni Moslem member of Parliament, killing him
and his driver and injuring two passers-by, police said.
   Across Beirut and surrounding mountains, Syrian forces and
gunners loyal to Lebanon's Christian leader, Gen. Michel Aoun,
dueled with mortars and tank cannons.
   Police said at least one person was killed and six wounded,
raising the overall toll to 927 killed and 2,731 wounded since the
latest round of fighting broke out March 8.
   The attack on Parliament member Nazim Kadri occurred as the
74-year-old politician entered his car outside his home in west
Beirut at about 10:20 a.m., according to witnesses.
   A police spokesman said Kadri and his police driver, Sgt. Sami
Suleiman, were killed instantly and two pedestrians were injured,
one seriously, in the shooting.
   One witness said the killers jumped out of a red car parked
behind Kadri's.
   ``The gunmen called Kadri by name, the deputy looked at them,''
the witness said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Two gunmen
opened fire. Kadri's driver drew his pistol, but another gunman took
several shots at him from an automatic rifle before he managed to
open fire.''
   The witness said the killers sped away, shooting into the air.
There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   An official obituary released by Parliament's public relations
department said Kadri was first elected as a representative for the
central Bekaa Valley in the one-chamber house in 1951. The former
lawyer was ``repeatedly elected'' until 1972 when the latest
parliamentary elections were held.
   The civil war, which broke out in 1975, has prevented further
elections. Kadri's assassination brought to 73 the number of
surviving deputies in the 99-seat Parliament. Twenty-five have died
and the seat of former President Amin Gemayel became vacant when he
was elected head of state in 1982.
   The latest violence occurred as an Arab League committee tried to
enforce a cease-fire call.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt told the Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Qabas
that the peace plan issued last week by the three-man committee was
``inadequate.'' He demanded guarantees that arms supplies to Aoun
would be cut off.
   Jumblatt said that without guarantees of a halt of weapons to
Aoun, the plan would amount to no more than a ``mere truce.''
   Aoun receives weapons from Iraq, a bitter rival of Syria.
   Syria has 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 mandate to quell
the civil war. Aoun says Syria violated the mandate by siding with
the Moslems in the civil war, and he has vowed to drive them out.
   The latest violence broke out after Aoun in March imposed a
blockade of ports run by Moslem militias. The Syrians responded by
shelling the Christian enclave north of Beirut, home to about 1
million Christians.
</TEXT>
