<FIRST>u a PM-BusAccident 8thLd-Writethru a0631 09-21 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Accident, 8th Ld - Writethru, a0631,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Texas School Bus Crash Kills 18, Injures 49</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Cox said ...' to CORRECT city to Carrollton.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MCA1, MCA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school bus was hit from behind by a
delivery truck and plunged into a watery gravel pit this morning,
authorities said. At least 18 youngsters were reported killed and 49
other people injured.
   Divers pulled several bodies from the 12 feet of murky water
covering the bus, which was carrying students to junior and senior
high schools in Mission when it fell on its side into the 40- to
45-foot hole, authorities said.
   ``They were just trapped. We had to break the glass of the
windows to get in,'' said Al Nye, a scuba diver who said he pulled
seven bodies out. Nye, who was driving his children to school at the
time of the accident, said, ``You couldn't see at all in there.''
   Mike Cox, spokesman for the Department of Public Safety, said at
least 18 people, ages 12 to 18, were killed in the 7:40 a.m.
accident, which occurred in clear, dry weather near the Mexican
border about 75 miles from Brownsville.
   Rescuers used a crane to lift the bus from the water but divers
continued searching at midday for any more victims.
   The number of people aboard the 70-seat bus was not immediately
known. The bus driver and the truck driver were being treated at
hospitals, authorities said. Their conditions were not known.
   The owner of the unfenced pit alongside the road was not
immediately known.
   ``We're going crazy here,'' said firefighter Ruben Ortiz. The
youngsters' parents ``are very hysterical. They have really lost
control, some of them.''
   Cox said it was the worst school bus accident in Texas history.
The two worst such accidents in U.S. history occurred in Kentucky.
In 1988, 24 children and three adults on a church outing died in a
fiery collision near Carrollton. In 1959, 27 people were killed when
a bus went into a creek in Prestonsburg.
   Mike Herrera, who was trailing the bus and the soft drink
delivery truck, said the truck ran into the back of the bus,
knocking it into the pit. Herrera said he jumped into the water and
helped rescue three students.
   Witnesses said that immediately after the accident, students and
the driver climbed onto the bus and screamed for help.
   At Mission Hospital, 29 people were in stable condition, said
Nora Martinez, a nursing supervisor.
   Seven were in good condition at HCA Rio Grande Regional Medical
Center, said spokeswoman Betty Baldwin.
   Thirteen were taken in McAllen Medical Center, spokeswoman Judy
Gomez said.
</TEXT>
