<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Auschwitz     09-21 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Auschwitz,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Identity Cards of Auschwitz Inmates Kept in Soviet Archives</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Convent, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Identity cards of 130,000 prisoners of the
Auschwitz concentration camp, which once were stored in sealed
Soviet archives, have been released and turned over to the Red
Cross, the Tass news agency said Thursday.
   ``The deaths of over 74,000 people were neatly recorded, day
after day, hour after hour, in 46 huge volumes,'' Valentina
Fatyukhina, head of the Soviet Red Cross research department, told
Tass.
   ``Their names, the birth dates and the names of parents were
written down,'' she said.
   Tass said the information was given to the International Red
Cross, which will soon begin the task of processing the cards,
making it possible to identify the citizens of many countries who
were victims of Auschwitz.
   Auschwitz, in Poland, was one of the most infamous concentration
camps run by the Nazis during World War II. An estimated 2.5 million
Jews were killed at the camp during the war.
   Ms. Fatyukhina said the Auschwitz material was found by Soviet
soldiers at the end of the war and shipped to the Soviet Union.
   Tass said access to the volumes only became possible about a year
and a half ago as more and more archives were opened to researchers
under the policy of glasnost initiated by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   ``Nobody expected that 130,000 individual cards of concentration
camp inmates existed,'' Tass said.
</TEXT>
