<HEAD>Defense Begins Presenting Its Side of Jim Bakker Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A laid-off but still loyal PTL employee
testified today that Jim Bakker truly cared about the contributors
he is accused of fleecing because they were the ones who built his
empire.
   Elizabeth Sacco, who answered correspondence at PTL until her
layoff in 1986, testified for the defense today that Bakker was
concerned about the ministry's ``partners'' _ $1,000 contributors
who were promised free lodging at the Heritage USA theme park in
Fort Mill, S.C.
   ``He wanted them treated fairly and politely,'' she testified.
``He said these were the people who built this place.''
   Prosecution witnesses in the 3{-week-old trial have testified
that many PTL employees were laid off at the same time Bakker and
his wife were receiving six-figure bonuses. But Ms. Sacco continues
to back Bakker.
   ``Yes, I do, and I'm proud of it,'' Ms. Sacco said. ``I feel
loyalty because I've seen what this man built. A greedy man doesn't
have his hair turn gray in five years. I wouldn't have taken his job
for $10 million a year.''
   Bakker is accused of defrauding his followers by diverting $3.7
million so that he could live in high style. If found guilty on all
24 counts, Bakker could be sentenced to 120 years in prison and
fined more than $5 million.
   On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Robert Potter rejected a
defense motion to dismiss the charges on the grounds that Bakker's
religious freedom was violated.
   ``This is not a case about religion,'' said prosecutor Jerry
Miller. ``This is a case about lying to people over television and
cheating them out of their money. ... This is a case about fraud.''
   Earlier Wednesday, prosecutors wrapped up their case, saying
Bakker's ministry had oversold partnerships at its hotels.
   The jurors saw 3-year-old tapes of ``The PTL Club'' show in which
Bakker called the purchase of such time shares ``a deal of a
lifetime.''
   ``We're not here to make money,'' Bakker said. ``I hope my
critics wake up and realize I'd be a fool if I tried to make money
off something like this.''
