<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DayCareTax     09-21 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Day Care Tax,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Tax Law May End Under-the-Table Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new federal tax law aimed at collecting
unreported day-care income may thin the ranks of baby sitters and
drive up the cost of child care, tax specialists and industry
spokesmen say.
   The law requires parents to provide the Internal Revenue Service
with the name and Social Security number of their day-care provider
if they want to deduct the cost on their federal income taxes.
   The IRS will check the cost reported by parents with the amount
reported by baby sitters as the agency goes after an estimated $7
billion in day-care income that goes unreported each year.
   ``I don't know that they'll send a grandma to jail, but it will
be tough on them,'' said Barry Barros, a tax preparer who
specializes in day-care provider returns.
   The law applies only to day care provided while parents are at
work.
   ``We will indeed be cross-referencing to see if that baby sitter
claimed that as income,'' said Sarah Wreford, a spokeswoman for the
IRS in Detroit.
   Day-care providers not claiming the payments as income on their
tax returns could be required to pay back taxes with interest and a
$50 fine, Wreford said.
   Barros, of Stockton, Calif., says it may take the IRS two or
three years before it's equipped to double-check a large number of
returns for day-care income.
   Baby sitters collecting money under the table may be more likely
to raise their prices once they are required to declare the income,
Barros said.
   The National Association for Family Day Care, a non-profit
organization representing about 3,000 day-care providers, said it
supports the new law.
   ``The association feels anything that can be done to provide a
more professional setting for child care is beneficial,'' said Kay
Hollestelle, accreditation administrator.
   The IRS says parents who seek the deduction without providing the
Social Security number or tax identification number of their
day-care provider could be turned down for the credit.
   ``We may lose some providers,'' said Carole Quarterman, executive
director of the Child Care Coordinating Council of Detroit-Wayne
County Inc. ``There are some people whose clear intention is to make
some money on the side and not report the income.''
   The credit allows parents and those paying for the care of
mentally or physically incompetent dependents to deduct a certain
percentage of their care costs directly from their income taxes.
Those eligible usually can claim a credit ranging from 30 percent of
the expense, if their income does not exceed $10,000, to 20 percent
if their income exceeds $28,000.
</TEXT>
