<HEAD>Basketball Team Buying Murdoch TV Station</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Murdoch, whose ...' to CORRECT that Murdoch
no longer owns Post. A version moved on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boston Celtics have agreed to buy a TV station
of the Fox Broadcasting network from Rupert Murdoch, owner of the
Boston Herald.
   Fox and the NBA team announced the agreement in a statement
Wednesday but provided no details.
   Murdoch, whose holdings once included the New York Post, had been
under pressure to sell WFXT or the Herald because of Federal
Communications Commission regulations against ownership two media
outlets in the same city.
   The Boston Globe said the price was an estimated $50 million. The
Herald, quoting unidentified sources, put the figure at closer to
$20 million.
   The sale is subject to FCC approval.
   Once the sale is final, the station will be able to broadcast the
Celtics' 39 road games as early as the 1990-91 season. Celtics games
are carried on WLVI.
   ``It's very positive that a station that three years ago nobody
ever heard of and then became a Fox affiliate will now be the
official station of the Boston Celtics,'' said Joe Robinowitz,
general manager of WFXT.
   Fox Television Stations Inc. is a unit on the Australian-based
News Corp., a media holding company controlled by Murdoch. The Fox
network owns seven of its more than 120 affiliates across the United
States, Robinowitz said.
</TEXT>
