<FIRST>r a AM-Naturists-PropertyTax     09-21 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Naturists-Property Tax,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Exemption for Naturist Religious Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walking naked through the woods,
using the land as a spiritual retreat, does not constitute a
religious activity in the definition of this county's tax
authorities.
   The Pasco County Property Appraisal Adjustment Board turned down
an attempt by T. Ward Gulvin, president of the Naturist Religious
Society, to win a tax exemption on 80 acres of undeveloped property
for a kind of open-air church for the uninhibited.
   ``It may be a personal religious experience. But in my mind it's
not the type of religious activity that meets the statutory
requirement for a tax exemption,'' said Allan ``Sonny'' Safranek
Jr., county commission chairman.
   The society is based in Hudson, just up the Central Florida Gulf
Coast from New Port Richey.
   Gulvin told the board Wednesday that ``people who are members of
the Naturist Religious Society use the land as a spiritual retreat.
They want to feel next to nature, and enjoy the trees and shrubs and
birds and flowers and animals ... and all the beauty of nature.''
   But Property Appraiser Ted Williams told the board Gulvin hadn't
established a church. He was unable to provide a list of members,
Williams said, noting that five members of the corporation were
related to Gulvin.
   The society was incorporated in 1944 in New Jersey to provide a
place of worship for those who ``don't believe that it is a sin to
expose the unclothed human body to members of (the) opposite sex of
like belief,'' incorporation papers state.
   ``It appears to be a closely held corporation,'' said Williams.
``I think he is saying ... that because they believe in worshiping
nature, the sun, the breeze and things of that sort, he should have
a church exemption. In my opinion, he hasn't established himself as
a church.''
   Pasco Commissioner Ann Hildebrand said if the exemption request
had been granted, ``You'd be setting a precedent for everybody to
communicate with God on their property and get a tax exemption.''
   ``Nudism is not a religion,'' said Joan Axford of the City
Retreat Nudist Resort in Hudson. ``Nudism is a different way of
life. It doesn't separate people according to their socio-economic
backgrounds. The only thing you have going for you is what's
inside.''
</TEXT>
