<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Edward James Olmos said he relied on a
``discipline muscle'' to rise from Los Angeles barrio kid to movie
star.
   ``I started off not speaking the language. I was a minority. I
did not know how to read or write,'' Olmos said Wednesday during an
appearance at a high school.
   Olmos, who starred in ``Stand and Deliver,'' told 1,800 mostly
minority teen-agers that developing discipline is like brushing
their teeth.
   ``Since all of you brush your teeth every day, something that you
don't get off on, what makes you think that you can't do something
that you like seven days a week?,'' he said.
   Olmos portrayed math teacher Jaime Escalante in the film. The
real-life teacher inspired 18 inner-city students at an East Los
Angeles to pass the Advanced Placement test in calculus in 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't the first time writer Ken Kesey
turned on LSD guru of the '60s Timothy Leary.
   The two appeared with former Black Panther Bobby Seale at Leary's
alma mater, the University of Alabama, but Leary couldn't get his
microphone to work.
   Kesey flipped a switch at the bottom of the mike stand.
   ``I have just been turned on by Ken Kesey,'' Leary joked. ``I
can't say it's the first time.''
   Leary told the college crowd Wednesday night people should be
allowed to use drugs if they want to.
   ``The war on drugs is the war against pro-choice,'' Leary said.
``The war on drugs is a war to make America respect authority.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball fans are shelling out $2 and more
to listen to Oakland A's slugger Jose Canseco talk about guns,
steroids and speeding tickets in recorded messages about his daily
life.
   ``To hear Jose discuss the topics of steroids, his ownership of
guns or speeding, press 2,'' Wednesday's recording said. Or callers
could press ``1'' for this account:
   ``My personal life was kind of boring. I woke up late again _
like I say, I like to sleep late _ and went to a mall with my friend
and ate Italian food.''
   The hotline began this week and is expected to be updated daily.
Callers pay $2 for the first minute and $1 for each minute
thereafter.
   The outfielder said he started the hotline because he was
frustrated by sportswriters who refused to tell the truth as he
views it.
   ``It's what the fans want to hear,'' said Jeff Borris, Canseco's
Beverly Hills agent. ``They want to know what's going on in his
life.''
   Wednesday's recording also included an account of a recent
speeding ticket Canseco received.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two workers at a Skid Row mission and a pair
of police detectives just driving by rescued actor Kevin Dobson from
a knife-wielding transient as the ``Knots Landing'' star donated
clothing to the poor.
   Dobson, who portrays Mack McKenzie on the CBS primetime soap
opera, is a regular donor to the downtown Midnight Mission.
   The actor was able to break free from the would-be robber
Wednesday outside the shelter, police officer Mike Schwehr said.
   Two mission employees came to the actor's aid, Schwehr said.
   Detectives Tom Blake and Joel Berk were driving past the mission
when the scuffle broke out. They arrested Sergio Orozco, 28, and
confiscated a hunting knife from him, Schwehr said.
   The secondhand clothes Dobson donated included several pairs of
Levis jeans and Calvin Klein socks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II's first
cousin, Alexandra, is not only a princess but the honorary head of a
regiment, and she'll present her troops with a puppy and a new flag
Saturday.
   The princess arrived Wednesday for the 75th anniversary of the
Canadian Scottish Regiment. She brought along a new mascot, an
8-week-old St. Bernard puppy, and a new regiment flag referred to as
the ``Queen's Color.''
   Members of the regiment won four Victoria Crosses in France
during World War I. The regiment also served in World War II in
France, Holland and Germany.
