<FIRST>u a AM-AgentIndicited     09-21 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Indicited,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Federal Drug Agent, Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has handed up an 11-count
indictment charging a federal drug agent, his wife and the owner of
a construction company with conspiracy, tax evasion and laundering
large amounts of cash, officials said Thursday.
   The federal grand jury indicted Drug Enforcement Administration
special agent Dennis Harker, his wife, Mary Ann, and Susan K. Terry,
who owns a construction business in West Des Moines.
   The indictment also charges Harker and Ms. Terry with ``use of an
interstate facility to promote an illegal activity.'' It alleges
that from 1986 and 1988 Harker and his wife ``spent, invested and
profited by cash transactions exceeding $1 million.''
   Harker and Ms. Terry were charged with using a business they
established ``to launder substantial amounts of currency which
Harker had acquired and to funnel the cash through what would appear
to be legitimate business transactions and loans between the two
partners.''
   There was no mention of drugs in the indictment, and U.S.
Attorney Joe Beck refused to elaborate beyond the indictment.
   Harker is assigned to the DEA in Miami, but formerly lived in
West Des Moines. He could face 40 years in prison and $2 million in
fines if convicted on all charges.
   The U.S. attorney's office said the indictment was handed up
Wednesday.
   Arraignment was set for Oct. 2.
</TEXT>
