<FIRST>r w AM-US-Pacific     09-21 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Pacific,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cranston Critical of Bush Efforts in Pacific Rim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration told Congress on
Thursday that it remains committed to enhancing economic cooperation
and dialogue with Asian Pacific nations, but that it will take time,
effort and patience.
   But Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., criticized U.S. diplomacy in
the area as ``complacent'' despite an economic boom in East Asia
that's bringing unparalleled prosperity and trading opportunities
and problems.
   Richard H. Solomon, assistant secretary of State for East Asian
and Pacific Affairs, told the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
that the Bush administration believes it's essential to build a
framework ``to help manage the increasingly interdependent economies
of the Asian-Pacific region.''
   Consultations, he said, are under way with nations along the
Pacific rim ``to strengthen the consensus for an open trading and
investment system essential for sustaining global economic growth
into the 21st century.''
   Consensus building is ``a delicate and measured process'' that is
difficult to rush, Solomon said.
   However, Cranston said ``there is insufficient initiative from
Washington to prepare for the challenges of the Pacific century.''
   ``And key Asian powers appear too willing to trot out the same
tired excuses to avoid the tough decisions necessary to organize for
the challenge of the 21st century,'' said Cranston, chairman of the
Foreign Relations subcommittee on Asia.
   A Pacific Basin Forum, Cranston said, ``would allow us to pursue
such crucial issues as free trade, economic development and security
confidence building.''
   Cranston called for the establishment of a permanent secretariat
to do research and pursue dialogue on a wide range of concerns.
   ``Unless we undertake a deliberate effort to establish a more
mutually beneficial business climate, trade tensions with Asia may
well increase in the years ahead as export-led development by the
remarkably successful capitalist nations of East Asia continues,''
he said.
</TEXT>
