<HEAD>NTSB Seeks Pilot's Hospital Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are seeking a
court order to force a hospital to release any psychiatric records
on the pilot who crashed in the Atlantic Ocean after a mysterious
800-mile flight.
   The petition filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court said the
National Transportation Safety Board wants all records related to
the physical and mental condition of Thomas Root.
   Board investigator Andrew Alston said Memorial Hospital in
Hollywood, where Root was treated after his July 13 crash, already
released its medical records but a court order is needed for it to
turn over any psychiatric records.
   Root, 36, a Washington communications lawyer, said Wednesday he
could not comment on the hospital records because he did not know
what they include. Root has said he does not recall how he suffered
a gunshot wound in the abdomen.
   Root says he passed out while at the controls, and his small
plane flew on for several hours on autopilot until it ran out of
fuel and crashed in the Bahamas. It was followed much of the way by
military jets.
