<FIRST>r i AM-Saudi-Executions     09-21 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi-Executions,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Shiite Terrorists Beheaded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDULLAH AL-SHEHRI</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen Shiite Moslems from Kuwait
were beheaded Thursday for exploding two bombs in Mecca at the
height of the Moslem pilgrimage to the holy city, the Interior
Ministry said.
   An Interior Ministry statement implicitly blamed Iran for the
attacks, which killed a man and were believed connected to the
centuries-old feud between Sunni and Shiite Moslems.
   Four other Kuwaitis were sentenced to 15 years and 20 years in
prison and 1,000 to 1,500 whiplashes for the bomb blasts, the
ministry statement said.
   Nine defendants were acquitted, it said. Convictions and
sentences were decided and confirmed by lower and appellate courts
of Islamic scholars, the statement said.
   A Pakistani man was killed and 16 other pilgrims of various
nationalities were wounded when the bombs went off the night of July
10 as 2 million Moslems gathered for the culmination of the
pilgrimage, or hajj.
   Thursday's report was the first official word that arrests had
been made in connection with the blasts near the Grand Mosque in
Mecca, Islam's holiest shrine.
   The executions were carried out ``in accordance with Islamic
law,'' the statement said without elaborating. Sources close to the
government, who requested anonymity, said the Kuwaitis were
blindfolded and beheaded by sword at dawn in a Mecca prison compound.
   Government sources said Saudi Arabia refused a Kuwaiti request to
extradite the bombers.
   Full confessions from the condemned men will be broadcast on
television, the announcement said.
   It described the blasts as ``an evil crime ... an aggression on
the sanctity of the holy sites and on the pilgrims ... (and) of the
entire Moslem nation.''
   The Interior Ministry said the defendants plotted the attack at
meetings in Kuwait, Mecca and the Saudi city of Medina.
   Their aim, it said, was to spread ``terror and fear in the hearts
of the pilgrims ... and show that (Saudi Arabia) was unable to
protect the house of God.''
   Every Moslem, Sunni or Shiite, has a duty to make the pilgrimage
to Mecca, the birthplace of the 7th century prophet Mohammed, and to
Medina, where Mohammed is buried.
   Sunnis and Shiites disagree about who should have succeeded
Mohammed.
   Iran, which has an overwhelming majority of Shiites among its
nearly 50 million people, had been urging Moslems to seize Mecca and
Medina.
   Without naming Iran, Saudi Arabia's statement said the July
bombings were perpetrated ``at the instructions of the mischievous
ones, who are enemies of this nation and for all pilgrims of God's
house, and cooperating with those mischievous ones on such
debauchery and terrorism in the most sacred spot in the world.''
   Since the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's 1979 Islamic
revolution in Iran, Iranian pilgrims have tried to turn the hajj
into a political forum to spread his fundamentalist teachings.
   In 1987, Iranian pilgrims clashed with Saudi security, leading to
the deaths of 402 pilgrims, most Iranians.
   After that, Riyadh restricted the numbers of pilgrims. This drew
protests from Iran, which boycotted the 1988 and 1989 pilgrimages.
   Saudi Arabia, citing subversion and terrorism, severed relations
with Tehran in April 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
