<FIRST>r a AM-VisaAgreement     09-21 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Visa Agreement,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Suspending Visa Requirement to Be Signed This Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natives of northwest Alaska and parts of
the Soviet Far East can look forward to streamlined travel across
the Bering Strait after the signing of a U.S.-Soviet agreement this
weekend.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze are to sign a document allowing visa-free travel
by 1,000 or so Alaska and Soviet Yupiks with relatives on opposite
sides of the strait.
   While meeting at Jackson Hole, Wyo., on arms control, the two
also are expected to sign another agreement creating a commission to
resolve minor incidents in the Bering Strait region. Since the
Soviet Union cut off travel across the strait in 1948, there have
been occasional border-crossing disputes.
   Elimination of the visa requirement ``means that family members
will be able to see each other again,'' said Janie Leask, president
of the Alaska Federation of Natives. ``It means that a people
divided by an artificial boundary will once again be able to share
experiences and their culture.
   ``I expect quite a bit of travel, especially from those villages
along the Bering Sea coast.''
   One of those planning to go is Branson Tungiyan, secretary of the
Gambell Common Council.
   ``Now that we've seen some of the ... Russians here at Gambell
we've made friends, and more than likely we have long lost relatives
we haven't seen since the 1930s,'' Tungiyan said.
   Improved U.S.-Soviet relations in the past year have resulted in
several trips across the strait and reunions. This week, 34 natives
from the Soviet Union have been participating in the Bering Straits
Region Elders Conference in Nome.
   Bering Air of Nome recently began offering charter flights
between that town, 100 miles southeast of the Bering Strait, and the
Soviet port town of Provideniya.
   Although the need for visas will end, passports still will be
required. People from each side of the Bering Strait will be allowed
non-visa visits of up to 90 days if they have been invited by
relatives or other people with whom they share a cultural heritage.
</TEXT>
