<FIRST>r i AM-Niger-Crash     09-21 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Niger-Crash,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Searchers See Plane's Parts Sprinkled Over the Desert; Recorders
Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airport Security, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGADEZ, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tiny pieces of UTA Flight 772 first
appeared like confetti in the sand. Then big chunks of the fuselage,
shattered in the crash that killed all 171 people aboard, came into
view.
   It was hard to imagine, during a low-level flight over the crash
scene, that the pieces ever came together to form a jumbo jet.
   Investigators in the Tenere Desert worked in 113-degree heat
Thursday to determine a cause for the crash of the Paris-bound DC-10
two days earlier. They recovered the flight and voice recorders from
the wreckage, a spokesman at the French Foreign Ministry in Paris
said Thursday night.
   UTA, or the Union des Transportes Aeriens, a private French
company that serves Africa and the Pacific, says a bomb was the most
likely reason that debris spread over as much as 40 square miles.
   The pro-Iranian group Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility in
separate telephone calls in London and Paris, although officials
said they could not authenticate the claim.
   Strewn across the sand was a piece of the wing of the 16-year-old
white and blue DC-10, and miles away, the tail. The bright colors of
clothes dumped from shattered bags contrasted with a dull brown
landscape.
   Blackened bodies were scattered across the desert.
   The dead included seven Americans, among them Bonnie Pugh, wife
of the U.S. ambassador to Chad, Robert L. Pugh. Other victims
included a Chadian Cabinet minister, two Swiss priests and eight
children.
   Two French military helicopters were stationed at a small camp at
the site. Two tents and several small vehicles, some with Red Cross
markings also were seen. The force was flown in from neighboring
Chad.
   They were gathering the bodies to fly them to N'Djamena, Chad for
identification, according to Col. Jean-Pierre Job, commander of the
French forces in Chad. His men were the ones who located the
wreckage and were the first on the scene.
   The French Transport Ministry appointed a commission to analyze
the information from the plane's flight and voice recorders.
   The plane was on a flight from Brazzaville, Congo to Paris. It
disappeared 400 miles northwest of N'Djamena, the Chadian capital,
where it had made a stop. The crash area is about 150 miles east of
Agadez, a city in central Niger.
   Crash investigation experts were en route from the United States.
Other officials were on site from Chad and Niger.
   In Washington, the FBI said it was reviewing information from the
crash to determine whether to open a criminal investigation.
   Anti-terrorism statutes give the FBI jurisdiction to investigate
terrorist attacks on Americans overseas.
   ``There is always a possibility of an FBI investigation. Right
now we are on consultation wth other government agencies,'' said FBI
spokesman Charles W. Steinmetz. ``It's certainly a serious issue we
are placing a significant amount of importance on.'' Before the FBI
can enter such cases, it must get permission of the country where
the crime occurred.
   An anonymous caller to the news agency in London said Islamic
Jihad was responsible for the plane's downing and demanded the
release of Shiite Moslem religious leader Sheik Abdul-Karim Obeid,
who was kidnapped from southern Lebanon on July 28 by Israeli forces.
   Islamic Jihad is among several radical fundamentalist groups in
Lebanon believed to be part of Hezbollah, or Party of God, the
umbrella group thought to hold 16 Westerners hostage in Lebanon.
Obeid is a member of Hezbollah.
   UTA said it received an anonymous telephone call about midnight
Tuesday, before the downed aircraft had been located by a French
military plane, saying Islamic Jihad was responsible.
</TEXT>
