<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Hammon     09-21 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Hammon,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polio Researcher Dead at 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEMINOLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Hammon, a retired missionary and
physician widely known for his research of polio and tropical
diseases, has died. He was 85.
   Hammon, recipient of the presidential Medal of Freedom in 1946,
died Tuesday at a nursing home in this community near St. Petersburg.
   In the 1950s, he worked with Dr. Jonas Salk researching an
effective vaccine for polio. Hammon had been a professor of
epidemiology at Harvard University and traveled throughout Africa,
the Pacific Islands and Asia practicing public health medicine.
   ``He was a pioneer in the field of polio,'' said Salk, who
finally developed the breakthrough vaccine that virtually wiped out
the crippling disease. ``His research was part of the progression of
how one might understand how to prevent polio,'' Salk said from his
medical institute in San Diego.
   Hammon, a native of Columbus, Ohio, had lived in the Tampa Bay
area since 1972.
   He was awarded the Outstanding Civilian Service Award from the
U.S. Army in 1973, was president of several national medical and
scientific societies and was a consultant with the World Health
Organization and Pan American Sanitary Bureau.
   He is survived by his wife Helen, a son, daughter and six
grandchildren.
   A memorial service was planned Friday in Seminole.
</TEXT>
