<FIRST>u i AM-Hugo-Aftermath     09-21 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Aftermath,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane-Damaged Puerto Rico Awaits Disaster Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Storm-weary residents searched for
scare water, gasoline and grocery items Thursday as crews worked to
restore the island's water and elecricity, knocked out by Hurricane
Hugo.
   Police said a 94-year-old woman, Emilia Negron Figueroa, was
found dead Wednesday in her home in San Juan, raising to 26 the
number of deaths blamed on Hurricane Hugo.
   The storm hit the U.S. commonwealth Monday after passing through
a string of Caribbean islands. Police said the woman apparently
fell, was unable to get up and drowned when water rushed into her
home.
   President Bush on Thursday declared Puerto Rico and the U.S.
Virgin Islands federal disaster areas, making them eligible for
emergency relief funds.
   A team of 1,100 soldiers dispatched by Bush entered the Virgin
Islands at St. Croix, which was pummeled by Hugo and then hit by a
looting frenzy.
   The Coast Guard in Miami said about 600 people had been evacuated
from St. Croix. It said crewmen on board the cutter Bear reported
that the city of Fredericksted in St. Croix ``erupted'' at sunset
Wednesday and that firing from automatic weapons and small arms
could be heard.
   Adm. William J. Crowe, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
described the situation as ``near anarchy'' and said troops had
rifles and were ordered to shoot if necessary to defend themselves.
   But presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the situation
had improved.
   ``The troops are having an obvious impact in controlling the
looting and other lawlessness associated with the destruction. It is
impossible to say at this point how long they will have to be
there,'' he said.
   Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon of Puerto Rico said the government
was taking an inventory of the damage and expected disaster relief
money to be made available within two weeks.
   The Red Cross was sending thousands of cots and bedding for some
of the island's estimated 25,000 people still in shelters.
   Coast Guard planes continued shuttling food, medicine, bedding
and clothes to the 8,500 residents of the offshore islands of
Vieques and Culebra, which were devastated by the hurricane.
   Seventy percent of the island remained without water and 25
percent was without electricity. Health officials warned a possible
health hazard if the island remained without water for much longer.
   Luis Ruiz Javier, director of the Puerto Rico Aqueduct and Sewer
Authority, said five electric motors for water pumps arrived from
the United States on Thursday to replace those demolished at
Carraizo Dam, which provides water to much of the capital of 1.1
million people.
   He one of the five motors would be installed by Friday morning
and would begin distributing water to the capital on a rationing
basis.
   By Monday, the authority expected to have water service restored
to 80 percent of the island, which has a population of 3.3 million.
   Many hospitals in the San Juan metropolitan area cut back
services because of water shortages, and at least two, Teachers
Hospital and San Jorge Hospital, stopped admitting patients
Wednesday.
   At Ashford Presbyterian Community Hospital, personnel worked 36
hours straight to deliver babies and take care of the injured from
the hurricane, said Ivan Millon, the hospital's executive director.
   ``Everybody's pitching in,'' he said. The hospital had its own
water supply and generators, he said.
   Supermarkets were opened on shortened hours, but bottled water
and canned foods were almost impossible to find. There was also
shortages of baby food, disposal diapers and milk.
   ``Yesterday we sold all the water we have,'' said Pilar Colon,
manager of a 7-Eleven. Looters stole the store's cigarettes and
liquor after the hurricane broke its front windows.
   Hernandez Colon said dairies back in operation after being shut
down by power outages had agreed to donate 300,000 quarts of milk a
day to the needy.
   Gasoline was also in short supply in some areas. A line of more
than a dozen cars waited at one of the few service stations opened
in San Juan.
</TEXT>
