<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Relief     09-21 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Relief,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Yorkers Aid Hugo Victims in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Yorkers prepared Thursday for weekend
telethons, fund-raising concerts and church collections to benefit
Puerto Ricans left homeless by Hurricane Hugo.
   A Trump Shuttle plane was to leave Friday morning, laden with
tons of supplies, including clothing, air mattresses and water.
   ``We're going to load it up with as much as we can get on the
airplane,'' said Bruce Nobles, president of Trump Shuttle. City
Council President Andrew Stein and Luis Miranda, the mayor's adviser
for Hispanic affairs, will accompany the shipment.
   Stein, noting the 1.5 million New York-area residents of Puerto
Rican descent, said, ``We are going to strengthen our ties and
relieve the suffering for those who are in need. ... In assisting
them, we will be assisting our neighbors as well.''
   The hurricane destroyed or damaged homes of an estimated 129,000
people on Puerto Rico.
   Pop music stars were joining in the fund-raising effort, which on
Sunday includes a telethon on the Spanish-language network
Telemundo, a marathon show at a South Bronx theater and a concert at
Nassau Coliseum on Long Island.
   ``My office has received hundreds of calls, and to my surprise,
the majority of calls are from English-speaking people,'' said the
Rev. Ruben Diaz, executive director of the Christian Community
Benevolent Association, which is coordinating some events.
   ``We have a saying in Puerto Rico that you know who your friends
are when you are in need,'' he said. ``People without knowing us
have come forward and are volunteering to help. It's beautiful.''
   Along with three banks accepting donations for disaster aid in
Puerto Rico, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York asked its
churches to collect money this weekend for relief work throughout
the Caribbean. The hurricane also struck the Virgin Islands,
Montserrat, Guadeloupe and Antigua.
   Sunday's ``Telethon for Brotherhood,'' from 11 a.m. to 11 p.m.
will originate from studios in New York and Florida, with live
transmissions from Puerto Rico. Singers Danny Rivera, Ruben Blades
and Chayanne are scheduled to perform.
   The Telemundo network of 34 stations reaches three-fourths of the
Hispanic households in America, said spokeswoman Alicia Villarosa.
She said the telethon's ``tentative, conservative'' goal is to raise
$2 million.
</TEXT>
