<FIRST>r w AM-WasteCzar     09-21 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waste Czar,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grace Says Wasteful Nation Needs `Waste Czar'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J. Peter Grace, who headed a presidential
commission on government costs in the Reagan administration, called
on President Bush Thursday to name a ``waste czar'' to lead a
campaign against waste of public money.
   ``We are in a crisis situation, and nothing less than a war on
waste, with the full support of every taxpaying American, will stop
Congress' wasteful spending,'' Grace told the National Press Club.
   ``To lead the war on waste, I am calling for the appointment of a
waste czar, reporting directly to the president,'' he said.
   Grace, chief executive officer of W.R. Grace &amp; Co., was chairman
of the President's Private Sector Survey on Cost Control, also known
as the Grace Commission, from 1982 until the commission reported to
Reagan in 1984.
   He is now co-chairman, with syndicated columnist Jack Anderson,
of Citizens Against Government Waste.
   Grace said the ``waste czar'' should have authority cutting
across governmental agencies, much like that of William Bennett,
appointed by Bush to coordinate the administration's war on drugs.
   Grace noted that the federal debt stood at $1.6 trillion when he
last spoke to the press club in early 1984, shortly after his
commission's report was presented.
   ``Now I'm back, five years later, and the federal debt stands at
$2.9 trillion, or nearly double what it was in 1984,'' he said.
   He said the waste czar should be given a mandate to carry out the
recommendations of his commission as well as cost-saving
recommendations of the congressional General Accounting Office and
government inspectors general.
   ``We don't need more taxes. We need less spending. We need less
waste. And that's why the American people need a waste czar to
protect their interests,'' he said.
   Grace also announced appointment of Alan L. Keyes, who was
assistant secretary of state for international organization affairs
in the Reagan administration, as president of Citizens Against
Government Waste.
</TEXT>
