<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BumSteer     09-21 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bum Steer,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Loses $28,000 Prize for Allegedly Using Same Steer in Two Competitions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl whose steer won first prize at the
Ohio State Fair must forfeit the $28,000 because the animal's hide
had been dyed, allegedly to mask that it had been entered under a
different name in another fair.
   The Ohio Expositions Commission, which operates the fair,
approved an agreement reached with the family of 17-year-old Susan
Shealy, whose steer named Hank won the prize in August. The family
admits to no wrongdoing, but the girl will not get her prize money
and must give up her first-place ribbon. She and her family also
were barred from competition for five years.
   ``The message is not to cheat at the livestock show at the Ohio
State Fair,'' said Jack Foust, general manager of the fair.
   Foust said officials could not prove suspicions that Hank had
also been shown under the name Carl at the Iroquois County Fair in
Illinois in July _ a violation of the rules. But, he said
investigators for the Ohio fair found that a white spot on Hank's
belly had been dyed black, which is also against the rules.
   Illinois officials did not have nose prints of Carl to compare
with those of Hank taken at the Ohio fair, Foust said. Carl was the
second-prize steer at the Illinois fair.
   Hank, a 1,245-pound Angus-cross steer, had been impounded at an
Ohio State University barn while investigators waited for his hair
to grow out. The Shealy family picked him up on Thursday.
   ``We're happy Ohio is strict, but I wish Illinois was as strict
as Ohio, because if they were we'd have nose prints and could prove
that they're two separate steers and we'd get you people off our
back,'' said a boy who identified himself only as a family member
when reached at the Shealy's home.
   The agreement was reached two weeks ago.
   Hank's credentials came into question when fair officials
received a tip from an Illinois extension agent on Aug. 19 that Hank
might be Carl, named reserve champion at the Iroquois County Fair in
Illionois on July 24.
   Investigators said black dye had been used to cover a swirl of
white hair on Hank's belly. A similar white patch can be seen in a
photograph of Carl.
   Fair rules prohibit misrepresentation of an animal's history or
ownership and forbid any alterations in an animal's natural
appearance. Under the rules of both fairs, an exhibitor also must
have owned the animal since Jan. 1 of the year in which it is shown.
   The agreement states that the Shealys exhibited Hank ``based upon
a misunderstanding created by advice provided a professional
groomer. ... Susan Shealy and the Shealy family believed that
certain coloring or shading of Hank the steer was fair and
appropriate to successfully present Hank the steer for competition.''
   The groomer was not identified.
   Foust said that, under state fair rules, there will be no grand
champion this year.
   The family of 12-year-old Jeremy Simmons, who exhibited Carl at
the Illinois fair, has denied any wrongdoing. They said Carl was
destroyed after the fair.
   Marvin Perzee, chairman of the Illinois fair, could not be
reached for comment Thursday. Telephone calls to him were not
answered.
   The $28,000 was the highest bid made for Hank at the state fair's
Sale of Champions on Aug. 14. Rod Link of Fremond-based Link
Carnivals bid the money.
   Link was on the road in Oklahoma and not available for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
