<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-21 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Kacey Cisyk walked around Ford Motor
Co.'s Dearborn assembly plant, no one recognized her. Perhaps if
she's just hummed a few bars ...
   Cisyk is the voice behind Ford's ``Have You Driven a Ford ...
Lately'' jingle that's been part of the company's advertising
campaign for eight years. The company estimates that her voice has
been heard 20 billion times in a variety of Ford advertisements
since 1981. Since then, she's also done commercials for Classic
Coke, Delta Airlines, American Airlines and Princess Cruises.
   The New York City woman, who got her first tour of an auto plant
Wednesday, said that after knocking on a lot of doors and making a
lot of demonstration tapes, she got a call from Ford and started
making commercials. A couple of months later, she was told that
someone at Ford named Donald Petersen wanted to meet her.
   ``Honestly, at that time I didn't know who he was,'' she said of
the executive who's now the company chairman. ``But we talked for
several hours about music. He's the only executive from any of the
companies I've done advertising for who has inquired about who's the
person behind the voice.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WINFIELD, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mules _ the uncelebrated offspring of a
donkey and a horse _ have no pride of ancestry nor hope of posterity.
   But the strong work animal of a bygone era will get some
recognition Saturday when this northwest Alabama town hosts the 15th
annual Mule Day.
   Proud mule owners from several states bring their animals to be
judged.
   There'll even be a reversal of historic farmland roles, with two
mules riding in a cart pulled by two strong men, a Mule Day charity
event.
   The late Curt Estes started Mule Day in 1975, leading a parade
with ``Old Kate.''
   ``He just came to a Chamber of Commerce meeting one day and
suggested we have a mule day,'' said the chamber's president, Danny
McDaniel. ``He said the mule is a dying breed, more or less, but had
been the backbone of the country for a number of years and that we
ought to honor the mule.
   ``The chamber picked it up and we've been doing it since then.''
   Mules now are kept ``mostly for show,'' McDaniel said. ``I don't
think anybody uses them much, although some are used to skid logs
out of woods in rough terrain.''
</TEXT>
