<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CableTV     09-21 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable TV,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable TV Better Than Critics Think, Cable Executive Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite its problems, cable television has a
lot to crow about, a cable executive said Thursday in urging his
colleagues to fight back against widespread ``cable-bashing.''
   National Cable Television Association President James Mooney,
saying ``there is no shortage of cable-bashing going on in the world
today,'' told a cable convention it was time for operators to
``stand up for cable and for what cable has achieved.''
   He said there were 51 million cable homes today, compared with 21
million in 1981, ``not because they have to be _ they're cable homes
because they want to be,'' thanks to an upsurge in first-run
programming featuring big-name stars since cable was deregulated in
1984.
   Mooney spoke to the Great Lakes Exposition cable convention in
Columbus, Ohio. A copy of his speech was released from NCTA offices
in Washington.
   Mooney reminded his audience that many cable programs are highly
praised by TV critics and that a recent Roper Organization poll
showed the public believes that cable cultural, children's, sports
and general entertainment programming is superior to that found on
broadcast TV.
   ``Is it any wonder then that most people _ voting with their
wallets _ think an average of $14.50 a month for over 30 channels of
basic cable is a good buy?'' he said.
   A General Accounting Office report to Congress last month said
the average cable bill, including premium services, went up 14
percent during the first 23 months after 1984 rate deregulation to
$24.68.
   Mooney said that increase was ``significant but hardly
unreasonable'' and that the price hikes had abated this year.
   ``According to the government's Consumer Price Index for this
year, cable bills from January through August went up only 1.4
percent, less than half the the overall CPI,'' Mooney said.
``Clearly, what happened during the first 23 months of deregulation
was an adjustment, and today we're back on track.''
   But a host of bills are pending in Congress that would reregulate
cable as lawmakers react to constituent complaints about poor cable
TV service and increased rates.
   In the face of such criticism, Mooney said it was important for
cable operators to ``let people know the value of what they're
getting'' and also to ``pay very serious attention ... to good
customer service.''
   He said the Cable Act required cable systems to dedicate more
channels for public, educational and governmental access and that
increases in cable franchising fees had fattened municipal coffers
by more than $3 billion since 1984.
   ``We've got to tell our story,'' Mooney said. ``We've changed the
way people spend their leisure hours; we've done for television in
15 years what the broadcasters couldn't do in 30. We've got a great
story to tell, and if we tell it effectively, a great future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
