<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany     09-21 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Declares Reform Group Illegal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The communist East German government declared a
newly formed pro-democracy group illegal on Thursday and accused the
organizers of ``anti-state policies'' and attempts to deceive the
public about its true aims.
   A statement issued by the Interior Ministry and carried by the
state ADN news agency formally rejected an application to legalize
the Neues Forum (New Forum) opposition group.
   Neues Forum was established two weeks ago by 30 East Germans
pushing reform of the hard-line government under ailing, 77-year-old
Erich Honecker.
   In a conflicting high-level signal, Deputy Culture Minister Klaus
Hoepcke demanded a state probe into why thousands of young East
Germans are leaving their homeland for the West.
   The Communist Party youth newspaper Junge Welt said Hoepcke told
students and teachers at an East Berlin art college that authorities
should investigate and correct the social problems prompting the
exodus.
   About 18,000 East Germans fled to the West through Hungary after
Budapest opened its border with Austria on Sept. 10 to those
refusing to return to East Germany.
   Legal emigration from East Germany to West Germany is also at
record levels, with more than 80,000 permitted to leave by early
September.
   West German officials earlier predicted about 100,000 East German
arrivals for 1989, but now say the number could reach 200,000.
   Bolstered by the widely publicized refugee tide, reformers
organized Neues Forum to press the leadership for change.
   But East German Communists are likely to be more resistant to
reforms than their Warsaw Pact allies in Hungary and Poland. Without
a communist government, the nation would have little cause to exist
as a state separate from West Germany.
   Hoepcke called for news media reforms and more dialogue between
the East German leadership and its citizens.
   On Wednesday, another prominent politician, Manfred Gerlach, had
questioned whether the leadership should rethink its positions in
view of the decision by so many ``children of the revolution'' to
abandon East Germany for the West.
   The main party daily Neues Deutschland has ignored suggestions
that reforms be considered.
   The ministry statement Thursday said Neues Forum's request for
legalization had been received, reviewed and rejected.
   ``The aims and concerns of the proposed organization contradict
the constitution of East Germany and present anti-state policies,''
it said. ``The signature drive for support of formation of the
organization was not allowed and is therefore illegal. It is an
attempt to deceive the citizens of East Germany about the true
intentions of the authors.''
   In Bonn, West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher told
reporters Thursday he will meet next week with East German Foreign
Minister Oskar Fischer to discuss the refugee problem and conditions
in East Germany.
   They will be in New York for the U.N. General Assembly session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
