<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Quake     09-21 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Quake,0134</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Measuring 4.7 Shakes Southeastern Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook southern Mexico
before dawn Thursday, the National Meteorological Service said.
There were no reports of damage or injuries.
   The meteorological service said the quake, which registered 4.7
on the Richter Scale, struck at 12:41 a.m. (2:41 a.m. EDT). It said
the epicenter was in the Pacific off Mexico and Guatemala.
   Local news services monitored in Mexico City carried brief
accounts of panic among residents who were rousted from their sleep.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake of magnitude 4 is capable of causing moderate
damage in populated areas, and one measuring 5 can cause
considerable damage.
</TEXT>
