<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1813EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-Georgia 1stLd-Writethru a0704 09-21 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Georgia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0704,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Flee as Hurricane Heads for Savannah</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADs with 16 grafs to UPDATE, add detail; PICKS UP 8th graf
prevs, `Others fled ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands fled Georgia's barrier islands and
parts of its coastline Thursday, but Hurricane Hugo's new northward
path offered hope that the state would be spared its full force.
   ``I think we escaped the brunt,'' said Ed Stelle, Glynn County
emergency operations spokesman, after the center of the storm was
200 miles east of Brunswick.
   The National Weather Service said the Georgia coast could expect
winds of 40 to 50 mph, near tropical storm strength but far short of
the fury closer to Hugo's center.
   Beryl Diamond of the Georgia Emergency Management Agency said
flooding was expected, ``but hopefully we're looking at less
damage.''
   Earlier, GEMA opened shelters and advised about 142,000 people,
more than 95,000 of them in Chatham County, to leave their homes.
   By mid-afternoon, Tybee Island on the north end of the coast and
St. Simons Island to the south were virtual ghost towns of
boarded-up buildings. The only open business on Tybee Island
appeared to be Nickie's Lounge, where a handful of holdouts gathered.
   As he sipped a drink, 63-year-old island resident Charlie Dowell
scoffed at the idea of heading for Savannah.
   ``I don't go in there even when the weather's good,'' he said.
   Authorities said they would cut off electricity to Tybee Island
at 6 p.m., and police prevented most vehicles from entering the
island.
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris declared a state of emergency in six
coastal counties.
   ``It is imperative that citizens heed the warnings to flee
low-lying areas and the barrier islands,'' Harris said in a
statement.
   Many didn't need much prompting. Hotels and motels were booked to
capacity in Savannah, not far up the Savannah River from the
northern barrier islands of Tybee and Skidaway, and further inland
at least as far as Statesboro and Hinesville.
   Most of Tybeee's 4,500 residents fled across a causeway to
Savannah, and many weren't stopping there. Bumper-to-bumper traffic
stretched at least 30 miles inland from Savannah. Many of the
vehicles were towing boats.
   But about 25 surfers lingered. One of them, Cannon Gould, said he
would be moving to his parents' house _ on higher ground than his
beach house, but still on the island.
   ``It's fun,'' Gould said of the surfing. ``I think tomorrow it
will be better.''
   Others fled low-lying areas on the mainland, especially people
living in mobile homes.
   Ann Owens of Brunswick, with two young daughters in tow, stocked
up on bottled water and canned goods at a supermarket. She said she
feared the hurricane would topple her mobile home.
   ``I'm not experienced with hurricanes, but after looking at it on
television I don't want to stand here and take my chances,'' Ms.
Owens said.
   She said she didn't know where she would go.
   Shelters were opened in Savannah, Brunswick and further inland.
The biggest ones were at Georgia Southern College in Statesboro,
with room for 15,500, and the Veterans Administration Medical Center
in Dublin, where officials said nearly 19,000 could be housed.
   Coastal school systems canceled class for the rest of the week.
   Forecasters expected the storm to turn north after striking land,
lessening the danger to historic structures in Savannah, which was
founded in 1733 as one of the nation's first planned communities.
   The barrier islands _ Tybee, Cumberland, St. Simons, Jekyll and
others _ also are rich in history. They hold wilderness areas and
luxury resorts, the graveyards of former slaves and the ruins of
once-prosperous rice and cotton plantations.
   Wild ponies roam Cumberland Island, while at the turn of the
century Jekyll was home to 20-room cottages inhabited by the likes
of the Rockefellers, Morgans and Vanderbilts.
</TEXT>
