<FIRST>r w AM-VetsLoans     09-21 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vets Loans,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Report Sees Problems in Veterans' Housing Loan Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterans' housing loan program is having
financial problems because of high foreclosures and may require more
aid than the Veterans Affairs Department has requested, according to
a government audit.
   The General Accounting Office audit covered the department's
financial statements for 1987 and '88, but made special note of VA's
housing loan program.
   ``The primary cause of the loan guaranty fund's increased need
for funding beyond that generated through normal operations was the
weakened financial condition of certain sectors of the economy,
particularly energy and agriculture,'' according to the report
released this week.
   The loan guaranty fund guarantees a portion of private sector
loans made to eligible veterans at special terms. About 13 million
veterans have taken advantage of VA housing programs.
   The fund largely paid its ways through the 1970s, but its
requirement for appropriations and money transfers ``has increased
significantly since 1980.''
   The fund required $900 million in transfers and appropriations in
1988, the GAO said.
   Congress and the VA are making several efforts to address the
issue, and VA says the problem is lessening because of a decline in
foreclosures.
   VA had 44,693 home loan foreclosures in fiscal 1987 and 48,963 in
fiscal 1988, the report said. Foreclosures totaled 38,721 in the
first 10 months of this fiscal year, said VA spokeswoman Donna St.
John.
   ``We expect further improvements ... and we expect the numbers to
continue to decrease,'' she said.
   VA says the fiscal year appropriation for the fund was $778
million, with $120 million of that in supplemental funds,.
   The GAO report says VA will need about $100 million in tranfers
from the direct loan fund plus about $453 million in additional
direct appropriations in fiscal 1990. The direct loan fund is a
separate fund used for direct mortgage loans to severely disabled
veterans.
   The report noted several possible influences that would change
VA's estimates:
   _A higher foreclosure rate than VA's projection.
   _The continued sale, without-recourse, of loans on properties
aquired by VA through defaults.
   When VA finances foreclosed property sales, it can package
several loans for sale to an investor. The sale with recourse
guarantees that VA will make good on any future default. Without
recourse means the investor cannot go against VA. The
without-recourse loans, though supposedly providing less liability,
provide less cash at time of sale, GAO says.
   A law will prevent VA from making without-recourse sales after
Sept. 30, but VA is proposing legislation to give it flexibility in
determining which types of loans to sell.
   _ A ``significant lapse'' of VA's authority to collect a 1
percent funding fee on loans. The last time there was such a lapse _
six weeks in 1988 _ VA lost $30 million, GAO said.
</TEXT>
