<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1817EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-Taxes 1stLd-Writethru a0716 09-21 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democratic Leaders Try to Get Rank-and-File in Line on Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 19th graf pvs, Rep. William, to CORRECT Gray's leadership
title. ^By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democratic leaders struggled Thursday to
sell party members on a deficit-reduction plan whose key element is
a multibillion-dollar tax increase for the nation's 600,000 richest
taxpayers.
   But there was no rush by rank-and-file Democrats to embrace the
proposal, aimed at staving off President Bush's plan to cut the tax
on capital gains. The Democratic alternative has a capital-gains
break of its own.
   ``This is an awful plan,'' Rep. Byron L. Dorgan, D-N.D., a member
of the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee, said of the proposal.
``George Bush wants to give big tax breaks to the rich, and we want
to give them to the near-rich.''
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., defended the plan, which
includes tax-deductible Individual Retirement Accounts for all
workers, as fair and sound.
   ``There is very substantial positive reaction to this proposal,''
he said.
   Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., who would be
expected to manage the Democratic alternative in the House, said
after a closed meeting with party whips: ``There's not too much
unity here.''
   Also attending that meeting was Democratic National Committee
Chairman Ron Brown, who recently cautioned party lawmakers against
repeatedly calling for tax increases in the face of Bush's
no-tax-increase pledge.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater complained that expanding
IRAs ``amounts to a tax increase.''
   ``If you institute a proposal that reduces revenue, the
government deficit gets larger and leaves you with even more
pressure for a tax increase,'' Fitzwater said.
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia told colleagues
that he was ``absolutely amazed that liberal Democrats would rush
into a tax-increase fight after the lessons of 1984 and 1988,'' when
Democratic presidential candidates portrayed as favoring higher
taxes were swamped.
   The Democrats' still-emerging plan is intended as a substitute
for the capital-gains tax cut that Republicans and six maverick
Democrats pushed through Ways and Means last week. The cut, which
Bush endorsed, is part of the committee's deficit-reduction plan.
   Democratic leaders note estimates that 80 percent of the benefit
of the capital-gains reduction would go to those with annual incomes
over $200,000. After briefly accelerating revenues, they contend, it
would deepen the budget deficit in 1992 and beyond.
   As an alternative, Democratic leaders proposed:
   _Expanding IRAs so all workers, regardless of income, could have
a deductible plan. The money could be withdrawn without penalty to
finance the down payment on a first home or for college education.
   _Eliminating a quirk in the 1986 tax overhaul in a way that would
raise taxes on the richest 600,000 couples and individuals. The
quirk requires some upper-middle-income Americans to pay a higher
rate of tax on part of their earnings than applies to the wealthiest
taxpayers.
   Under that law, for example, a single person with $75,000 taxable
income pays a top rate of 33 percent on a $10,000 pay raise or
investment windfall. But a $250,000-a-year earner pays only 28
percent tax on a similar increase in income.
   The Democratic plan would apply the 33 percent rate to all
taxable income above $44,900 for a single person and to all above
$74,850 for a couple.
   _Assuring that the 33 percent rate would not apply to any
capital-gains income. Thus, the maximum tax on capital gains, which
for some upper-middle-income people is 33 percent, would be cut to
28 percent.
   Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., who as House Majority Whip is
the Democrats' chief vote-counter, called the proposal ``a
continuation of the simplification of the tax code'' that would
encourage saving and investment.
   Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., said the plan gives the party a chance
to stand for something, rather than just oppose the capital-gains
cut. The capital-gains reduction has drawn little public response,
he said, but ``the mere mention of IRAs caused the phone to ring.''
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., calling any capital-gains cut a blow
against deficit reduction, said there would be ``a large group of us
that will vote against any kind of change.''
   ``I think it's a mistake for the Democratic Party to be
advocating an increase in taxes until the president has done that,''
said Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., chief sponsor of the capital-gains cut
that won Ways and Means approval.
</TEXT>
