<FIRST>u w AM-Marines-Border     09-21 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marines-Border,210</SECOND>
<UNK>Border Patrol Recruiting Marines</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Border Patrol is hoping to enlist the
help of the Marines to help intercept illegal aliens and drug
smugglers crossing the U.S.-Mexican border, an immigration official
said Thursday.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service, which oversees the
Border Patrol, is negotiating an agreement with the Marine Corps
that would allow the platoon of about 45 Marines to conduct
surveillance to help detect smugglers, said INS spokesman Duke
Austin.
   The Marines would operate radar and other equipment to help the
Border Patrol in stopping illegal aliens and drug traffickers,
Austin said.
   The Border Patrol and the Marine Corps are discussing what type
of equipment the Marines will use, he said.
   ``They would not have any arrest authority whatsoever,'' Austin
said. Federal law forbids use of regular military forces in civilian
law enforcement.
   The Marines will have to receive a special legal designation to
enable them to accompany the Border Patrol officers onto private
property, Austin said. U.S. law prohibits military personnel without
such a designation to enter private property. The Border Patrol is
empowered to patrol private property within 25 miles of U.S. borders.
   Austin declined to say what part of the southern border the
Marines would watch.
</TEXT>
