<FIRST>u a AM-CDC-HealthObjectives     09-21 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC-Health Objectives,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Health Service Plans New National Health Objectives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hold for release until 6 p.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEONARD PALLATS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Public Health Service said Thursday many of
its 1990 objectives for a healthier nation won't be met, but said
the agenda for the next decade calls for a longer life expectancy
and a reduction in infant mortality.
   Substantial progress can be made in the 1990s also in areas like
obesity, where little improvement was made in last 10 years, said
Dr. J. Michael McGinnis, director of the Office of Disease
Prevention and Health Promotion.
   ``We know more now about what the risk groups are,'' he said.
   Areas where goals for 1990 apparently will not be reached are
immunization of children before age 2 and flu vaccinations for
high-risk populations, the Atlanta-based national Centers for
Disease Control said in its Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report.
   The report referred to a draft of the Health Service's ``Year
2000 Objectives for the Nation,'' released Thursday.
   Tentative targets for the next decade include cutting the
percentage of adult smokers in half, to about 15 percent, and
reducing infant mortality from 10.4 infant deaths per thousand in
1986 to no more than seven. Other goals include raising life
expectancy from 74.9 years to at least 78 and increasing years of
healthy life to 65 years from an estimated 60 in 1987.
   ``Smoking is a good example,'' said McGinnis, a deputy assistant
secretary for health based in Washington, D.C. ``It's accountable
for 390,000 deaths a year. It's an example of where we can target
low income and minority populations, where the most difficult
challenges lie.''
   McGinnis said that for goals to be reached, every sector of
society must get involved.
   ``The most important component is the work of voluntary
organizations,'' he said. ``We have to have leadership at the state
and local levels.''
   In the area of infant mortality, McGinnis said: ``It has been
said that one of the truest measures of civilization is the care
society gives its children. We have had a 35 percent reduction in
infant mortality since the 1970s when the (1990) goal was set.''
   He said infant mortality is an area where ``progress has been
reasonably good, but we need to target areas where the population is
most vulnerable. We have not been able to close the gap between
blacks and whites and have missed the target for 1990 of reducing
the rate for blacks.''
   The service listed 21 areas for improvement by the year 2000.
   ``We ought to be able to anticipate progress in each of them,''
McGinnis said. ``The biggest challenge will be in the area of
violent and abusive behavior.''
   The 21 areas include: nutrition; physical activity and fitness;
tobacco, alcohol and other drugs; sexual behavior; violent and
abusive behavior; vitality and independence of older people;
environmental health; occupational safety and health; and
unintentional injuries.
   Others are maternal and infant health; immunization and
infectious diseases; AIDS; other sexually transmitted diseases;
cholesterol and high blood pressure; cancer; other chronic
disorders; oral health; mental and behavioral disorders; health
education and preventive services; and surveillance and data systems.
   ``We need to emphasize that these are national goals and not
federal goals,'' McGinnis said. ``Federalizing is not the way to do
this. We hope by laying out a common framework we'll be able to
focus our collective resources.''
   McGinnis said in a telephone interview that the planning process
was not complete and that comment was welcome.
</TEXT>
