<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-Yeltsin     09-21 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Yeltsin,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Light Moment in Serious Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's meeting with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze had at least one light moment,
Secretary of State James A. Baker III suggested Thursday: Soviet
maverick Boris Yeltsin's visit.
   But, a laughing Baker told reporters after the White House
session: ``There are some things that I'm not going to repeat.''
   Baker suggested that Yeltsin's well-publicized visit was brought
up indirectly by Schevardnadze.
   The Soviet Communist Party newspaper Pravda printed a public
apology Thursday for a report that said Yeltsin had gone on a
boozing and buying spree in the United States. Yeltsin had denounced
the report as ``garbage.''
   A senior administration official, who was present for at least
some of the Bush-Schvardnadze-Baker meeting, said that Yeltsin had
not been mentioned by name.
   But the U.S. official, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
quoted Schevardnadze as joking with Bush, ``You can't believe all
the things you hear are going on these days in the Soviet Union.''
   Yeltsin, a frequent critic of Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev,
met briefly with Bush last week as he toured the United States.
   Baker was asked whether the Yeltsin visit came up. ``It was
indirectly alluded to,'' he said. I think it was alluded to by the
other side. There are some things I'm not going to repeat out of
that meeting.''
