<FIRST>r w AM-Hugo-MilitaryBases     09-21 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Military Bases,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Bases Make Preparations for Hugo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon announced Thursday that 220 Air
Force and 177 Army aircraft had been flown out of the expected path
of Hurricane Hugo from bases in the Southeast.
   Spokesman Fred Hoffman said planes were moved from these bases:
Fort Stewart, Ga.; Fort Bragg, N.C.; Pope Air Force Base, N.C.;
Charleston Air Force Base, S.C.; Shaw Air Force Base, N.C.; and
Myrtle Beach Air Force Base, S.C.; McEntire Air National Guard Base,
N.C.
   The Air Force aircraft included C-141 transport planes, A-10
ground attack jets and F-4 and F-16 fighters. Most of the Army craft
were helicopters, officials said.
   The spokesman said 14 Navy ships had left the Navy base at
Charleston, S.C., to ride the storm out at sea. Four ships from the
Mayport, Fla., station were taken to more secure berths near
Jacksonville, Fla., while three other Navy ships have been told to
remain at sea, he said.
   Precautions such as securing equipment and preparation for
evacuation were taken at these bases, Hoffman said: Naval Air
Station, Jacksonville, Fla.; Naval Air Station, Oceana, Va.; Langley
Air Force Base, Va.; Cherry Point and New River Marine Corps Air
Stations, N.C.; Marine Corps Air Station, Beaufort, S.C.; Naval Air
Station, Cecil Field, Fla.
</TEXT>
