<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1826EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama     09-21 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Blacklists Panamanian Firms, Individuals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIA VICTORIA GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government announced Thursday
it was putting 14 Panamanian companies and individuals on a trade
blacklist, including a former presidential candidate supported by
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The blacklist prohibits any U.S. company from dealing with the
14, with a possible penalty of 10 years imprisonment or a $50,000
fine, or both.
   The move was announced in a press release by the U.S. Embassy in
Panama City and in a Treasury Department announcement published in
the Federal Register in Washington.
   It was part of a continuing campaign by the U.S. government to
force the ouster of Noriega, who was indicted by two U.S. federal
grand juries last year in Florida on drug trafficking charges.
   Noriega holds the real power in Panama through his command of the
Panamanian Defense Forces.
   Former opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara entered
the second day of a hunger strike to back his plea that Panamanians
refrain from gambling or playing the lottery in an effort to cut
government revenue.
   International observers say Endara won last May's elections by a
3-to-1 margin, but the Noriega-controlled government nullified that
vote and installed a provisional president.
   Carlos Duque, Endara's main opponent and a Noriega associate,
headed the list of individuals and companies residing in Panama that
are banned from doing business with U.S. firms.
   Many Panamanian companies do business with U.S. operations such
as the Panama Canal Commission and the U.S. Southern Command, which
has military installations in Panama with about 14,000 soldiers.
   The United States has moved all its personnel on base and
restricted off base movement.
   Washington imposed economic sanctions on the Panamanian
government early last year, freezing its assets in the United States
and barring U.S. companies from paying Panamanian taxes.
   Canal revenues due to go to Panama were also frozen.
   The Treasury Department blacklist is made up of associates or
friends of Noriega and will probably be expanded, said a U.S.
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Noriega denies the drug charges and says U.S. economic help to
the political opposition in Panama made fair elections impossible.
   He says moves against him are part of a U.S. plot to renege on
its obligations to turn the Panama Canal over to Panama at the end
of the century.
</TEXT>
