<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EPA-WasteFacility     09-21 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EPA-Waste Facility,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Acknowledges It Backed Off Action Against Polluter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Thursday it halted enforcement against a polluting Louisiana
waste-burning plant for more than two years because it didn't want
to damage a criminal investigation of the facility.
   The EPA action frustrated area parents whose children had a
higher-than-usual incidence of cancer, the House Government
Operations environment subcommittee was told.
   The enforcement halt also stymied state officials, who
aggressively sought civil penalties against the Marine Shale
Processors plant, near Morgan City, La. Louisiana officials found
air, water and hazardous waste violations at the plant.
   Edward E. Reich, acting assistant EPA administrator for
enforcement, said the agency declined to take action under an
agreement with the Justice Department, which believed that any civil
enforcement could lead to dismissal of criminal evidence and other
problems.
   Subcommittee Chairman Mike Synar, D-Okla., said there's something
``fundamentally wrong'' with a system that ``allows violations for
years to go unabated.''
   ``It's unfair to the community'' to say that a pending criminal
investigation means ``we cannot protect the safety of people,'' he
said.
   The criminal investigation ran from November 1986, when the EPA
and FBI searched the plant, to last July 24, when the company
pleaded guilty to three pollution violations _ one felony and two
misdemeanors _ and was fined $1 million.
   The violations involved hazardous waste storage, creating an
obstacle to navigation and allowing contaminated storm water to
enter a waterway.
   Reich said only an imminent health danger would have changed the
policy, and it didn't find one.
   But Rep. W. J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, D-La., who represents the
district where the plant is located, said there is a higher than
average rate of child cancer in the area and a state study has tried
to determine if the Marine Shale plant is responsible. He said there
is no conclusive evidence to implicate the facility.
   Marine Shale Processors is located along Bayou Boeuf, part of the
heavily traveled Gulf Intercoastal Waterway System. The facility
burns hazardous waste, producing a byproduct known as aggregate,
which is used as a substitute for gravel in road building.
   Robert C. Olde Jr., an attorney representing the company, said in
an interview ``There are no hazardous releases'' from the firm's
operation.
   He said the company was not responsible for child cancer in the
area, saying he suspected ``chemical companies that have been
dumping chemicals all around'' his region of Louisiana.
   ``We're not making hazardous waste. We're trying to clean up
hazardous waste,'' he said. ``We make a clean product.''
   State officials first discovered pollution violations beginning
in August 1985 but were asked by the EPA to place enforcement on
hold while the criminal investigation continued, according to
Elizabeth Megginson, assistant secretary of legal affairs for the
Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality. The state has has
proposed $5.5 million in penalties against the plant.
   Under prodding by Synar, Reich acknowledged that the agency only
did routine inspections during the criminal probe out of ``concern
that the criminal investigation not be interfered with...'' He
admitted the EPA lacked hard data on health hazards.
   ``I find that incredible. You've been telling people for three
years there's no imminent helath threat and you have nothing to back
that up,'' Synar said.
   Tauzin told the panel, ``I wish you could have seen the
frustration of the families'' who believe EPA ``let them down.'' He
said local residents from Morgan City were ``traumatized'' by the
lack of action because they couldn't get answers to ``why children
are dying of cancer.''
</TEXT>
