<FIRST>r a AM-HumanShield     09-21 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Human Shield,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Guilty of Using Toddler as Shield in Gun Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted Thursday of snatching a
toddler from his mother and using the child to shield himself from
gunfire during a wild battle between gangs fighting over drugs.
   The 3-year-old child, put on the stand by prosecutors last week
to show the jury his wounds, is recovering from a bullet that
pierced his chest on Feb. 1.
   Eric Casseus, 19, was convicted of assault, reckless endangerment
and endangering the welfare of a child. He faces five to 15 years in
prison when he is sentenced Oct. 10.
   ``This defendant's crime _ grabbing a little boy from his mother
and using him as a shield against flying bullets _ was depraved,''
said District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman. She said her office would
seek a stiff sentence.
   Casseus ``was controlled, but stunned'' by the verdict, defense
lawyer Elizabeth Sack Felber said. She said she would appeal the
verdict.
   Casseus maintains he was an innocent bystander mistakenly
identified by the child's mother, Modesta Alvarez.
   Ms. Alvarez was pushing one of her children in a baby carriage
and had her son, Gregory, walking at her side when the gunfire
erupted at a housing project in the East New York section of
Brooklyn.
   The mother took cover with the children between two parked cars.
But Casseus, one of eight youths involved in the gun fight, ran
toward them, grabbed Gregory and then held him up as a shield.
   He released Gregory only when a bullet went through the boy's
chest, penetrating his lungs and grazing his left arm as it exited.
Casseus was shot in the leg and identified by Ms. Alvarez at a
hospital where he and the boy were treated.
</TEXT>
