<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-Evacuees     09-21 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Evacuees,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Returning Tourists Tell of Looting After Hugo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN THOMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weary residents and tourists who arrived here
Thursday from St. Croix said they armed themselves with makeshift
weapons and watched in horror as looters rampaged through the
hurricane-ravaged island.
   ``The worst stories that you hear, you can believe them,'' said
John Curans of Washington, D.C., who was honeymooning with his
bride, Patty, when Hurricane Hugo struck.
   Currans was among 77 people evacuated from the popular tourist
retreat by the Coast Guard aboard a C-130 transport plane that flew
into Miami airport.
   In Grand Rapids, Mich., two brothers chartered a plane and
rescued their parents after receiving a desperate call from them in
St. Croix.
   ``My father managed to get to a boat yesterday and radioed my
brother and _ he only was on for a minute _ he said, `Do whatever
you can to get us out of here,' '' said Kim Sorrelle. ``My parents
were in fear for their lives.''
   ``My father said it's total anarchy,'' Sorrelle said. ``The
island is completely destroyed.''
   She said her parents, Bruce and Mary Langlois, had seen a
National Guardsman use his gun to break the lock of a jewelry store
for looting, and that people were firing rifles from rooftops.
   Sorrelle's two brothers, Joel and Bruce Langlois, flew to Miami
late Wednesday, where they chartered a small plane into St. Croix on
Thursday afternoon. Because their plane had eight seats, the
brothers also were bringing four other people back to Miami,
Sorrelle said.
   A Pan American Airlines emergency flight carrying some 250
passengers from St. Croix arrived Thursday at about 5 p.m.
   Drew Simpson of Toronto, Canada, told of forming a ``dynamic
team'' with several dozen others who took refuge in a hotel outside
of Christiansted.
   He said they used machetes to sharpen flag poles into spears and
blocked roads to the hotels with trees and debris because of fears
of potential violence.
   ``Once it became dark, you really got spooked,'' he said,
describing hearing weapons fire. But he and others said they were
not threatened by looters.
   During the long days, Simpson said his group tossed around a
coconut-turned-football and taught cribbage to some Louisiana
construction workers. He said they found a cistern with fresh water
and ate thawing food from a hotel freezer.
   National Guardsmen and St. Croix police joined in the looting
spree, Simpson said.
   ``We didn't go out after dark,'' said Jim Clark of Westport,
Conn. ``Whatever the storm didn't break, the looters broke. ``It
looked like a war zone.''
   Clark, a concert promoter, said he watched as authorities shot a
looter in the leg after several warning shots.
   Art Morales, a California police officer, said the lawlessness
after the hurricane Sunday was ``unbelievable.''
   Like Simpson's group, he and guests at their small hotel armed
themselves with plastic batons and organized security watches.
   Morales and his wife, Timi, of Tustin, Calif., were also on their
honeymoon.
   ``There's nothing left over there,'' Mrs. Morales said.
   Mrs. Morales said they carried only one small flight bag off the
island. They left the rest of the belongings behind, donating some
of their clothing to those in need.
   Simpson said he was looking forward to relaxing after fearing for
his life for the past few days.
   ``I want to get a nice cold beer, sit down and take it easy,'' he
said. ``I haven't slept for four days. And then find a flight back
to sunny Toronto.''
</TEXT>
