<FIRST>u i AM-Hugo-Crash     09-21 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Crash,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescue Helicopter Crashes Into Sea; 6 Dead, 3 Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo; AM-Hugo Aftermath</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French air force helicopter helping rescue efforts
in hurricane-battered Guadeloupe crashed into the sea, killing six
people and leaving three missing, officials said Thursday.
   The twin-engine Puma plunged into the Caribbean on Wednesday
night about a half-mile southeast of the outlying island of
Desirade, said officials in the capital, Point-a-Pitre.
   The helicopter was evacuating Bernard Berchel, who had suffered
head injuries when Hurricane Hugo hit on Sunday, officials said. The
other eight people aboard were Berchel's son, four medical workers,
and the helicopter's crew of three, the officials said.
   They said six bodies were recovered with three missing. Chances
were dim that searchers in helicopters and fishing boats would find
them alive, the officials said.
   The cause of the accident was unknown, but witnesses reported
hearing loud mechanical noises as the helicopter lifted off from
Desirade, about six miles east of Guadeloupe.
   The helicopter was part of ongoing rescue efforts involving about
3,000 French servicemen assisting civil authorities in coping with
the aftermath of Hugo.
