<FIRST>r a AM-LifeDisconnected     09-21 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Life Disconnected,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman on Life Support Dies When Electricity Disconnected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman on life support died after a utility
company disconnected power to her home instead of the house next
door, a company spokesman said Thursday.
   Northern Indiana Public Service Co. President Gary Neale said an
employee was sent to disconnect a customer's service in this Chicago
suburb because the bill had not been paid. However, the employee
accidentally turned off the power to the sick woman's home.
   Service was disconnected about 10 a.m. Tuesday, and a relative
notified the power company about a half hour later that power had
been cut off and that life-support equipment was in use, Neale said.
   ``A customer service representative working with the relative
immediately initiated a call to dispatch an employee to the home to
restore service,'' Neale said. Service was restored by 11:10 a.m.
   The woman, described as in her late 50s or early 60s, was taken
to Saint Margaret Hospital and Health Centers in Hammond, where she
died about 3 p.m.
   ``We have expressed our sincere regrets and condolences to the
customer's family and offered any assistance we can provide,'' Neale
said. He said the electric company would pay for any medical or
funeral expenses.
   ``The accidental disconnection of service was a tragic mistake
and we take responsibility for it,'' Neale said.
   The woman's name and medical condition were withheld at the
family's request.
   The woman was not on the company's life support registry, which
lists customers who use life support and medical treatment machines
in their homes.
   People on the registry get priority service whenever there is a
power outage. Their meters are tagged and service is never shut off,
Neale said.
   ``Because we had no record of the customer's life support
equipment, the electric meter was not tagged. Had it been tagged, it
would not have been disconnected,'' Neale said.
</TEXT>
