<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Fighers-Jammer     09-21 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fighers-Jammer,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sen. Pryor Charges Jammer Flawed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department's planned $4.8 billion
system for jamming enemy radar is ``seriously flawed'' and
production of the joint Navy and Air Force program should be put on
hold, a senator charged Thursday.
   ``I believe we have discovered a Pentagon embarrassment and a
potential waste of billions of dollars,'' said Sen. David Pryor,
D-Ark.
   The Airborne Self-Protection Jammer, under development since
1969, is used to deceive or jam enemy radar and will be used on Navy
and Air Force fighters, including the F-14, F-18, F-16 and AV-8B.
The Defense Department plans production of 2,369 jammers.
   To date, $577 million has been spent on research and development
of the system.
   Pryor, in a speech on the Senate floor, said unclassified Navy
documents quote testers as saying the system is ``marginally
operationally effective. In order to become potentially effective,
ASPJ effectiveness must be improved for all threats not meeting
reference criteria.''
   The senator complained that further testing on the system is not
planned until 1991 when more than 300 systems will have been
produced, or committed to production, at $2 million a copy.
   ``All arrows point to a multibillion dollar rip-off,'' Pryor said.
   In a letter to the U.S. Comptroller General Charles Bowsher,
Pryor asked that the General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, review the testing, costs and possible alternatives
to the jammer system.
   The Defense Department declined comment on the charges until it
has seen Pryor's comments.
</TEXT>
