<FIRST>u i AM-Quayle-Conservatives     09-21 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Conservatives,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle at Conservative Meeting in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle joined conservative party
leaders from around the world Thursday at a meeting expected to
focus on ways to help drives toward greater democracy in Eastern
Europe.
   Quayle came to Japan from a two-day trip to South Korea, where he
toured the Demilitarized Zone and denounced communist North Korea as
an ``astonishing dictatorial regime.''
   He shares the spotlight at the Tokyo meeting of the International
Democratic Union with Britain's Margaret Thatcher, who asked the
West to give stronger support to reforms initiated by Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev.
   British officials said Prime Minister Thatcher and Quayle had a
half-hour meeting and discussed East-West relations and Cambodia,
where Vietnamese troops began final withdrawal moves on Thursday.
   On Saturday, Quayle will visit U.S. military bases in Japan with
his wife, Marilyn. Next week, he holds talks with Prime Minister
Toshiki Kaifu and other Japanese leaders before traveling to the
Philippines and Malaysia.
   The International Democratic Union, founded in 1983, groups 26
right-of-center political parties, and holds leaders' meetings every
two years. Representatives from 17 nations are attending this
meeting, with Kaifu, head of Japan's long-governing, conservative
Liberal Democratic Party, acting as host.
   The three-day conference ends Saturday. Comments by IDU officials
and advance texts of speeches indicated a major theme would be moves
toward greater democracy in such East bloc countries as Poland and
Hungary.
   A senior U.S. administration official said that in Quayle's
keynote speech at a luncheon Friday, the vice president will urge
his fellow conservatives to help democratic forces in Central
America, as well as in Eastern Europe.
   ``In Central and Latin America, the crunch is really coming
now,'' said the official, briefing reporters on condition of
anonymity.
   Andrew Peacock, leader of Australia's opposition Liberal Party,
said in a speech prepared for delivery Friday that Eastern Europe
``is today at a watershed in its history (and) many states in the
Asia-Pacific region are also searching for a new strategy.''
   ``Who would have thought when we established the IDU in 1983 that
we would, six years on, be witnessing such changes. We must renew
ourselves in the battle of ideas and lead the agenda.''
   Peacock, who is to become IDU chairman, said the organization
should ``examine ways in which we can give practical assistance to
those sympathetic parties that are developing in Eastern Europe,
South America, Asia and the Pacific.''
   The outgoing chairman, Norwegian former Prime Minister Kaare
Willoch, told a news conference European conservatives have been
traveling in Eastern Europe to make contacts with pro-democracy
activists.
   ``I think this is very important, because through such contacts
it is possible to help those groups fighting and working for freedom
in Eastern Europe,'' he said.
   ``This is a very complicated issue, because we all want to help,
and we know that some sorts of help may be counterproductive. So
thorough study of what's going on and what can be done are very
useful.''
   Willoch said it was premature to think of having Eastern European
groups join the IDU, since forming non-communist political parties
was still difficult.
   Mrs. Thatcher flies to Moscow Friday to meet with Gorbachev. She
had lunch Thursday with Emperor Akihito.
   In comments to reporters, she praised Gorbachev as ``the most
bold and courageous leader the Soviet Union has had while it's been
under communism. What Mr. Gorbachev is attempting to do ... is in
the interests of liberty as a whole and in the interest of all other
nations who believe in the cause of democracy as well.
   ``We should do, therefore, everything we can to support this
great, historic movement.''
   Mrs. Thatcher noted a trend in favor of Western political and
economic views but cautioned against relaxing defenses. She
predicted a period of ``very great uncertainty'' in East-West
relations and cited unexpected developments in China as a strong
example.
</TEXT>
