<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-YoungHeroes     09-21 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Young Heroes,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Presents Medals to Young Heroes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday presented medals for
bravery to a 12-year-old girl who rescued a Japanese tourist from
the ocean in Hawaii and an 18-year-old boy who subdued a gunman at
his California high school.
   Bush, in a White House ceremony, also presented a Young Americans
Medal for Bravery posthumously to a 17-year-old who died rescuing
victims of a Texas bus accident.
   Angela Marie Campanoli, a seventh grader from Lacey, Wash., and
Ruben Ortega, a former student at San Gabriel High School in
Alhambra, Calif., received the medals.
   Angela was vacationing with her family at Maui, Hawaii, in
October when she dove into the surf and helped pull out a Japanese
woman being swept away by a strong current.
   Ortega subdued a student armed with an assault rifle who was
holding 70 students hostage at his high school April 26, 1988.
   Bush praised them for ``facing death and challenging eternity.''
   The president also presented a posthumous award to John and Rosie
Bankston, parents of John Clinton Bankston.
   John drowned July 17, 1987, while helping rescue others when a
church bus and a van carrying 43 people from a children's camp were
swept into the Guadalupe River in Kerr County, Texas.
   ``We know that a parent's grief is a special hardship,'' Bush
told the couple. ``But we hope that your grief is tempered now by
pride _ a pride in your hero, your son, John.''
   Bush also presented Young American Service Awards to:
   _John Philip Donovan, 18, of River Vale, N.J., for a variety of
community activities, including leading a Boy Scout troop with
disabled members and for leadership in a student group campaigning
against drunken driving.
   _Freddy Torres, 19, of East Boston, Mass., for volunteer work in
helping keep young people away from drugs and for his work in AIDS
prevention programs.
   _Sean Fox, 20, of Ethel, Wash., for starting a food bank for the
needy.
   _Vicki Lynn Urich, 19, of Alvin, Texas, for leading efforts to
clean up beaches along the Texas coast.
   ``These services may not be as dramatic as pulling someone from
the surf or subduing a gunman, but Freddy, John, Sean and Vicki know
something very profound: that it is in the daily accumulation of
small acts of kindness that can be improved; and often, that lives
can be saved,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
