<FIRST>u a AM-AgentIndicted 1stLd-Writethru a0679 09-21 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Indicted, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0679,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Federal Drug Agent, Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with detail from indictments, comments from
Ms. Terry, her lawyer; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has indicted a federal drug
agent, his wife and the owner of a construction company on charges
of conspiracy, tax evasion and laundering large amounts of cash,
officials said Thursday.
   The federal indictment named Drug Enforcement Administration
agent Dennis Harker; his wife, Mary Ann; and Susan K. Terry, who
owns SKT Construction in West Des Moines.
   Ms. Terry was one of five recipients of the ``women of enterprise
award'' sponsored by the U.S. Small Business Administration last
year, said William Kutmus, her lawyer. She's a business partner of
Roxanne Conlin, a former U.S. Attorney and Democratic gubernatorial
candidate.
   Kutmus said she is a widow with two young children whose husband
died in a construction accident. He called her ``a spokeswoman for
women in non-traditional positions.''
   ``I was shocked and outraged to learn that I was being
indicted,'' Ms. Terry said at a brief news conference.
   The 11-count indictment alleges that between 1986 and 1988 Harker
and his wife ``spent, invested and profited by cash transactions
exceeding $1 million.''
   Kutmus said he had advised Ms. Terry not to comment on the facts
of the case, but ``the charges themselves are ruinous to her and her
business.''
   Kutmus said he would enter an innocent plea at arraignments
scheduled for Oct. 2.
   ``She feels she is wholly innocent and that the charges are very
ridiculous,'' Kutmus said.
   Harker and Ms. Terry were charged with using a business they
established ``to launder substantial amounts of currency which
Harker had acquired and to funnel the cash through what would appear
to be legitimate business transactions and loans between the two
partners.''
   The indictment also says Harker loaned thousands of dollars in
cash to other drug agents and spent more than $30,000 in cash to buy
rare coins.
   There was no mention of drugs in the indictment, and U.S.
Attorney Joe Beck refused to elaborate on it.
   Harker, 42, is a supervisory agent for the DEA in Miami who
joined the agency in 1971, and previously was assigned to St. Louis
and Laredo, Texas, before coming to live in West Des Moines. He
could face 40 years in prison and $2 million in fines if convicted
on all the charges. The Harkers also could owe taxes and penalties.
   Mrs. Harker, 40, faces up to 20 years in prison and $1 million in
fines if convicted. Ms. Terry, 38, faces up to 30 years in jail and
fines of up to $1.5 million.
   The U.S. attorney's office said in a statement released Thursday
that the indictment was handed up Wednesday. It resulted from an
investigation that began in spring 1988 ``as a result of information
received by the FBI,'' the statement said.
   In the indictment, Harker was charged with one count of
conspiracy, three counts of tax evasion and four counts of using an
interstate facility to promote illegal activity _ presumably the
mailing of bundles of cash. His wife faces a conspiracy count and
three tax evasion charges.
   Ms. Terry faces three counts of arranging bank deposits to avoid
a federal law that requires banks to report cash deposits larger
than $10,000.
   The indictment details real estate transactions _ many in cash _
in Texas, Florida, California, Colorado and other locations.
Farmland, resort properties and homes were bought, the indictment
said.
   The Harkers filed returns for 1986 claiming taxable income of
$38,999, but it actually was more than $416,000, the indictment
charged. For 1987, the couple claimed just over $34,000 but it
really was nearly $680,000, the indictment charged.
   There was no mention of the source of the income in the
indictment or accompanying statement.
</TEXT>
