<FIRST>r a AM-HershLibelTrial     09-21 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hersh Libel Trial,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hersh Testifies at Own Libel Trial: I Tried to `Follow the Truth'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalist Seymour Hersh testified Thursday he was
trying to ``follow the truth'' when he wrote a book being challenged
by a former Indian prime minister in a $100-million libel suit.
   Morarji Desai, prime minister from 1977-79, claims Hersh defamed
him by saying he was a paid CIA informant and a valuable ``asset''
to the U.S. government during the administrations of Lyndon Johnson
and Richard Nixon.
   Hersh, called to the stand by lawyers for Desai, testified he had
made several errors in the first printing of ``The Price of Power,''
a book he wrote in 1983 about former U.S. Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger.
   The mistakes _ that Desai did not remain a cabinet member after
he resigned in 1969 but was a member of Parliament, the spelling of
Desai's first name, and the year Indira Gandhi returned to power _
were corrected in a second edition published a few months later. The
mistakes are not at issue in the libel case.
   ``I made a mistake,'' Hersh testified. ``The Indian ambassador
called me up, told me I had a mistake there.''
   When questioned by the plaintiff's attorney Francis Baumgart
about his accuracy in reporting and writing, Hersh said he was
attempting to be truthful.
   ``The notion is truth. I follow the truth, is what I'm trying to
do,'' he said.
   Hersh testified that six sources told him Desai worked as an
informant for the CIA, but acknowledged that he said in two 1983
interviews there were only two. He testified that one source among
the six told him Desai was paid $20,000 to be an informant.
   ``Did it occur to you this source may not be accurate,''
questioned plaintiff's attorney John O'Meara.
   ``Yes, it would to anybody,'' Hersh answered.
   But subsequent research ``butressed my view about certain
important facts ... and increased my confidence which, in fact, was
already high,'' Hersh testified.
   Under questioning, Hersh declined to reveal the name of another
source who was a foreign service officer in Washington, D.C., for
the Indian government. He said he submitted part of his manuscript
prior to publication to the source for verification of its accuracy.
   Earlier, plaintiff's attorney Cyriac Kappil told the court
Kissinger had been subpoenaed to testify, but his whereabouts were
not known.
   ``We'll make every effort to bring him in,'' Kappil said. ``On a
personal level, we prefer not to inconvenience Mr. Kissinger because
of his schedule.''
   Kappil said he would give Kissinger the opportunity to come in
voluntarily before asking the judge to enforce the subpoena. He also
said he was considering using a videotaped deposition made by
Kissinger if he was unsuccessful in procuring the former secretary
of state.
   Under U.S. libel law, Desai's attorneys must convince the
six-member jury that Hersh knowingly printed false, negligent or
malicious material.
   Hersh won the Pulitzer Prize for international reporting in 1970
for his articles exposing the My Lai massacre in Vietnam when he was
a reporter for the Dispatch News Service. He was also a reporter for
The Associated Press and for The New York Times. He left the
newspaper to pursue his own writing projects.
   He is working on a book on the Middle East.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
