<FIRST>u w AM-USAirCrash-Cushions     09-21 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir Crash-Cushions,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0812 to restore keyword line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Seat Cushions Sub As Life Preservers In USAir Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-USAir Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lacking life jackets and vests, flight
attendants had to throw seat cushions to passengers evacuated into
New York's East River after a USAir jetliner broke apart in an
aborted takeoff, a spokeswoman for the flight attendants union said
Thursday.
   Cindy Yeast of the Association of Flight Attendants said the
aircraft's cabin crew was unable to open all exits as the floor
buckled and the plane broke apart.
   Seat cushions on commercial aircraft are designed to float, with
enough buoyancy to support a person. Some flight attendants have
been critical of rules that require inflatable life vests only on
flights that spend appreciable time over major bodies of water, Ms.
Yeast said.
   As it became apparent the Boeing 737-400 carrying 61 people would
not stop safely, the attendants began yelling ``brace'' commands to
get passengers to grab their ankles and put their heads down to
reduce injuries, she said.
   ``The floor of the plane buckled up and down like a roller
coaster,'' Ms. Yeast said, based on information the union received
from flight attendants and others.
   Some passengers were sent down an inflatable slide into the
water. Others scrambled onto the aircraft's wing. Passengers in the
water hung on to floating timbers and other debris untio rescued.
   Later, Ms. Yeast said, flight attendants and the plane's captain
tried to use the slide as a raft _ as slides are designed to be used
in a pinch _ to reach several passengers caught in the rear of the
cabin as the plane sections filled with water. But the slide
deflated, apparently punctured by debris, she said.
   The interior of the plane was dark and shifting in the current,
Ms. Yeast said, as at least one passenger yelled for help from
behind a place where the floor had buckled all the way up to the
ceiling. That passenger and others were rescued, but two other
passengers died in the accident.
   Ms. Yeast said the pilot and last flight attendants stayed in the
aircraft trying to free passengers and left only after rescue
workers arrived and ordered them to evacuate.
   ``When the flight attendants realized passengers were going into
the water, they ripped of seat bottom cushions and began throwing
them out the door,'' she said.
   People were in the water for as long as 30 minutes, she said, and
some started singing as they awaited rescue.
   Ms. Yeast identified the flight attendants on the flight as Wayne
Reed, Jolynn Galmish, Susan Harrelson and Kelly Donovan, all based
in Baltimore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
