<FIRST>r i AM-SwissScandal     09-21 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swiss Scandal,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Former Justice Minister Charged With Passing Secrets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Justice Minister Elisabeth Kopp
was indicted on criminal charges of leaking official secrets to her
lawyer-husband during an inquiry into drug money laundering,
prosecutors announced Thursday.
   Special federal prosecutor Joseph-Daniel Piller said enough
evidence was uncovered in a preliminary investigation to bring
charges against Mrs. Kopp before Switzerland's supreme court, the
Federal Tribunal.
   Mrs. Kopp, indicted Wednesday, resigned in January amid reports
she gave her husband inside information. She is the only woman to
have served as a Swiss government minister.
   Two former subordinates were also charged with passing
confidential goverment information.
   Piller said in a statement an inquiry was dropped into whether
Mrs. Kopp's actions provided illegal benefits to her husband.
   Her troubles stem from a secret telephone call last October to
her husband, Hans W. Kopp, urging him to cut ties with a
Zurich-based company, Lebanese-controlled Shakarchi Trading AG.
   The company had come under scrutiny in Switzerland's biggest-ever
inquiry into the laundering of drug money.
   Kopp gave up his post as Shakarchi board vice president shortly
before prosecutors linked the company to the scandal, which came to
be called the ``Lebanon Connection.''
   The supreme court, responsible for handling cases involving
government ministers, now must rule whether to accept as
well-founded the charges against Mrs. Kopp.
   Mrs. Kopp indicated Thursday in a statement issued through her
spokesman that she will contest the charges.
   She has denied criminal wrongdoing while acknowledging she made a
``mistake.''
   She could face a prison term or fine if tried and convicted.
   No charges have been filed against Shakarchi, which has denied
involvement.
</TEXT>
