<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ethnic     09-21 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ethnic,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Report 292 Dead in 20 Months of Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's top policeman, Interior Minister
Vadim V. Bakatin, said 292 people were killed, 5,250 were wounded
and 360,000 had to flee their homes in ethnic violence since January
1988, Tass reported Thursday.
   Bakatin reported on the magnitude of the problem on Wednesday,
final day of a two-day meeting of the Communist Party Central
Committee devoted to trying to resolve the country's ethnic turmoil.
   He said thousands of homes were robbed or burned down in the past
20 months.
   It has been months since Soviet officials issued any nationwide
statistics on ethnic violence. Unofficial counts had put the number
of dead at slightly more than 200 and the number of refugees at
about 200,000. Bakatin did not break down the statistics by ethnic
groups.
   The Central Committee passed a policy statement calling for the
15 Soviet republics to take on more economic and political autonomy,
including ownership of all natural resources, but drew a line at
calls for independence.
   At the end of the long-delayed session, the Central Committee
accepted the retirement of Ukrainian party chief Vladimir V.
Shcherbitsky, former KGB chief Viktor M. Chebrikov and Viktor P.
Nikonov from the ruling Politburo.
   In a major power play, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev also
succeeded in promoting his new KGB chief, Vladimir A. Kryuchkov, and
economic planning chief Yuri D. Maslyukov.
   Ethnic activists interviewed by telephone on Thursday cheered the
three retirements, but said the development may not change official
attitudes toward their demands for sovereignty.
   ``Everybody thinks it was a good riddance,'' journalist Tarmu
Tammerk of the newspaper Kodumaa said of the reaction in the small
Baltic republic of Estonia.
   Shcherbitsky, 71, the last holdover from the 1964-82 era of
President Leonid I. Brezhnev, was regarded as one of the Politburo's
most conservative members. He kept a tight rein on the Ukraine for
17 years.
   He did not immediately resign as Ukrainian party chief, but that
is likely when a Central Committee meeting can be held in his
republic.
   Ukrainian activists said they did not know who might replace him,
and doubted whether his successor would pursue more moderate
policies.
   ``All the members of the Ukrainian Politburo are more or less
like Shcherbitsky, even the younger ones'' said Bogdan Gorin, a
leader of the Ukrainian Helsinki group, formed to monitor human
rights in the Soviet Union's second-largest republic.
   Gorin said in a telephone call from Lvov he was disappointed in
Gorbachev's speech setting out his ethnic policy. The speech smacked
of ``old stereotypes'' that regard the country as being under a
unified government rather than a federation of equal governments, he
said.
   ``He started for the first time to threaten those political
figures and organizations who are raising the issue of
independence,'' Gorin said.
   Gorbachev said Moscow would not tolerate anarchy in the Soviet
republics, or separatist ``demagogues.''
   Tonis Avikson, a spokesman for the Estonian People's Front, said
his political movement found little new and nothing to worry about
in Gorbachev's speech. For Estonians, the retirement of conservative
Politburo members was more important, he said.
   He said the activists particularly were pleased by Chebrikov's
retirement. Some people accused Chebrikov of knowing beforehand of
an attack by soldiers on a nationalist protest in the Georgia
republic. Twenty protesters were killed.
   Avikson noted that Maslyukov, who was promoted in the shake-up,
does not share the Baltic republics' enthusiasm for economic
self-management. He takes a particularly hard line on the idea of
transferring control of state-run enterprises from Moscow to the
republics, Avikson said.
   ``Maslyukov is not a big radical,'' he said. ``We have our
differences with him, but I think it's possible to talk to him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
