<DOCNO> AP890921-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     09-21 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leader Released from Jail, Accuses Government of Kidnap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The second-in-command of the Haitian
Communist Party was released Thursday after six days in jail and
accused the military government of trying to kidnap him.
   ``I escaped by the skin of my teeth. ... The three police who
broke into my courtyard wanted to kidnap me. They roughed up the
guard, but he didn't have a key, so they couldn't get into my house
without making noise,'' Max Bourjolly said after he and his guard
were released from the National Penitentiary.
   Bourjolly was arrested last Friday, several hours after his
security guard Jean Wilfried Herard had been taken into custody for
illegal possession of an Uzi submachine gun.
   ``The kidnapping failed, so they arrested me instead. If the
kidnapping had succeeded, I might have been killed,'' he said.
   Bourjolly admitted his guard did not have a permit for the
weapon, but said he had been ``targeted by the government because of
my opposition to its economic policy.''
   On Aug. 29, the government of Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril decreed a
series of tax measures that drew protests from politicians and labor
leaders. They claimed tariffs and tax hikes for small shopkeepers,
allegedly imposed by the IMF, would provoke social upheaval.
   Haiti, one of the poorest countries in the Western Hemisphere,
recently negotiated a $26.5 million standby loan with the IMF. It
owes the IMF $41 million.
   On Monday, bus horns honked and people beat on pots and pans in a
15-minute symbolic protest called by 18 organizations.
   The six political parties _ including the Haitian Communist Party
and the centrist parties of Louis Dejoie Jr. and Hubert De Ronceray
_ four labor unions and eight other groups threatened to call for a
general strike if the government did not rescind the measures.
   On Thursday, the Haitian Chamber of Commerce said the measures
``might lead to a social explosion.''
   In a news conference last month, Bourjolly was the first to
denounce government negotiations with the IMF.
   Bourjolly, 48, said he was well-treated during his week in jail,
although he claimed Herard was beaten.
   Bourjolly was arrested twice during the Duvalier regime, and was
jailed in the dreaded Fort Dimanche prison. He was released and
expelled from Haiti in 1977, in a general amnesty of political
prisoners, after 13 months in jail.
</TEXT>
