<HEAD>Duarte Reported Near Death, Bids Farewell to President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 7 grafs SUB for grafs 6-15, `Sources close ... their spouses'
to UPDATE with Duarte gets out of bed briefly, details. Picks up 16th graf
pvs, `Monsignor Fredy ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Napoleon Duarte on Thursday
bid farewell from his deathbed to his successor, President Alfredo
Cristiani, Duarte's doctor said.
   Jose Luis Saca, the former president's personal physician, said
Cristiani arrived early Thursday to see Duarte, who is dying of
liver cancer.
   Duarte's cancer was diagnosed in June 1988. His condition has
deteriorated rapidly the past two days, and his doctor says the end
is near.
   ``It seemed like the visit raised his spirits a bit,'' said Saca.
Even so, he said the 63-year-old Duarte ``is in a terminal state.''
   Cristiani arrived before journalists had taken up watch at
Duarte's home in the fashionable San Benito neighborhood, so what
the two men said to each other was not available.
   Saca said the cancer now ``has invaded the lungs.''
   The doctor said Duarte was asking for friends and colleagues to
be sent to his room for brief farewells.
   ``He is completely aware that he is dying,'' said Saca.
   Duarte's youngest child, Lorena, said her father was in a coma
for a time Thursday, but woke up, got out of bed, sat down in a
wheelchair and in ``a moment of lucidity'' asked that a favorite
grandson be brought to see him.
   Moments earlier, Raquel Cerezo, wife of Guatemalan President
Vinicio Cerezo, told reporters Duarte sat up and spoke with her _
``He was lucid. Even joking.''
   Duarte's daughter, Ines, told reporters earlier Thursday, ``His
condition is very serious. He could die today or tomorrow.''
   The former president's wife, Ines, all six of his children and
most of their spouses were at the house.
   Monsignor Fredy Delgado, Duarte's confessor, said Duarte received
last rites early Thursday. He said Duarte has taken communion every
day since his cancer was diagnosed last year.
   Saca said Duarte has given up the battle and was refusing
medication that could prolong his life.
   ``We're trying to make his death painless,'' Saca told reporters.
   Duarte's condition has been critical since Tuesday, when his
health badly deteriorated while he was attending a meeting of
regional Christian Democrats in Guatemala.
   Duarte was president for five years and was Washington's
staunchest ally in the Western Hemisphere. He handed over power to
Cristiani, of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, on June
1.
   Duarte underwent treatment last year at Washington's Walter Reed
Army Medical Center. Two-thirds of his cancerous stomach was removed
and chemotherapy was used to slow the disease's advance in his
kidneys.
   He had been receiving chemotherapy periodically until last month,
when he was judged too weak to endure more.
</TEXT>
