<FIRST>u w AM-Whites-Poll 1stLd-Writethru   09-21 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whites-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0832,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whites Polled On Attitudes About Blacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to restore dropped word ``said.''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most whites would not mind having a black
dinner guest, boss, doctor or neighbor, but well over half say they
don't want their sisters dating one, according to poll results
released Thursday.
   The poll conducted for USA Today said that 30 percent of whites
believe members of their race are prejudiced against blacks. An
earlier poll of blacks by the newspaper found that 26 percent of
blacks believe whites are prejudiced.
   The poll of whites, conducted Sept. 13-14, found that 75 percent
said they have had black guests in their home, 86 percent would have
no objection to having a black next-door neighbor, 86 percent would
not mind having a black doctor, and 89 percent had no problem with
the idea of a black boss.
   But 60 percent said they would not approve of their sisters
dating black men, and 69 percent objected to the idea giving jobs to
blacks to make up for past discrimination if it meant that equally
qualified white people were to be passed over.
   The poll, which contacted 806 white adults nationwide selected at
random, has a sampling error of plus of minus 3.5 percent. It was
conducted by the Gordon S. Black Corp.
   A poll of blacks was conducted for the newspaper in August.
   Results and analysis will appear in USA Today Friday editions,
the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
