<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-21 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Hugo Bears Down on Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo, packing 135 mph winds, headed for the mainland
United States on Thursday, bringing showers to much of the Southeast
and prompting a hurricane warning from Florida to North Carolina.
   Elsewhere around the nation, showers and thunderstorms were
widely scattered from the central Gulf Coast states through the
lower Ohio Valley to the middle Atlantic Coast states and southern
New England.
   A hurricane warning was in effect from Fernandina Beach, Fla., to
the Oregon inlet of North Carolina, including Pamlico Sound, with a
tropical storm warning and hurricane watch in effect from the oregon
inlet to Cape Henlopen, N.C., including the Albermarle Sound and
Chesapeake Bay.
   High wind warnings were in effect through Friday for the north
and south Midlands of South Carolina and south central sections of
Virginia.
   Storm surge flooding 12 to 17 feet above normal tide levels was
expected near and to the north of where the center of the hurricane
crosses the coast.
   A few tornadoes were likely in parts of South Carolina and North
Carolina, with rainfall amounts of 5 to 10 inches expected in the
path of the hurricane.
   Flash flood watches issued for South Carolina, North Carolina and
southeastern Georgia. Flash flood watches were posted for Friday for
Virginia, Maryland, Delaware, the eastern Panhandle of West
Virginia, and the District of Columbia.
   A coastal flood watch issued for Friday in much of the middle
Atlantic Coast. An urban and small stream flood watch was posted
through Friday evening for the lower Susquehanna Valley of
Pennsylvania.
   Showers and thunderstorms associated with Hugo were in South
Carolina, eastern Georgia and coastal North Carolina.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hours ending at 8 p.m. EDT
included 1{ inches at Savannah, Ga. 1 1-3 inches at Fort Stewart,
Ga., and nine-tenths of an inch at Beaufort, S.C.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended across eastern Nebraska
and central Kansas, as well as the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas.
   Cloudy skies and a few showers prevailed over the north central
United States, with fair skies predominant across the western third
of the country.
   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed across Florida, with high
temperatures in the lower 90s at many locations. Miami Beach's
93-degree high was a record for the date.
   Afternoon highs were mostly in the 80s across southeastern and
south central sections of the country, with readings in the 90s
reported in southern Texas and in the 80s and 90s in the
southwestern deserts.
   Clouds and rain helped keep temperatures unseasonably cool in the
north central United States, with afternoon readings only in the 50s
from northern Minnesota to the central High Plains.
   An arctic cold front with strong northwest winds is expected to
bring much colder weather to the north central states in time for
the official start of autumn Friday evening, with freezing
temperatures expected by Saturday morning.
</TEXT>
