<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0819 09-21 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0819,0885</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Report: Colombia's Justice Minister Resigns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with background, minister goes
to palace, other. Picks up graf 9 pvs, `Early Thursday ...' Minor editing
thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Minister Monica de Greiff, who
traveled to the United States to seek protection for judges under
death threats from Colombian drug lords, resigned Thursday after two
months on the job, a radio chain reported.
   She would be the sixth justice minister in three years to resign.
   Ms. de Greiff, 32, has been threatened with death since she
signed an extradition order that brought Eduardo Martinez Romero to
Atlanta on Sept. 6 to face U.S. charges that he was a drug money
launderer for the Medellin cartel.
   The report by Radio Caracol could not be confirmed late Thursday
at either the presidential palace or the Justice Ministry. Her
resignation has been rumored almost since she took the post July 16.
   She has been constantly surrounded by bodyguards and secret
police scout the routes to and from the ministry before she is
driven to her office. She is said to take a different route every
day.
   After the radio report, Ms. de Greiff, a lawyer and mother of a
3-year-old son, met Thursday night with President Virgilio Barco at
the palace.
   Radio Caracol, quoting unidentified sources, said she handed a
letter of resignation to the president, who offered her the
ambassadorial post in Portugal. She reportedly declined.
   She traveled to Washington in August amid reports she had
resigned. But she repeatedly denied those reports, one of which was
by Caracol.
   In Washington, she met with U.S. government officials and won a
pledge of $19 million to provide security for the hundreds of
Colombian judges under death threats from drug traffickers. At least
41 judges and 220 court officials have been killed by traffickers
the past 10 years.
   Reports say she left her son in the United States because he was
also threatened by death, as was her husband.
   Wearing a black and white checkered suit, her blonde hair pulled
back in braids and her face framed by heart-shaped amethyst
earrings, the young minister has become well-known in the Colombian
and U.S. news media.
   When she teamed up with Barco, 69, she vowed to wage a tough
fight against the cocaine cartels, winning admiration for her
courage worldwide.
   ``What Americans are seeing is this brave old man, this young
woman and her child fighting these criminals,'' drug czar William
Bennett said in an interview with Newsweek.
   Barco's government is presently in crisis following allegations
that senior government officials are being paid by drug cartels.
   Early Thursday, 10 bombs ripped through the offices of Colombia's
main political parties after senators urged the government to
publish names of officials suspected of taking bribes from drug
barons.
   Newspapers Thursday identified 25 politicians denied U.S. visas,
following days of rumors the United States has a blacklist of
Colombian officials on the payroll of drug traffickers.
   Nine bombs in Bogota went off shortly after 3 a.m. in nine
offices of the governing Liberal Party and opposition Conservative
Party. Another explosion damaged a savings and loan bank.
   Two people were injured in the blasts.
   There have been reports the government has a list of politicians,
journalists, army and police officials allegedly spying for drug
cartels. During debate this week, senators asked the government to
make the alleged list public, but President Barco has denied such a
list exists.
   A list was published in newspapers Thursday naming 25 legislators
and other politicians recently refused entry to the United States.
   Foreign Minister Julio Londono Paredes said he will ask
Washington for its blacklist.
   ``We want to establish the context in which the information was
made public,'' he told reporters.
   Three senators claimed Thursday they were denied visas for
political reasons, rather than links to drug traffickers.
   Liberal Party presidential candidate Alberto Santofimio Botero
accused the United States of retaliating for his criticism of its
intervention in Latin America.
   He claimed one reason he was denied a visa is that he met
Medellin cartel leader Pablo Escobar, the most wanted man in
Colombia, eight years ago at a political rally while both were
congressmen. But he said he ``barely knew him.''
   Sen. Juan Slebi, also of the Liberal Party, said: ``This is part
of the war the United States is waging in our country ... for us to
submit to them on extraditions. But I will never approve of the
extradition of Colombians to battle narco-traffickers.''
   The U.S. Embassy refused to comment on the list, citing the
Privacy Act. Embassy spokesman Pablo Urutia said he did not know if
those denied visas are suspected of links to drug merchants.
   Barco declared war on the cocaine cartels after the Aug. 18
assassination of leading presidential candidate Sen. Luis Carlos
Galan, a staunch enemy of drug dealers. Barco then decreed emergency
measures empowering him to bypass Congress to extradite Colombians
to the United States.
   Only Martinez Romero, accused of being the Medellin cartel's
financier, has been extradited. Top drug barons remain at large,
including Escobar.
</TEXT>
