<FIRST>r a AM-USAirCrash-Bridegroom     09-21 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir Crash-Bridegroom,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Can True Love Triumph Over a Plane Crash and a Hurricane?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-USAir Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The groom survived a plane crash, but the wedding
site was in the path of Hurricane Hugo, which had just rendered the
intended honeymoon resort a disaster area.
   ``I've had everything possible go wrong with this wedding so
far,'' said Tom Newberry, shortly after the crash of USAir Flight
5050. The plane skidded off a LaGuardia Airport runway into the
water late Wednesday. Two people died, and 59 survived.
   The flight was headed for Charlotte, N.C. Newberry was going to
Wilmington, N.C., on the coast 1{ hours north of Myrtle Beach.
   He's to be married there, to Connie Bland, on Saturday.
Unfortunately, Hurricane Hugo was expected to arrive about midnight
Thursday.
   The couple, both 27, then plan to take a honeymoon.
   ``You'd laugh if I told you (where),'' said Newberry. ``Virgin
Islands.''
   The Caribbean resort has been declared a disaster area. Hugo
passed through a string of islands Sunday and Monday, leveling
buildings, killing 26 people and leaving 50,000 homeless.
   Only once during the crash ordeal did Newberry, a New York City
banker, question if he'd make it.
   ``It's not a pleasant feeling,'' he said. ``There were problems
maneuvering the (police) boat and we got caught sort of sideways
near the boat. ... I was really mortified.''
   ``We just grabbed onto a big piece of floating wood and held on
for dear life,'' he said. ``I was just hoping and thinking that if
we just held onto the wood we'd be alright, surely some boat would
come get us. We were all screaming bloody murder at whoever was up
on the runway.''
   Those aboard knew what was coming about 30 seconds before the
crash, Newberry said.
   ``Everybody was kind of grim and just got down,'' he said.
``There was no indication given that there was going to be a crash.
Everybody just knew it.''
   Barely three hours later, Newberry seemed quite calm as he spoke
to reporters. He'd already called his fiancee twice.
   ``East River water doesn't taste real good,'' he recounted. ``My
shoes are at the bottom right now, along with all my clothing.''
   Newberry got off the plane via an emergency slide. Next he had to
figure out how to get to North Carolina. At last report, he was
planning to drive.
</TEXT>
