<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Deadbeats     09-21 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Deadbeats,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pay Up or Lose Your Vote, United Nations Tells Three Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Thursday the Dominican Republic, El Salvador and Equatorial
Guinea are so far behind in their dues they risk losing their vote
in the General Assembly.
   The U.N. Charter says any nation two years behind loses the right
to vote in the Assembly.
   The Assembly may let the country vote if it is satisfied that
failure to pay is due to circumstances beyond the country's control.
   The Dominican Republic, which is assessed about $224,000
annually, must come up with $223,600 to keep its voting rights, said
the U.N. chief's letter.
   El Salvador, assessed more than $74,000 annually, must pay
$12,057 and Equatorial Guinea, assessed the same, must pay $46,300
to keep their votes.
   When a small, impoverished nation has been unable to pay in the
past, its former colonial power or a major ally quietly paid the
dues.
   South Africa is also in arrears, but has refused to pay since the
General Assembly suspended its voting rights in 1974 as punishment
for its racial segregation policy. If its voting privileges were
restored, South Africa would have to pay more than $35 million to
regain its vote.
   Dues are based on a formula that largely relies on a nation's
gross national product.
   The United States still owes more than anyone. As of Aug. 31,
America was $278.8 million in arrears for past years and owes more
than $216 million for this year's dues, bringing the total close to
$500 million.
   The United States is assessed for one-fourth of the regular U.N.
budget, about $216 million a year.
   President Reagan's administration began withholding a large
portion of the U.S. dues starting in 1985 to spur reforms and budget
cuts at the world body. Reagan announced a year ago he was satisfied
with U.N. progress along these lines and authorized full payment of
U.S. dues and payment of all back dues on a six-year plan.
   Congressional committees refused to pay back dues this year,
citing constraints imposed by the U.S. federal budget deficit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
