<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRdp Adv22   09-21 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion Rdp, Adv 22,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Sept. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vision Interfaith Satellite Network, the year-old
venture of a consortium of 22 different faith groups, will expand
its hours and add new programs to its faith- and values-oriented
schedule beginning Oct. 9.
   ``We begin our second year with a renewal of our commitment to
offer a full range of religious programming,'' said Wil Bane, chief
executive of VISN, which was started Sept. 19, 1988, by the National
Interfaith Cable Coalition.
   VISN will expand its schedule to 18 hours, from 8 a.m. to 2 a.m.
Eastern.
   New programs include ``On The Line,'' a call-in show; ``The Joy
of Music,'' discussion and perfomance of classical and sacred music;
``Family Theater;'' ``Short Story Sampler;'' and ``Children's Video
Bible.''
   Two October specials are Zubin Mehta conducting the Israeli
Philharmonic at the ancient fortress Masada on Oct. 4 to salute the
Jewish New Year, and live coverage Oct. 16 of the ``World Food Day
National Conference'' in Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops
will give $7.2 million collected in parishes across the country to
213 self-help poverty groups as part of the Campaign for Human
Development.
   ``The funding of these projects, in which low-income people
organize to improve their lives, is firmly grounded in the social
teachings of the church and in America's traditional concern and
compassion for the poorest among us,'' said St. Louis Archbishop
John L. May, president of the national conference.
   Since its inception in 1970, the Campaign for Human Development
of the U.S. Catholic Council has funded more than 2,500
community-based self-help groups, said the Rev. Alfred LoPinto,
executive director. ``The issues that concern them most are decent
wages and benefits, quality education for their children, affordable
housing and drug-free communities.''
   The 1989 annual CHD collection in each of the nation's Catholic
parishes is the weekend of Nov. 18-19.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Jewish Committee, American Jewish
Congress and Anti-Defamation League will work together toward
reversing a ``deterioration'' in communication between the Jewish
community and Christian bodies.
   Citing a ``lack of sensitivity'' by both Christians and Jews to
important issues, the three organizations on Sept. 13 announced an
agreement to form the International Interreligious Entity.
   They called in a statement for review of Christian ``policies and
theological formulations'' seen by Jews as ``erosions of earlier
positions that were theologically more forthcoming and politically
more sensitive to Jewish concerns.'' They also said Jews need ``a
more effective instrumentality that can conduct a wide-ranging
dialogue with Christian counterparts.''
   ``We hope to advance constructive relations between us and
international Protestant, Catholic and Christian Orthodox bodies,''
they said.
   Leadership will be shared by Rabbi Leon Klenicki of the ADL,
Michael Wyschogrod of the Jewish Congress and Rabbi A. James Rudin
of the Jewish Committee, who will be the first chairman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
