<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv24   09-21 0922</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 24,0946</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Farmers Union, Yeutter Look at Farm Bill Differently</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Farmers Union and Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter would agree that profitable, family-owned
agriculture is a noble dream of American farmers.
   But the NFU has its own ideas how best to achieve mastery of the
agricultural dream machine, and Yeutter has a few of his own.
   They're not alone.
   Many other agricultural and commodity organizations, individuals,
analysts and special interest groups of all sorts are jockeying for
position as Congress works on the 1990 farm bill to replace the 1985
law.
   And Yeutter is not the only one who has a say in what the Bush
administration wants in the 1990 bill. Trade policy, budget
requirements, White House political nit-picking and dozens of other
factors litter the road ahead.
   Yeutter has said repeatedly that the administration doesn't have
its specific farm bill proposals ready for Congress but hopes to
outline those by the end of the year.
   But a look at some of NFU's legislative desires and a few of
Yeutter's ruminations might help a bit to clarify some of the
thinking as farm bill debate unfolds.
   Earlier this month, about 150 NFU members from 16 states, mainly
in the Midwest and Great Plains, participated in a two-day
``fly-in'' to Washington that included brisk lobbying treks to
Capitol Hill.
   The current farm law, the Food Security Act of 1985, covers a
multitude of programs, from conservation, credit and fish farming to
food stamps, rural development, research and trade.
   But the heart of the 1985 law _ and its predecessors for more
than half a century _ is the array of commodity programs that
provide federal price supports and related benefits for milk, sugar,
wool and major crops such as wheat, feed grains, cotton, rice and
soybeans.
   Among other things, the 1985 law gave the Agriculture Department
more discretionary authority in administering commodity programs,
including reductions in some of the price support benefits. A goal,
supported heartily by the Reagan administration, was to help make
U.S. products more competitive in foreign trade.
   Supporters of this approach say the 1985 law has been successful
in this regard. The NFU disagrees.
   ``Low farm prices are not the answer to our problems,'' says NFU
president Leland Swenson. ``Low prices are the problem.''
   In letters to members of Congress, Swenson and NFU vice president
Michael V. Dunn said farmers and consumers alike ``are all
interested in promoting the sustainability of our natural resources,
promoting the sustainability of our communities and ensuring a
stable, safe food supply.''
   The NFU is proposing a 10-point legislative list that features
``a voluntary supply management program'' based on using bushels or
other units of production instead of acres to control crop output.
   It also would encourage participation in the program by offering
farmers higher price support loan rates and higher target prices for
base levels of crop production. These are key items that the 1985
farm law allowed to be reduced.
   The NFU says a bushel-based system of supply management would
allow the government to ``better predict farm program costs and give
farmers income protection without sacrificing crop rotation
flexibility.''
   Yeutter also thinks there should be more flexibility for farmers
to rotate crops and have more management control.
   ``A primary objective for the price and income support elements
of the new farm bill should be to reduce the rigidity of present
programs,'' Yeutter told the American Soybean Association in July.
   One proposal, called the ``triple base'' plan, would limit crop
deficiency payments under the target price formula _ a subsidy
making up the difference between the market price and the target
price for a specific crop _ to the existing base acreage or a
portion of it. Farmers could then plant other crops on the remainder
without losing any of their acreage base.
   ``Flexibility is not just a back-door way to cut target prices,
as some have labeled it,'' Yeutter said. ``Even though budget
constraints must be addressed in all 1990 legislative proposals,
greater flexibility should and can be achieved because it is the
right thing to do.''
   The NFU wants Congress to include in the 1990 farm bill a
statement ``that would reaffirm policy designed to foster and
sustain the family farm system of agriculture.''
   It also would recognize that the objective ``is to ensure that
U.S. consumers have ample quantitites of domestically produced,
nutritious, safe and reasonably priced food and farm products. Such
an objective is long-term and non-negotiable.''
   One of the paragraphs, according to NFU, should declare that the
1990 farm bill ``must enhance, promote and be fully supportive of
the family farm structure'' and ``must avoid measures which would be
detrimental to family-scale operations.''
   At a White House news conference on Sept. 15, Yeutter was asked
about his role and the usual perception of farmers that the
secretary of agriculture is their champion.
   Yeutter said he intends to be ``a champion for the interests of
American agriculture'' and believes that he can be as vigorous and
effective as anyone who has ever held the job.
   ``But I'm not always the champion for some of the programs that
some ... would prefer to be enacted into law,'' he said. ``The
question is what does one champion? And I'm going to be the champion
of agricultural programs that I believe are in the best interest,
the best long-term interest of American agriculture.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
