<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-WalterMears Adv24   09-21 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv24,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun Sept 24 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Springtime Revisited for Foreign Policy Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not quite a replay although it comes close
_ President Bush is accused of timidly yielding the diplomatic
initiative to Moscow but insists he isn't going to be pressured into
hasty offers on arms control.
   When that script was written, only last May, Bush produced the
ending, silencing his critics with a proposal for conventional arms
cuts in Europe that upped the Soviet ante. Now the complaints are
about foot-dragging on strategic arms reductions.
   There's no hint that the administration has a September surprise
ready to match its springtime comeback. But the White House does
control the agenda, and that carries with it the power to undercut
Democratic attacks on Bush-style diplomacy.
   It happened before, less than four months ago, with the same cast
and similar dialogue. Bush got the last word and Democratic leaders
had to switch overnight from complaints to applause.
   In both cases, Soviet officials also criticized the
administration's diplomatic pace. This time, 10 days before his
Thursday meeting with Bush, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze said the administration had been restrained, indecisive
and timid in arms talks.
   The White House called that complaint mystifying.
   Senate Democratic Leader George Mitchell of Maine said Monday
that Bush ``must reach beyond the status quo thinking that appears
to dominate administration policy.''
   ``He must cast aside the ambivalence, the hesitation and the
timidity and adopt a more energetic and engaged policy toward the
Soviet Union and eastern Europe,'' Mitchell said. ``The
administration appears to have become complacent about the arms
control process, trusting that the Soviets will do the work and
provide the results.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III dismissed Mitchell's
comments as political talk. ``When the president of the United
States is rocking along with a 70 percent approval rating on his
handling of foreign policy, and I were the leader of the opposition
party, I might have something similar to say,'' he said.
   Baker and Shevardnardze are spending the weekend in Jackson Hole,
Wyo., discussing arms control and other U.S.-Soviet issues.
   ``Now, will we conclude a treaty in Wyoming? The answer to that
is obviously no,'' Baker said. ``I think if you will judge us at the
end of the day, hopefully next Sunday, that you will agree that
we've moved the process forward substantially across the full range
of our arms control agenda.''
   He said that includes strategic arms reductions, chemical
weapons, and long-stalled negotiations on nuclear testing. Baker
said he also hopes the Soviets will move toward acceptance of Bush's
proposal that both sides cut their conventional forces in Europe.
   That was the U.S. proposal that stilled the earlier round of
criticism, after months during which the Soviets seemed to be
out-maneuvering the new administration. Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev announced unilateral cuts in troops and weapons in the
East, scoring public relations points in western Europe while Bush
was silent, awaiting a review of U.S. policy.
   At home, the Democrats complained about the president's pace. But
Bush turned that around at the end of May, proposing conventional
arms cuts with solid allied support at the NATO summit in Brussels.
He said the offer put the United States on the offense and tested
Soviet intent. ``We may be at an important turning point in history,
one in which the security environment in Europe can be
transformed,'' Sen. Mitchell said at the time.
   Now the cycle is recurring, with a new agenda.
   Bush said anyone who thinks the administration is reluctant to
move forward on strategic arms talks is misreading his intent,
perhaps because the conventional arms proposal was his first
priority.
   ``We're working inside our own administration to have proposals
that I think will capture the imagination of the Soviet Union,''
Bush said Monday. He didn't say when.
   ``I think we have to be careful not to become frantic and rush
out here to negotiate a treaty on strategic arms, or anything else
for that matter, that would be non-ratifiable,'' Baker said. The
president said he was in no rush to stage a summit meeting with
Gorbachev.
   And he's calling the plays.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist for
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national
politics for more than 25 years.
