<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-21 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0818</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Corp., the nation's second
largest banking company, announced a major recapitalization plan
that includes adding $1.15 billion to its loan loss reserves to
cover shaky Third World debt and the immediate issuance of $500
million in new common stock.
   Chase, which also said Wednesday the plan would result in a loss
of more than $1 billion in the third quarter, is the second major
money-center bank this week to sharply boost its loan loss reserves.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy continued to grow late this summer
at a slow to moderate pace regionally, while inflation eased across
much of the nation, the Federal Reserve reports.
   Analysts said Wednesday's report indicates the Fed is continuing
to attain its goal of a ``soft-landing,'' easing inflationary
pressures without slowing the economy so much that it is driven into
a recession.
   In a survey of economic conditions around the country, the
central bank said most of its districts ``describe the growth of
economic activity as modest or slow, although regional variation in
activity is substantial.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales at chain stores have grown faster this year
in oil-patch states than elsewhere in the country, while West Coast
retailers have done better than their East Coast rivals, according
to a new report.
   Department stores and discounters in the El Paso, Texas,
metropolitan area posted the best sales gain for the first half of
1989 while Akron, Ohio, retailers suffered the worst decline, the
International Council of Shopping centers said in the report
released Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salary increases for U.S. workers will average 5.3
percent this year, indicating that spending power probably will lag
behind inflation for the second straight year, according to a new
survey.
   The survey of 1,260 businesses found that, after taxes, raises
will not match the increased prices of goods and services bought by
urban wage earners and clerical workers, which rose at an annualized
rate of 5.1 percent through August. The survey was released
Wednesday by the compensation consulting firm Hewitt Associates.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Automakers will phase out some
assembly and component plants during the 1990s as they adjust to a
shrinking vehicle market, a Chrysler Corp. executive said.
   None of the closings should hit Chrysler next year despite a
forecast of a 4 percent to 5 percent slump in new vehicle sales,
Robert Lutz, president of Chrysler Motors Corp., said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major airlines are mulling whether they should
match an American Airlines plan that would raise some
advance-purchase fares by more than 15 percent and double
cancellation penalties.
   The increases proposed by American, one of the largest carriers,
would take effect Sept. 29. They would follow a recent rise in a
type of discount fare popular with business travelers, reflecting an
effort by airlines to partly recoup revenue lost from bargains
offered this summer to fall vacationers.
   Spokesmen for competitors of Dallas-based American said Wednesday
those airlines were considering matching the increases but hadn't
decided.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government ordered $630,000 in fines
against Pan Am, alleging the airline failed to properly screen
passengers and cargo for the Boeing 747 blown up over Scotland last
year.
   The Federal Aviation Administration said nothing in its order
Wednesday alleged that the violations contributed to the Dec. 21
bombing that killed all 259 people aboard the jumbo jet and 11 on
the ground in Lockerbie.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has rejected a plea by Colombian
President Virgilio Barco for a one-year reinstatement of a
coffee-export quota system that benefitted Colombian farmers, the
White House said.
   Colombian coffee prices have fallen sharply since the 74-nation
International Coffee Agreement _ to which both the United States and
Colombia belonged _ collapsed in July after the United States pulled
out in a dispute over prices with coffee-producing nations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher
signed investment and tourism agreements and extended his stay to
negotiate a pact to persuade American companies to do business in
the new Poland.
   The proposed accord signed Wednesday would address the concerns
of U.S. companies considering investing in the economically and
politically volatile country, which has the East bloc's only
non-communist-led government.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices hovered in a narrow range Wednesday, as the Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 3.42 to 2,683.89.
   Bond prices suffered a broad setback.
   The dollar slumped as investors worried that West Germany might
raise its interest rates.
   Coffee futures prices surged and futures prices for energy,
precious metals, grains and pork all advanced, while cattle futures
prices declined.
</TEXT>
