<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-Italy     09-21 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Italy,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC, Italian Securities Agency Reach Mutual Assistance Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission and
Italy's securities market watchdog have announced a tentative mutal
assistance agreement.
   The announcement Wednesday came in a joint communique issued by
SEC Chairman David S. Ruder and Franco Piga, Chairman of the
Commissione Nazionale Per la Societa' e la Borsa (CONSOB).
   The communique covered only the exchange of information between
the two agencies.
   It was issued at the 14th Annual Conference of the International
Organization of Securities Commissions in Venice, which Ruder is
attending in one of his last official acts before stepping down at
the end of the month.
   The communique was described as ``an interim understanding''
between the two agencies to provide the fullest mutal assistance
permitted by law or regulation in their countries to exchange
information that will help each agency oversee markets, conduct
investigations and prosecute wrongdoers in their own jurisdictions.
   ``It is in the best interest of all nations to expose and
prosecute those who would abuse the integrity of the securities
markets,'' the two-page agreement said.
   It noted that Italian transactions in U.S. corporate securities
grew from about $269 million in 1985 to $1.8 billion in 1988.
Conversely, U.S. transactions in Italian corporate stock increased
from about $457 million to some $656 million over the same period.
   Both agencies ``contemplate that it will be a preliminary step to
a more expansive and comprehensive memorandum of understanding''
after they obtain the legal authority to do so, the communique said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
