<DOCNO> AP890921-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Ford-Europe Bjt   09-21 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ford-Europe, Bjt,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Automaker With Largest European Presence Wants More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co., the U.S. automaker with the
largest and longest presence in Europe, wants more.
   During the past two weeks, Ford has acknowledged it is holding
talks with the Swedish car and truck maker Saab-Scania AB and has
started acquiring up to 15 percent of Jaguar PLC of England.
   Ford may be positioning itself in the European luxury car market
as it gets ready for the evaporation of trade barriers among the 12
members of the European Community in 1992, analysts said Wednesday.
   ``I think they want to move their image a little up market in
Europe,'' analyst Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc.
said from New York. ``They really have been a mass-market producer
and never have been regarded as having some specialities.''
   And there's a benefit for Jaguar, too, said analyst Scott Merlis
of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``Ford could help Jaguar with product and technology,'' he said.
   Ford has declined to describe the nature of its talks with Saab.
Some analysts have speculated that Ford is interested in Saab's
heavy truck business, an area where Ford is weak in Europe.
   Ford's heritage in Europe dates back to the early years of this
century. Company founder Henry Ford started the automaker's European
connection in 1903 by exporting cars to England from the United
States. Five years later, Ford opened an office in France, the
company's first overseas branch.
   The continent has been important to Ford not only as a car and
truck market but as a base for its earnings. During the past two
years, profits from Ford's European operations have risen, to $1.46
billion last year, while North American earnings have fallen.
   Ford, which has a number of European assembly plants, isn't the
only U.S. automaker moving to increase its presence in Europe before
1992.
   Robert Lutz, president of Chrysler Motors Corp., the
vehicle-making arm of Chrysler Corp., said Wednesday that the No. 3
U.S. automaker has developed a network of 770 dealers in Europe. The
company recently introduced U.S-made versions of the Dodge Spirit
and Plymouth Acclaim to the European market, he added.
   He said Chrysler's European sales would reach 100,000 annually in
a few years. While that's far behind Ford's 1.7 million in European
car and truck sales last year, it marks a return to the European
market for Chrysler.
   Chrysler sold its European plants more than a decade ago when it
encountered financial trouble that led to a U.S. government bailout.
In February, it announced it would return to European production
through a joint venture with France's Renault to build a
sport-utility vehicle, now named the ``JJ,'' at plants yet to be
disclosed in Europe and the United States.
   General Motors Corp. sold 1.45 million vehicles in Europe last
year through its General Motors Europe subsidiary in Zurich,
Switzerland. GM began exporting U.S. cars to Europe in 1911 and
started making cars on the continent in the early 1920s. It now has
seven assembly and 30 component plants in Europe.
   GM owns all of Group Lotus PLC of Britain and has a European
joint truck venture with Isuzu Motors Ltd. of Japan.
   U.S. automakers must have assembly capabilities in Europe when
the trade barriers fall in about two years, Sudol said.
   ``It will be a fortress Europe and if they have no manufacturing
over there, they will have to jump over a high tariff wall,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890921-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares Bjt   09-21 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares, Bjt,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Airlines Ponder American's Proposed Fare Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's major airlines are pondering whether
they should match an American Airlines proposal that would raise
some discount fares by more than 15 percent and double cancellation
penalties.
   The increases proposed by American, one of the largest carriers,
would take effect Sept. 29. They would follow a recent rise in a
type of discount fare popular with business travelers, reflecting an
effort by airlines to partly recoup revenue lost from bargain fares
offered this summer to fall vacationers.
   Spokesmen for competitors of Dallas-based American said Wednesday
those airlines were considering matching the increases but hadn't
decided.
   ``I think there are several carriers out there that are inclined
to match,'' said Edward Starkman, an airline analyst at the
investment firm PaineWebber Inc.
   Under American's proposal, the popular ``MaxSaver'' cut-rate fare
often used by vacationers, which must be purchased 14 days in
advance, would be increased by $10 to $20 per round trip. A
``MaxSaver'' ticket on American between Dallas and Los Angeles, for
example, would go from $338 to $358 round trip. The ``MaxSaver''
tickets would remain non-refundable.
   In addition, American would raise fares on seven-day-advance
tickets by $30 to $60 round trip. The same Dallas-Los Angeles round
trip ticket bought seven days in advance would go from $378 to $438.
The penalty for changing or canceling a reservation would double to
50 percent of the ticket price.
   ``We're trying to get the yields up,'' said John Hotard, a
spokesman for American.
   An airline's yield, which reflects the average revenue from
passengers for each mile flown, is the lifeblood of the competitive
air transport industry.
   Starkman, like many industry analysts, is expecting little
improvement in yields overall for the rest of the year and into 1990.
   In mid-August, the airlines announced steep fare cuts for the
fall, extending summer travel bargains. They slashed round-trip
fares by as much as $160 to lure passengers in the historically weak
autumn season. Most fares to Europe were reduced by $100 into next
spring.
   Last week, in an effort to recover some of the losses, the
airlines boosted ``Supercoach'' one-way fares by about $20 for a
one-way ticket. These fares are favored by business fliers because
they have more lenient advance-purchase requirements than cheaper
discount fares and don't require a Saturday-night stay.
   Spokesmen for United Airlines, Continental Airlines, Delta Air
Lines, Northwest Airlines, USAir, Pan Am and Eastern Airlines said
Wednesday those airlines were studying American's proposal but
hadn't decided if they will match it.
   If they don't follow suit, it would be difficult for American to
raise the fares alone and remain competitive. But Hotard said the
airline planned to go ahead next week, in any case.
   American also announced Wednesday an increase in service from
Miami to become a larger competitor in that market, historically
dominated by Eastern, which has been hobbled by a prolonged strike.
   American's efforts to buy Eastern's Latin American route network
recently collapsed when Eastern decided not to sell it. But American
officials said the airline would seek government approval for routes
on its own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
