<DOCNO> AP890921-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChaseRecap Bjt   09-21 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chase Recap, Bjt,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chase Manhattan Raises Loan-Loss Reseves, Takes Big 3rd Qtr Hit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Co. has become the second major
U.S. bank this week to strengthen itself against problem Third World
debt, reflecting a growing realization among bankers that the money
lent years ago may never be fully repaid.
   In a major recapitalization plan announced Wednesday, Chase said
it would add $1.15 billion to its loan-loss reserves in the third
quarter and issue $500 million in new common stock. The move is
expected to result in a loss of more than $1 billion in the quarter.
   Manufacturers Hanover Corp. said Monday it would add $950 million
to its reserves and also issue up to $500 million in common stock.
But unlike Chase, it is raising much-needed capital by selling a
controlling interest in its financial services unit, CIT Group, and
a 4.9 percent equity stake to Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. of Japan,
the world's largest bank, for about $1.4 billion.
   Chase said it would have an after-tax charge totaling $1.26
billion in the third quarter, which would result in a net loss of
$1.12 billion for the period. Chase said it didn't have an earnings
estimate for the full year.
   For the first six months of 1989, Chase earned $269 million, or
$2.57 per share, vs. $501 million, or $5.53 a share, a year earlier.
   Included in Chase's after-tax charge is the $1.15 billion
addition for the loan-loss reserve, an $85 million charge reflecting
the lower value of problem real estate assets in Chase's Arizona
banking subsidiary and a $25 million charge relating to securities
trading activities.
   ``The basic core earnings of the bank have been going well but
they have been masked by these three drags,'' Chairman Willard C.
Butcher told a news conference.
   Butcher said the actions would eliminate a current after-tax
earnings drag of about $200 million a year. ``This will result in
Chase entering the 1990s with renewed financial strength and
enhanced earnings potential,'' he said.
   Chase, with $100 billion in assets, is the second largest U.S.
bank behind Citicorp, which has assets of more than $210 billion.
   The Chase announcement came after the close of trading Wednesday
on the New York Stock Exchange. Chase was up $1.62{ at $39.50 a
share before trading was halted late in the day.
   Some industry analysts predicted the market would act favorably
to Chase's actions.
   ``It's a big step for Chase,'' said James J. McDermott Jr. of
Keefe Bruyette &amp; Woods. ``By stepping up and taking a big hit and
getting the problem into a different zone, it's going to allow for
greater focus on its core earnings base.''
   With the big charge, Chase's total reserve for possible credit
losses at the end of the third quarter will be about $3.7 billion.
   This includes about $2.9 billion for loans to developing nations,
or about 46 percent of Chase's total $6.2 billion of medium- and
long-term loans to Third World countries. The ratio had been 26
percent.
   The major New York money center banks generally have loan loss
reserves equalling roughly a third of their outstanding Third World
loans. Chase's new reserve ratio will lead the pack.
   Major banks have been under increasing pressure lately to boost
their reserves to cover Third World debt in the aftermath of the
recent Mexico debt agreement and the plan by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady that emphasizes bank forgiveness of these accounts.
   ``This action resulted from our ongoing review of economic and
political conditions and our belief that recent developments,
including the Brady initiative, have resulted in increased pressure
on banks to reduce their claims ... and an increased resistance on
the part of some lesser developed nations to meet their contractual
obligations,'' Butcher said.
   He said the pressure ``has become apparent in the now-completed
Mexican negotiations and the negotiating positions announced by
other countries.''
   Chase's new stock issuance amounts to about 14 million shares. As
of June 30, Chase had 90.2 million common shares outstanding.
   The charge involving the Arizona subsidiary reflects the
continuing economic downturn in the Southwest. By establishing the
provision for the real estate loans and foreclosed property, Chase
anticipates improvement in the core earnings in that area. After-tax
losses for the first half of 1989 for that subsidiary totalled $30
million.
   Chase said it lost $25 million after taxes in the first half from
securities trading. It said the third-quarter charge reflected its
decision to get out of market-making in British government bonds and
U.S. mortgage-backed securities.
</TEXT>
