<FIRST>r f PM-PanAmFine 1stLd-Writethru f0020 09-21 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pan Am Fine, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0020,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Fined for Flight 103 Violations, But No Link to Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS date to Dec. 21 in graf 2, `The Federal ...' This also
moved on general news wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am is being fined $630,000 for alleged
security breaches mainly involving its flight that blew up over
Scotland, but federal aviation officials say the violations did not
lead to the bombing.
   The Federal Aviation Administration announced the fines involving
the Dec. 21 flight on Wednesday, giving the airline 30 days to pay
or appeal.
   The action came as the House of Representatives, prompted by the
Pan Am bombing and another apparent airliner bombing over Northern
Africa on Tuesday, passed a bill to bolster international aviation
security.
   The FAA fine covers charges of improper screening of passengers
and cargo boarding Flight 103 at West Germany's Frankfurt and
London's Heathrow airports, as well as five other European flights
within a few days after the bombing.
   The agency said its letter announcing the fines to Pan Am
``contained no allegations that any of the violations contributed to
the Flight 103 tragedy.'' All 259 people aboard the flight were
killed, as well as 11 on the ground in Lockerbie, Scotland.
   The FAA said all of the problems cited in the accusations have
been corrected.
   Pan Am chairman Thomas G. Plaskett called the alleged security
lapses ``administrative rather than substantive'' and also said they
did not contribute to the bombing.
   ``There is no evidence that any of the items noted in the ...
inspection by the FAA were in any way related to the bombing of our
aircraft last December,'' said Plaskett.
   Investigators are still trying to determine who planted plastic
explosives in a radio-cassette player found in debris from the
Boeing 747's cargo hold.
   The fines came as a team of U.S. investigators was setting out
for Niger in Northern Africa to look into the crash of a DC-10 en
route from N'Djamena, Chad, to Paris. The French airline UTA said a
bomb apparently downed its plane carrying 170 people.
   A spokesman for Pan Am Flight 103 victims' relatives, Bert
Ammerman, reacted to the fines by saying the government, not
airlines, should be responsible for aviation security. The relatives
have called for a federal investigation into the bombing.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., praised the FAA action, saying the fines
would ``serve notice not only on Pan Am but all other airlines that
we are going to be insistent on not only proper maintenance of the
aircraft but proper screening of passengers and baggage that goes on
airplanes today.''
   The House on Wednesday passed a bill that would have the
government pay $270 million for modern weapons-detection equipment
at many U.S. and foreign airports. The Transportation Department has
ordered airliners to install and pay for the devices.
   The legislation, approved 392-31, also would require for the
first time that commuter airlines screen passengers and luggage,
require airlines to acknowledge that they have received FAA warnings
of possible security threats, and urge agreements with other
countries to require detectable chemicals in plastic explosives.
   The FAA accused Pan Am of failing to properly check 31 passengers
at Heathrow airport and another five at Frankfurt, where the flight
to New York originated.
   Other violations were cited in the handling of passengers or
cargo for three other flights from London and two from Frankfurt
within three days after the bombing of the Boeing jumbo jet.
   In some cases in which passengers were identified for further
checks, hand-held metal detectors were used on their carry-on
luggage rather than having it opened for physical inspection as
required, the FAA said.
   Pan Am said in May that all passengers and cargo boarding Flight
103 were thoroughly inspected. The airline said the allegations of
security lapses ``appear to be based on a misunderstanding of Pan
Am's procedures.''
   A New York lawyer who handles aviation cases, James Stengel, said
that despite the FAA's failure to connect the lapses with the
bombing, the fine might still be used by plaintiffs as evidence in
support of suits against Pan Am. He said it could support
allegations that Pan Am was not meeting all of its security
responsibilities at the time of the incident.
   Another aviation lawyer, Keith Gerrard of Seattle, said he
thought the FAA fines would be excluded as prejudicial evidence in
liability cases since the government has not concluded that the
violations contributed to the bombing.
</TEXT>
