<DOCNO> AP890921-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1024EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     09-21 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0334</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today with a lift
from fresh evidence of a slowing economy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.70 to 2,689.59 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 561 up, 322 down and
546 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.60 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before the trading day began the Commerce Department reported
that the nation's gross national product grew at an annual rate of
2.5 percent, after adjustment for inflation, in the second quarter
of the year.
   That came as a mild surprise to analysts, who had generally been
expecting no change in the GNP reading from the 2.7 percent
estimated increase the department reported last month.
   The resulting suggestion of a slower-than-expected pace of
business activity prompted a slight decline in open-market interest
rates.
   And brokers said that, in turn, provided a measure of support for
stock prices.
   Chase Manhattan climbed ~ to 40] in active trading. Wall
Streeters generally upgraded their appraisals of the company's
earnings outlook following its announcement late Wednesday of large
writeoffs on its loans to lesser-developed nations.
   Other money-center bank stocks also rose on the news. Citicorp
added ~ to 31~; J.P. Morgan { to 40[; Bankers Trust New York { to
51\, and Bankamerica { to 33].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.43 to 192.88. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .22 at 379.36.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 3.42 to
2,683.89.
   Advancing issues just nosed out declines on the NYSE, with 708
up, 703 down and 538 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 136.64 million shares, against 141.61
million in the previous session.
