<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir-GM 1stLd-Writethru   09-21 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air-GM, 1st Ld-Writethru,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Texas Air Negotiating Sale of Reservation System</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE with no comments from companies; uppicks
4th graf pvs: Analysts estimated ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. is discussing the sale of its computer
reservation system to a General Motors Corp. unit in a deal that
could bring the troubled airline concern as much as $400 million,
according to a report published today.
   Unidentified sources cited in the Wall Street Journal confirmed
that negotiations with Electronic Data Systems Corp. were advanced
and that barring a snag, an agreement could be forged within several
weeks.
   A spokesman at Texas Air headquarters in Houston was said to be
unavailable for immediate comment on the Journal report while in
Dallas, EDS spokesman Roger Still said the company does not comment
on speculation.
   Analysts estimated that Texas Air's System One, the third-ranked
computer reservation system in the airline industry, could fetch
between $300 million and $400 million.
   Texas Air has given no indication of what it might do with the
proceeds from any sale.
   Texas Air is facing considerable difficulties. Frank Lorenzo, its
chairman, last month said he may sell an interest in Continental
Airlines, Texas Air's main operating unit. And its Eastern Airlines
unit is in bankruptcy proceedings.
   The Journal noted that the airline industry's computer
reservation system is undergoing its own restructuring. Earlier this
week, Delta Air Lines Inc. disclosed it was discussing merging its
reservation system with PARS, an operation jointly owned by Trans
World Airlines Inc. and NWA Inc.'s Northwest Airlines.
   And AMR Corp.'s Sabre reservation system has been seeking a
partner after the Justice Department quashed its plans to link up
with Delta's system.
   The paper also noted that a System One-EDS combination would mark
the first non-airline owner of a computer reservation system.
   System One has a market share of about 19 percent, according to
the Journal, roughly half that of AMR's Sabre system.
   In addition to the work it performs for GM, EDS is involved in
health insurance, government and financial institution data
processing.
</TEXT>
