<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-21 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain on Frost Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forecasts for freezing temperatures this weekend
in the Midwest gave grain and soybean futures a boost in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Some forecasters expect frost in Minnesota and northern Iowa
Saturday night, with the cold moving into the eastern Corn Belt
Sunday night.
   If frost occurs, it would be about a week ahead of normal.
Analysts said the greatest threat would be to soybeans in Indiana
and Ohio, where crops were planted late due to heavy spring rains.
   In the western Corn Belt, where the crops are more mature, ``I
don't think you're talking about yield losses, I think you're
talking about quality problems,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Frost could slow the natural drying of mature corn and lock some
chlorophyll into not-quite-ripe soybeans, causing some
discoloration, Gustafson said.
   In early trading, wheat futures were \ cent lower to { cent
higher with the contract for delivery in December at $3.91{ a
bushel; corn futures were { cent to 1 cent higher with December at
$2.29{ a bushel; oat futures were unchanged to 1 cent higher with
December at $1.40{ a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents to 5{ cents
higher with November at $5.78 a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mostly higher while pork-belly futures
were mostly lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange after bellies soared the 2-cents-a-pound daily limit on
Wednesday.
   Live cattle futures were .05 cent to .40 cent higher with October
at 71.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent
higher with September at 83.30 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent
lower to .35 cent higher with October at 42.12 cents a pound;
frozies were .75 cent lower to 1.40 cents higher with February at 49
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures retreated Wednesday while pork futures advanced.
</TEXT>
