<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1256EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL     09-21 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tender Offer for UAL To Begin Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The total cost of an employee-management group's
leveraged buyout of UAL Corp. would be $9.45 billion, according to a
merger agreement filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   The $300-a-share tender offer for the parent company of United
Airlines was to begin today.
   According to the agreement filed with the SEC, the buyout group
will require $6.8 billion to purchase UAL's 22.65 million fully
diluted shares. It said the group may refinance $950 million in
existing UAL debt, which would leave $512 million in long-term debt
and $411 million in capital leases outstanding.
   In addition, there are fees and a $1.3 billion credit facility
for working capital included in the total buyout cost.
   In addition to management personnel and United pilots, the buyout
group includes British Airways PLC as a minority partner.
   The group plans to finance the transaction with $750 million from
British Airways; $200 million in voluntary pension contributions
from the pilots; $1.3 billion from UAL cash reserves and $7.2
billion in bank loans.
   The buyout would give UAL nonmanagement employees 75 percent
ownership.
   Around midday on the New York Stock Exchange, UAL was up $2.12{
to $287.12{.
</TEXT>
