<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Monsanto-Mobil     09-21 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Monsanto-Mobil,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobil Ordered To Pay $21 Million in Contract Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury has awarded Monsanto Co. more
than $21 million for an alleged breach of contract by Mobil Oil
Corp. to buy pure phosphorus produced at plants in Idaho and
Tennessee.
   Monsanto contended Mobil violated a five-year agreement to buy
the phosphorus and other products, including detergents and
lubrication additives, at Mobil plants in suburban Cincinnati and
Charleston, S.C.
   A six-member jury in U.S. District Court deliberated two hours
Wednesday before awarding $21,126,557 to Monsanto.
   Mobil contended during the trial, which began Sept. 11, that its
sale of the Ohio and South Carolina plants to Albright &amp; Wilson Inc.
in April 1985 negated the contract with Monsanto.
   ``We obviously disagree with the verdict. It's a complex
commercial case,'' said Richard A. Ahrens, a lawyer for Mobil. He
said Mobil would ask the judge to overturn the verdict or order a
new trial.
   Monsanto produced elemental phosphorus _ the pure, uncombined
chemical element _ at plants in Soda Springs, Idaho, and Columbia,
Tenn.
</TEXT>
