<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-21 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished higher against all major
European currencies in cautious trading Thursday.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said trading remained in a narrow range
with players unwilling to take aggressive positions ahead of this
weekend's meeting in Washington of the Group of Seven finance
ministers and central bankers.
   Traders said they weren't expecting any new initiatives out of
the weekend meeting, but they were being cautious in case there was
a communique expressing concern over an excessive rise in the dollar.
   Recent statements by Japanese and West German officials indicated
some concern about the dollar's strength.
   The G-7 nations are the United States, Japan, West Germany,
France, Britain, Italy and Canada.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.25 yen to a closing 145.00 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a higher rate of 145.10 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5805 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5820 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday:
1.9435 West German marks, up from 1.9400; 1.6830 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6800; 6.5710 French francs, up from 6.5585; 2.1920 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1890; 1,401.00 Italian lire, up from 1,399.50;
1.1842 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1824.
   Gold held steady in London at a late bid price of $363.25 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Wednesday's late bid.
   In Zurich, gold also was unchanged at a bid $363.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.69 to close at a bid $364.11.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.14 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $5.13.
</TEXT>
