<FIRST>r f AM-IBM-Baxter     09-21 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-Baxter,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM, Baxter To Form Joint Venture in Health-Care Computing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. and Baxter
Healthcare Corp. said Thursday they planned to form an 800-employee
company that provides computers, software and services to hospitals
and other health-care providers.
   IBM said this was the first time it had bought into a company
providing computing services to a particular industry.
   While the companies will equally share ownership of the company,
nearly all the employees will come from Baxter's Systems and Annson
Systems divisions. The companies declined to disclose terms of the
deal or to forecast revenue.
   IBM said it is has opened centers in Washington, D.C., and Dallas
and will open others in Los Angeles and Chicago to market the
products and services of the joint venture.
   The venture will be based in Hauppauge, N.Y. IBM has headquarters
in Armonk, N.Y., while Baxter is based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
