   Fresh evidence of a slowing economy helped propel
stock prices to a moderate gain today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.55 to 2,692.44 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 9 to 7 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 733 up, 563 down and
585 unchanged.
   Before the trading day began the Commerce Department reported
that the nation's gross national product grew at an annual rate of
2.5 percent, after adjustment for inflation, in the second quarter
of the year.
   That came as a mild surprise to analysts, who had generally been
expecting no change in the GNP reading from the 2.7 percent
estimated increase the department reported last month.
   The resulting suggestion of a slower-than-expected pace of
business activity prompted a slight decline in open-market interest
rates.
   And brokers said that, in turn, provided a measure of support for
stock prices.
   Chase Manhattan climbed | to 40[ in active trading. Wall
Streeters generally upgraded their appraisals of the company's
earnings outlook following its announcement late Wednesday of large
writeoffs on its loans to lesser-developed nations.
   Other money-center bank stocks also rose on the news. Citicorp
added ~ to 31~; J.P. Morgan { to 40[; Chemical Banking } to 39, and
Bankamerica ] to 33\.
   Telerate jumped 5\ to 20]. Dow Jones &amp; Co. proposed to acquire
the approximately one-third of Telerate it doesn't already own for
$18 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.63 to 193.08. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .83 at 379.97.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 101.87 million shares with two
hours to go.
