<DOCNO> AP890921-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1446EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BAT Bjt   09-21 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BAT, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoylake Gets British Government Clearance For BAT Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoylake Investments Ltd. won an important second
round in its takeover battle for BAT Industries PLC Thursday when
the British government cleared the group's $21 billion hostile bid
for the conglomerate.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said he would not refer Hoylake's
offer to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, upholding the
Conservative government's free-market policies and sweeping aside
concerns about the advent of giant, highly leveraged, junk
bond-financed buyouts in Britain.
   However, Ridley said, the matter could be reconsidered if there
were a material change in the terms of the bid for BAT or other
``material facts.''
   The decision followed last week's ruling by the Panel on
Takeovers and Mergers giving Hoylake _ which is led by financier Sir
James Goldsmith _ more time for its bid. The offer has been delayed
by regulatory hurdles in the United States.
   BAT stock rose 22 cents to close at $13.07 a share Thursday on
London's Stock Exchange.
   Hoylake is offering $13.87 in securities for each BAT share.
   BAT noted Ridley's decision ``with regret,'' but said it was
pleased the trade secretary left open the possibility of referring
the bid to the mergers commission if its terms were changed.
   BAT said a referral to the monopolies commission would have given
the British government a chance to establish a policy on takeovers
that rely heavily on risky junk bonds.
   Junk bonds have a ``negative potential for the markets, for
companies and for small shareholders,'' BAT said.
   Securities analysts have said Hoylake would have to raise its
offer and include cash to succeed.
   Hoylake wants to retain BAT's tobacco interests and sell its
retailing, financial services and paper and packaging operations.
   BAT Chairman Patrick Sheehy said his company would try to defeat
the Hoylake bid on its merits. He said BAT was determined to ``take
suitable measures to provide a sustainable long-term increase'' in
shareholder value.
   Because Hoylake was formed by Goldsmith, British merchant banker
Jacob Rothschild and Australian entrepreneur Kerry Packer
specifically to make the BAT bid, it was unlikely the offer would be
referred to the monopolies commission on competition grounds, a
common basis for review.
   The bid's opponents have argued for an investigation into whether
the offer is in the public interest, contending that such
highly-leveraged takeovers could strap British companies with debt,
cut down on their investments and distract executives from
day-to-day management.
   Ridley said he based his decision on a recommendation by Director
General of Trading Sir Gordon Borrie, who advised there were no
competitive problems raised by the buyout offer.
   ``In the first instance it must be for the shareholders to
decide,'' Ridley said in an interview on British Broadcasting Corp.
radio. ``I would not wish to interfere in a purely market
situation.''
   Bryan Gould, an opposition Labor lawmaker who serves as his
party's spokesman on trade matters, said, ``This is a triumph of
narrow ideology over the wider interests of British industry.''
   Hoylake requested that the takeover panel grant it a lengthier
bid timetable because of the need to secure approval from U.S. state
insurance commissioners for a change in ownership of BAT's Farmers
Insurance Group Inc., which is based in Los Angeles.
   Insurance regulators in nine states have undertaken reviews of
the deal.
   Hoylake wants to sell Farmers to the French insurance company Axa
Midi Assurances. Goldsmith's group is hoping the move will speed up
U.S. approval for their bid.
   BAT immediately appealed the takeover panel's decision allowing
Hoylake to renew its offer for BAT within 21 days of overcoming its
regulatory obstacles in the United States.
   Normally in Britain, a bidder is given 90 days to win a majority
stake in its target. If the bidder fails, it must wait at least a
year before bidding again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890921-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC Bjt   09-21 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, Bjt,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Will Hold Meeting on Contentious Quota Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers will meet this weekend to
tackle the troublesome issue of how to fairly divvy up
oil-production shares among the 13 nations. Some want much more than
their current allotment.
   But analysts were skeptical the eight-member committee of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would do much more
than review proposals for reworking output quotas assigned each
member.
   Fergus MacLeod, analyst at the investment firm of Barclays de
Zoete Wedd in London, said he expected ``not very much'' to come out
of the meeting that begins Saturday in Geneva, Switzerland.
   Failure to reach any meaningful conclusion on current production,
however, could be ``very dangerous'' because countries might widen
their oil taps and increase their already high production level, he
said.
   Another analyst, Nick Antill, of London's County NatWest,
predicted the ministers would ``leave the fighting until November''
when all 13 ministers are scheduled to gather for a key year-end
meeting in Vienna.
   ``They will discuss (quotas) but they will take no decision,''
said Pierre Terzian, editor of the oil publication Petrostrategies
in Paris.
   The ministers are at odds over how the cartel divides up and sets
the ceilings for each country's crude output.
   Some countries, like Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates, want a
larger share of the production pie. Both have been ignoring their
quotas in recent months and pumping at higher levels.
   Moreover, Iraq just opened the second phase of a twin pipeline
across Saudi Arabia, which will add more than a million barrels a
day to its export capacity. The move increases the likelihood it
will want a higher quota.
   Analysts estimate OPEC's current production at close to 22
million barrels a day, well over the cap of 19.5 million set in June
for the last six months of the year.
   Prices have been lower than earlier in the year. A basket of
seven crudes monitored by OPEC was priced at $17.04 a barrel last
week, under the cartel's target of $18.
   West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. oil, has
been trading in the range of $19.50 to $20 for a 42-gallon barrel.
U.S. crude normally sells for about $2 above the OPEC-monitored
crudes.
   Indonesian Oil Minister Ginandjar Kartasasmita was quoted earlier
this month as saying he was not satisfied with the market's recent
performance.
   ``We have not been able to reach the $18 per barrel price level
that we wanted, except for a few weeks earlier this summer,'' he
told OPECNA, the cartel's news agency.
   At their June conference, the ministers agreed to begin the tough
task of finding a more acceptable way to figure out each country's
take of the cartel's daily output.
   But analysts detected less willingness now _ with higher
production and weaker prices _ to try to solve the problem.
   Nevertheless, they expected OPEC Secretary-General Subroto to put
forth proposals for drawing up quotas that would consider only
oil-related factors. Some members have suggested that quotas take
into account a country's ``need'' for oil revenue as determined by
its foreign debt, balance of payments and population.
   While quotas were likely to grab most of the attention, the
ministers were also expected to decide whether to boost their supply
cap to 20 million barrels a day in the last quarter.
   An OPEC official, who demanded anonymity, said there was ``a
slight possibility'' they would do so.
   ``They may want to narrow the gap between the quota and actual
production,'' said Bahman Karbassioun, an oil consultant in Vienna,
Austria.
   But he said production ``could go even higher'' if countries
failed to agree to abide by their ceilings.
   The International Energy Agency reported in its Monthly Oil
Market Report that the nations lifted output in August to 21.6
million barrels a day, the highest so far this year. The agency is
an arm of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development,
made up of two-dozen Western nations.
   The eight-member Long-term Strategy and Price-Monitoring
Committee includes ministers from Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Nigeria, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela. The other five nations
_ Gabon, Ecuador, Libya, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates _ were
also invited to attend.
   Saudi Arabia's oil chief, Hisham Nazer, was reported recovering
from surgery earlier this month in the United States and was not
expected to attend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890921-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PPG-Clorox     09-21 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PPG-Clorox,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>PPG Buys Paint Units from Clorox</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PPG Industries Inc. said Thursday it purchased
the Olympic HomeCare Products and Lucite HomeCare Products
subsidiaries from Clorox Co. for $130 million.
   PPG said the acquisition includes headquarters offices in
Bellvue, Wash., and plants in Ballard, Wash.; Batavia, Ill.;
Louisville, Ky.; and Langley, British Columbia. It said the units
have about 350 workers.
   PPG said combined annual sales of the paint and stains
subsidiaries of oakland, calif.-based Clorox exceed $100 million.
   Eugene B. Mosier, PPG group vice president for coatings and
resins, said the addition of the Olympic and Lucite product lines
``will contribute to the profitable growth of our architectural
coatings business.''
   PPG markets paints under the Pittsburgh Paints name in North
America and the PPG Corona brand name in Europe.
   Clorox Chairman Charles R. Weaver said in June his cmpany had
decided to sell the paints and stains businesses ``to focus
resources on its core business as a diversified manufacturer and
marketer of household grocery products.''
</TEXT>
