<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1957EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Ferranti     09-21 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Ferranti,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ferranti Plans To Sell $158 Million in Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferranti International Signal PLC said Thursday it
plans to sell $158 million in assets to reduce its debt and that it
had reached agreement with its creditor banks on a support program.
   The program is to help Ferranti weather any financial
difficulties resulting from losses related to irregularities it
recently discovered in its accounts.
   Ferranti's discovery of possible contract fraud by its Lancaster,
Pa.-based subsidiary International Signal and Control led the
company to seek assurances from its banks they would hold open lines
of credit.
   Ferranti Chairman Derek Alun-Jones announced the latest
developments in a Thursday letter to employees, a copy of which was
obtained by the AP-Dow Jones News Service.
   It said the company ``has now reached agreement with its bankers
by which credit facilities for the company are in place to take it
forward.''
   The letter didn't elaborate on the extent of the credit.
   It said Ferranti was in talks with parties for the sale of about
$158 million, or 100 million British pounds, of ``peripheral''
assets.
   Alun-Jones said Monday that an investigation of contract
irregularities at International Signal and Control suggested that
Ferranti was ``at least misled and possibly made the victim of
serious fraud.''
   But he said these problems affected only a few transactions and
were not connected with other important contracts.
   The Sunday Times of London reported that the company might have
to write off $237 million or more against non-existent contracts for
which the company had previously believed it had been paid.
   The newspaper also reported that International Signal and Control
has been the target of a secret, two-year investigation by the U.S.
Justice Department for allegedly selling arms illegally in the
Middle East and South Africa.
   Trading in Ferranti shares was suspended last week and the annual
shareholders' meeting postponed due to problems with the company's
accounts.
   Ferranti merged with International Signal and Control two years
ago in a $656 million deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
