<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-21 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Moves Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground against the major
currencies in quiet dealings Thursday.
   Gold prices were unchanged to slightly higher.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, a troy ounce of gold finished
at $365.50, up 60 cents from Wednesday. Republic National Bank later
quoted a bid of $363.85 for a troy ounce of gold, up 25 cents from
late Wednesday.
   Currency traders continued to square up their positions ahead of
this weekend's meeting in Washington of the Group of Seven finance
ministers and central bankers. The G-7 includes representatives from
the United States, Japan, West Germany, France, Britain, Italy and
Canada.
   Although dealers were divided over whether any new initiatives
would result from the meeting, the underlying sentiment toward the
dollar remained bullish.
   With the Federal Reserve openly intervening throughout the week
to drive the dollar lower, ``one would believe that something will
happen (to push the dollar down), but we're seeing a continued
demand for dollars,'' said Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Recent statements by Japanese and West German officials indicated
some concern about the dollar's strength. But at regularly scheduled
meeting of Bundesbank officials Thursday failed to result in an
expected hike in West German interest rates.
   Some traders are anticipating higher West German and Japanese
interest rates in tandem with softer rates in the United States, a
scenario that would depress the dollar.
   ``That would take away the interest-rate differential, which is
sustaining the demand for dollars,'' Flanagan said.
   Separately, the dollar failed to respond to the Commerce
Department's downward revision in the second-quarter gross national
product. The government pegged economic growth at a moderate 2.5
percent during the April-June period.
   ``The technicals are bearish, and you would think the momentum
would be on the downside,'' said Linda McLaughlin, a trader at
Chemical New York Capital Markets Group. ``But it looks like we're
having real difficulty getting the dollar lower.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.25 yen to a closing 145.00 yen. Later in London,
it was quoted at a higher rate of 145.10 yen. In New York, the
dollar closed at 145.65 yen, up from 145.10 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5805 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5820 late Wednesday. In
New York, one pound cost $1.5790, less expensive than Wednesday's
$1.5835.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, included: 1.9846 West German marks, up from 1.9397;
1.6835 Swiss francs, up from 1.6815; 6.5740 French francs, up from
6.5560; 1,400.25 Italian lire, up from 1,399.00, and 1.1830 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1833.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.9435 West German marks, up from 1.9400; 1.6830 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6800; 6.5710 French francs, up from 6.5585; 2.1920
Dutch guilders, up from 2.1890; 1,401.00 Italian lire, up from
1,399.50; 1.1842 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1824.
   Gold held steady in London at a late bid price of $363.25 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Wednesday's late bid. In Zurich, gold also was
unchanged at a bid $363.50. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.69 to
close at a bid $364.11.
   Silver prices rose. On New York's Comex, silver closed at $5.181
a troy ounce, up from $5.119 on Wednesday. Earlier in London, the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $5.14 a troy ounce,
compared with Wednesday's $5.13.
</TEXT>
