<HEAD>Dow Jones Offers $18 a Share for Remaining Telerate Stake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs with Telerate comment; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs,
`Investors were...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. offered Thursday to acquire the
33.8 percent interest in Telerate Inc. that it does not already own
in a deal that values the financial information company at nearly
$1.71 billion.
   In a letter to Telerate President and Chief Executive Officer
Neil Hirsch, Dow Jones said it would begin an $18 a share cash
tender offer for the stake in Telerate now held by the public.
Telerate has approximately 94.9 million outstanding shares.
   Telerate said it appointed a committee of two independent members
of its board to consider the offer and would have no comment pending
evaluation.
   Investors were enthusiastic about the offer, and bid the price of
Telerate stock up $5 to $20.12{ a share in early New York Stock
Exchange trading.
   Dow Jones said it was willing to discuss its offer with Telerate,
an indication that it might increase its bid.
   Telerate supplies computerized financial information to
subscribers that include brokerage houses.
   Dow Jones, which also provides business information services,
publishes newspapers including The Wall Street Journal and Barron's.
   Warren Phillips, the chairman of Dow Jones, said in a statement
his company was seeking full ownership of Telerate ``to obtain
operational efficiencies and to permit even closer and more
efficient working relationships in marketing, customer service and
the management of our related businesses.''
