<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     09-21 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hit New Record for 12th Straight Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 466 money market mutual
funds rose $1.30 billion in the latest week to a new all-time high
of $348.98 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   It was the 12th straight week that fund assets reached a new
record and reflected the growing popularity of money market mutual
funds despite a general softening of interest rates.
   The institute, a Washington-based mutual-fund trade group, also
revised upward its week-earlier asset figure to $347.68 billion from
the $347.07 billion first reported, largely because of the addition
of three new funds.
   It said that in the latest week, assets of 230 general purpose
funds rose $1.13 billion to $113.21 billion, assets of 95
broker-dealer funds increased $815.8 million to $151.56 billion, and
assets of 141 institutional funds declined $645.4 million to $84.21
billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.26 percent from 8.27 percent the
previous week, said Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.26 percent from 8.28 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 37
days, up from 36 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts unchanged from a week earlier at
6.44 percent.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, remained unchanged from a week earlier at 5.10 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.24
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.25 the
previous week. Yields were 8.29 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.30 percent; 8.21 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.22 percent;
and 8.21 percent on 5-year CDs, unchanged.
</TEXT>
