<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-21 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Rally, Bracing for Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rallied strongly Thursday on the
Chicago Board of Trade as the markets braced for the first hard
freeze of the season in the Midwest.
   On other markets, silver futures were sharply higher for the
second consecutive session; energy futures were mixed; and livestock
and meat futures were mixed.
   Wheat futures settled 2 cents to 3 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in December at $3.94} a bushel; corn futures were
unchanged to 3 cents higher with December at $2.31{ a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 2 cents higher with December at $1.41{ a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 7\ cents higher with November at
$5.82} a bushel.
   The rally was rooted in forecasts for freezing temperatures this
weekend and early next week, possibly reaching as far south as
northern Arkansas and Tennessee.
   ``This is record-breaking or near-record-breaking type cold
coming in,'' said Charles Notis of Freese-Notis Weather Inc., a
private forecasting firm in Des Moines, Iowa.
   Most corn and soybean crops west of the Mississippi River and in
Illinois have matured beyond the danger stage. But the crops in
other Midwestern states east of the Mississippi _ especially
soybeans _ are susceptible to freeze damage.
   Notis estimated that 500 million bushels of soybeans, a little
less than a quarter of the crop, were still vulnerable to frost
damage and that 45 million to 70 million bushels could be hurt by
the arctic high pressure system sweeping down from northwestern
Canada.
   Most of that damage is likely to occur in Indiana and Ohio, he
said.
   In the western Corn Belt, where the crops are more mature, ``I
don't think you're talking about yield losses, I think you're
talking about quality problems,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Frost could slow the natural drying of mature corn and lock some
chlorophyll into not-quite-ripe soybeans, causing some
discoloration, Gustafson said.
   Dennis Michelsen, a meteorologist with Murray &amp; Trettl Inc. of
Northfield, Ill., predicted a less-severe freeze than Notis.
   Still, he said, ``I would expect to see a killing frost over a
great portion of the upper Midwest by early next week. We've got
quite a cold snap here.''
   Silver futures scooted up sharply on New York's Commodity
Exchange as the dollar weakened but gold futures made only slight
gains, held back by the oil market's lackluster showing.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 60 cents higher with October at $366.30
a troy ounce; silver was 6 cents to 6.4 cents higher with September
at $5.181 a troy ounce.
   Crude-oil futures were narrowly mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange but near-month gasoline and heating-oil futures rose
sharply amid concerns about potential damage to refineries from
Hurricane Hugo.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents lower to 3
cents higher with November at $19.62 a barrel; heating oil was .25
cent to 1.03 cents higher with October at 57.58 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .30 cent lower to 2.12 cents higher with
October at 61.86 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .55 cent higher with October
at 71.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .20
cent higher with September at 83.10 cents a pound; hogs were .43
cent lower to .13 cent higher with October at 41.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were 1.10 cents lower to .60 cent higher with
February at 48.75 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
