<FIRST>u f AM-Immunex 1stLd-Writethru f0215 09-21 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immunex, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0215,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immunex Transforming Into Pharmaceutical Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 4th graf pvs, `Overall, I... to UPDATE with
closing stock price; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Immunex uses...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immunex Corp. on Thursday announced a plan that
will transform it from a research-dominated firm in medical
biotechnology into a conventional pharmaceutical company.
   The 8-year-old company, based in Seattle, said it would achieve
the transition primarily by reacquiring rights to sell
Immunex-developed products in the United States. In return, its
business partners will get rights to some other Immunex products,
primarily for overseas distribution.
   Immunex's plan will require the company to build a sales staff
from scratch, but it should permit it to keep more of the profits
from its work, said Joseph Edelman, an analyst at Labe, Simpson &amp; Co.
   ``Overall, I think it's an aggressive strategy,'' Edelman said.
   In over-the-counter trading Thursday, Immunex stock fell 50 cents
to $16.50.
   Immunex uses gene-splicing and other biotechnology techniques to
create products for medical treatment, mainly products that either
promote or inhibit the activity of the immune system.
   Products that are being tested on people in government-supervised
trials include ones for cancer therapy, wound healing and protection
of bone marrow from the harmful effects of radiation therapy and
chemotherapy.
   The biggest threat to Immunex is that other companies developing
products in the same field could challenge its patent position,
Edelman said.
   At the end of 1988 Immunex had marketing rights for only two of
its own products. After the changes announced Thursday, some of
which occurred earlier this year, it will have rights to more than a
dozen.
   Like many small biotech companies, Immunex had given marketing
rights for its products to other companies in exchange for research
funding and help in manufacturing. Even after the deals, other
companies will retain foreign marketing rights for many
Immunex-related products.
   Immunex's partners include Eastman Kodak Co., West Germany's
Behringwerke AG and Syntex Corp.
   The restructuring will give Immunex a five-year head start on its
plan to transform itself into a conventional pharmaceutical company
by 1995, Stephen Duzan, the chairman and chief executive, said at a
New York news conference.
   ``We're going to be a modest-sized but fully integrated
pharmaceutical company,'' Duzan said in an interview.
   Immunex said it is poised to enter the cancer market in the
coming five years and the infectious disease and autoimmune disease
markets in 1995 to 2000. Autoimmune diseases are those such as
arthritis and diabetes in which the body is attacked by its own
immune-system defenses.
   Immunex reacquired worldwide marketing and manufacturing rights
to interleukin-1 receptor and interleukin-4 receptor products by
restructuring its joint venture with Kodak's Sterling Drug Co.
   It also reacquired U.S. co-marketing and manufacturing rights
from Behringwerke AG for CM-CSF (granulocyte macrophage colony
stimulating factor), interleukin-3 and other CSF products.
   In return, it gave Behringwerke the foreign rights to a package
of receptor products, including receptors for interleukin-1,
interleukin-4 and other undisclosed receptor products.
   It retained all North American rights for all receptor products.
Receptors can block the destructive action of the immune system by
serving as decoys for attackers.
</TEXT>
