<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FraudSettlement     09-21 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fraud Settlement,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>ITT Consumer Financial To Repay Millions in Consumer Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ITT Consumer Financial Corp. agreed Thursday
to pay what could total more than $50 million for allegedly bilking
hundreds of thousands of Californians with loans later packed with
extra requirements.
   California Attorney General John Van de Kamp called the civil
settlement capping a three-year investigation ``one of the largest
and most sweeping consumer fraud settlements in American history.''
   He said Minneapolis-based ITT lured applicants into expensive
loans packed with extras such as various forms of insurance and
thrift club memberships. Applicants were bilked of as much as $2,000
each, he said.
   ITT is the parent company of co-defendants Aetna Finance Co. _
which Van de Kamp said had no connection with Aetna Insurance Co. _
ITT Lyndon Property Insurance Co., and ITT Lyndon Life Insurance Co.
   All the consumers involved are to be sent letters explaining the
settlement.
   Van de Kamp estimated as many as 300,000 victims but said only
about one third are expected to seek restitution, with the total
return between $25 million and $50 million.
   ITT also will pay $10.5 million to establish consumer protection
trust funds, $8.67 million in civil penalties and $575,000 for legal
costs and a toll-free phone number for consumers claiming refunds.
   Van de Kamp said ITT took advantage of people ``in desperate need
of money'' and charged up to 35 percent interest on loans and
attached items.
   ITT said in a statement it agreed to restitution at the same time
a civil suit was filed Thursday in Alameda County Superior Court. It
neither admitted nort denied wrongdoing.
   ITT said the accusations ``without doubt were contraventions to
our procedures and not a pattern of behavior condoned by the
company,'' but added that ``pre-existing safeguards'' existed on
loans and insurance.
   Claimants will be entitled to interest paid, interest on the
interest for years involved and the cost of all extras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
