<DOCNO> AP890921-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Morgan-LoanReserve 1stLd-Writethru   09-21 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morgan-Loan Reserve, 1st Ld-Writethru,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.P. Morgan Adding $2 Billion to Loan-Loss Reserve</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with background, analyst comments; adds
byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc. moved ahead of other major
banking companies Thursday by adding $2 billion to its cushion of
reserves for loan losses, indicating deeper pessimism about the
chances of repayment by developing countries.
   Morgan's action was far more severe than those taken earlier this
week by Chase Manhattan Corp. and Manufacturers Hanover Corp.
   Morgan's reserves now equal 100 percent of its medium- and
long-term loans to developing countries. In contrast, Chase's equal
46 percent after its addition this week and Manufacturers Hanover's
36 percent.
   Morgan, the parent of Morgan Guaranty Trust Co., said it would
continue doing business in developing countries but would focus on
merchant banking rather than general lending. Merchant banking
involves providing advice, trading and investing and finance.
   ``We will continue to consider lending in appropriate specific
transactions. We intend to continue to play a constructive role in
developing countries,'' Morgan spokeswoman Kathleen Baum said.
   The bigger cushion indicates Morgan has gotten tired of prolonged
and unfruitful negotiations with debtor nations on repayment, said
Stephen Berman, a banking analyst at County Securities USA.
   ``I think they just want to say the hell with this,'' he said.
   Morgan, the nation's third-largest bank-holding company, also is
one of the financially strongest. That means it was able to take the
punishment of the $2 billion addition, which will result in a loss
of about $1.8 billion in the current quarter.
   Morgan's action could be an indication of trouble for the
negotiations on debt relief under a plan devised by Treasury
Secretary Nicholas F. Brady, Berman said. Less developed countries
have debts of $1.3 trillion.
   ``Early on in this process everybody sort of pulled together,
followed the lead of Citibank,'' Berman said. ``Everybody is sort of
cutting and running now and pursuing their own interest.''
   This week's round of additions to loan-loss reserves was
triggered by the conclusion last week of an accord to provide debt
relief to Mexico under the Brady plan, which emphasizes debt
forgiveness by the banks.
   The terms of the Mexico accord made banks acknowledge that they
had been overly optimistic in their earlier expectations for
repayment. But Morgan's action seemed to go beyond necessity, Berman
said.
   ``Economic and political problems have intensified in several
countries where we have significant exposure, including problems in
paying interest when due,'' Lewis T. Preston, Morgan's chairman,
said in a written statement.
   Preston said he was concerned that debtor countries could be
expecting more help from the Brady plan than the industrial
countries are likely to provide.
   He also said: ``Achieving satisfactory loan restructuring
agreements will also be more and more difficult because of
increasingly divergent approaches to LDC (less-developed country)
debt problem among bank lenders and among governments.''
   Morgan now has a total of $3 billion in loan-loss reserves, with
$2.8 billion of that unofficially allocated to loans to developing
countries. That $2.8 billion is equal to 70 percent of Morgan's
total loans to developing countries, and 100 percent of the
medium-and long-term loans to those nations. In an indication of
Morgan's financial strength, Moody's Investors Service and Standards
and Poor's both confirmed their investment-grade ratings on Morgan
senior debt.
   The last big round of additions to reserves was in late 1987, and
many banking companies have not taken any action since then.
   For example, Chemical Banking Corp.'s loan-loss reserves equal
just 28 percent of its loans to developing countries, the level it
reached in late 1987, spokesman Charles Salmans said.
   Chase Manhattan said Wednesday it would take a $1.31 billion
charge in the third quarter, largely to boost its reserves for
troubled loans to developing countries.
   Chase also announced plans to raise $500 million by selling new
common shares.
   Chase said its reserve increase would boost its reserves for
losses on loans to developing countries to 46 percent of its $6.2
billion in such loans and would produce a third-quarter loss for the
holding company of $1.11 billion.
   Manufacturers Hanover on Monday added $950 million to its
loan-loss reserves and sold control of its asset-based lending unit,
CIT Group, to Japan's Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank for $1.28 billion.
   Manufacturers Hanover also agreed to sell a 4.9 percent stake in
the parent company to Dai-Ichi Kangyo for another $120 million.
   Manufacturers Hanover said the addition to its loan-loss reserve
would produce a third-quarter loss of $775 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
