<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-IMF-WorldBankDebt     09-21 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IMF-World Bank Debt,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Bank Reports Incomes Up in Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incomes rose sharply for people in key Asian
countries last year, with Japan's increase almost twice that of the
United States, the World Bank reported Thursday.
   In Japan, the average went up to $12,480 from 1987's $11,780,
while average income in the United States rose to $14,080 from
$13,650. The figures are corrected for inflation.
   The data show that compared with wealthier countries, the Third
World is losing its share of the world's income, said John O'Connor,
who heads the bank's office on social and economic data.
   ``Comparatively, the poor are getting poorer,'' he said.
   People in countries where earnings are lower showed more modest
gains. The average South Korean had a proportionately large
increase: from $2,760 to $3,060 in 1988. India was up from $310 to
$330, the Philippines from $620 to $680 and Thailand showed a sharp
rise from $830 to $940.
   China's figure for 1988 was not in yet. In 1987, the average
Chinese had an income of $510. No figure was given for Taiwan, which
is not a member of the bank.
   ``For 1989, we expect to see a modest correction in what have
been very high rates of growth down to more sustainable levels for
India, China and several middle-income countries,'' said Attila
Karaosmanoglu, the bank's vice-president for Asia.
   The World Bank's figures deal largely with Third World countries,
since it is the largest source of loans to raise their standards of
living. Statistics for 1988 are not yet complete, officials said.
   Scattered reports for a few European countries that borrow from
the bank showed increases in Cyprus from $4,810 to $5,010 and Greece
from $4,310 to $4,440. But in Yugoslavia there was a drop, to $3,080
from $3,180 in 1987.
   In Latin America, the 1988 figure fell to $1,800 from $1,830.
   The significant losses came in the larger countries. In Brazil,
which accounts for a third of the production in the continent,
average income dropped to $1,930 from $1,980. In Mexico the fall was
to $2,260 from $2,300 and in Venezuela from $3,390 to $3,290. Chile
rose to $2,370 from $2,280, while Argentina's figure was not
available.
   For southern Africa, the bank's figures show a steady decline
since 1980, when the average income for the area was $570 a year. In
1988 it was $440. The Republic of South Africa is not included in
this calculation.
</TEXT>
