<FIRST>u f AM-UAL     09-21 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Buyout Cost Could Reach $9.45 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Texas Air-GM, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The total cost of the UAL Corp. buyout could reach
$9.45 billion, according to Securities and Exchange Commission
filings by the employee-managment group seeking to take over United
Airlines' parent.
   The group, composed of United pilots, UAL's top management and
British Airways PLC, also announced in newspaper ads Thursday the
commencement of their tender offer for all outstanding shares of
UAL's common stock for $300 a share.
   According to the merger agreement filed with the SEC on
Wednesday, the buyout group will require $6.8 billion to purchase
UAL's 22.65 million fully diluted shares.
   It said the group may refinance $950 million in existing UAL
debt, which would leave $512 million in long-term debt and $411
million in capital leases outstanding.
   Various fees and a $1.3 billion credit facility for working
capital are also included in the total buyout cost.
   The buyout, accepted by UAL's board of directors Sept. 14, will
give UAL workers 75 percent ownership of the company. Management
will own 10 percent and British Airways will own 15 percent.
   The group plans to finance the transaction with $750 million from
British Airways, $200 million in voluntary pension contributions
from the pilots, $1.3 billion from UAL cash reserves and $7.2
billion in bank loans.
</TEXT>
