<FIRST>r f BC-DuPont-Extortion     09-21 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Du Pont-Extortion,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bail Denied in Du Pont Extortion Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. magistrate denied bail Thursday to
one of three defendants charged with trying to extort $10 million
from Du Pont Co. in exchange for trade secrets stolen from the
chemical giant.
   U.S. Magistrate Sue Robinson denied bail for Bruno Skerianz
during a pretrial detention hearing, saying there was a possibility
Skerianz would not show for trial because he was an international
traveler with ``considerable resources.''
   Skerianz was returned to the United States from Switzerland last
week. He had fought extradition since his arrest there earlier this
year.
   Defense attorney Richard Zappa had sought limited electronic
monitoring for Skerianz.
   Skerianz and two other suspects have been in custody at
undisclosed locations since their arrests in February. All are
charged with one count each of attempted extortion. They face up to
20 years in prison and a $250,000 fine each.
   The federal government plans to drop charges against a fourth
suspect, Maria I. Lorenzo de Bianchini, who is living in a private
home in Elsmere. According to court documents, the charges will be
dropped in exchange for her testimony if needed.
   The three Argentinian nationals and Skerianz were arrested in
Geneva, Switzerland, after an aborted meeting at which Du Pont was
to pay $10 million to the suspects in exchange for ``sensitive
documents'' concerning Lycra, Du Pont's trade name for spandex
fiber, the FBI said.
   The suspects had all worked at Du Pont's plant in Mercedes,
Argentina, one of several plants that make the fiber.
   Spandex is used primarily in swimming suits, leotards and
pantyhose.
</TEXT>
