<FIRST>r f BC-China-SovietTrade     09-21 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Soviet Trade,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>China-Soviet Barter Trade Gains Favor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China prefers to sell its goods for Western
hard currency but its imports from the Soviet Union, paid for by
bartering, are way up, the Central Intelligence Agency reports.
   ``Chinese imports of goods such as timber and fertilizer, where
the quality of the Soviet commodity is comparable to that elsewhere,
will probably grow this year as Beijing turns to barter to conserve
foreign exchange,'' the CIA said in an analysis prepared for
Congress and released this week to the press.
   Sino-Soviet trade grew 27 percent least year to a two-way total
of $3.3 billion and figures for the first half of 1989 show even
stronger growth, with Chinese imports surging by 63 percent and
exports up 12 percent, the report said.
   Trade along the Soviet-Chinese border has risen swiftly to
account for 10 percent of the two countries' trade, welcomed by
remote Chinese provinces lacking easy access to other markets, it
noted.
   The report also disclosed that 8,000 Chinese laborers are working
on projects in the Soviet Union under arrangements generally
providing payment to China with a percentage of the production. At
least 5,000 more are expected to follow, it said.
   The two countries normalized relations last spring, providing a
boost to their economic relations which, however, appear to be
reaching their limits, since Beijing will continue to favor Western
technology, said the CIA.
</TEXT>
