<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 2133EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-FantasyTakeover     09-21 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fantasy Takeover,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carl Icahn, Jesse Jackson, Others Play Simulated Takeover Game</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Do takeover battles really end when the power
system blows during a climactic board meeting?
   Probably not. But that was about the only thing clearly out of
character Thursday as TWA chairman and investor Carl Icahn and a
cast of corporate and civic heavyweights including the Rev. Jesse
Jackson put some of their well-honed moves on public display in a
three-hour simulated takeover.
   ``I think it's been incredibly realistic,'' Arthur R. Taylor, the
dean of the Graduate School of Business Administration at Fordham
University, said shortly before the lights dimmed and the
microphones went dead.
   He said the participants in the program that people from his
school designed were ``acting as they do at real board meetings.''
   Robert O. Anderson, the former head of the Atlantic Richfield Co.
who played the role of the chief executive of the company under
siege, rated the interplay among the board members ``surprisingly
good.''
   But Frederick H. Joseph, the chief executive of the investment
banking firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., cautioned that there were
limits to the imagined reality. ``What we are doing in 10 minutes
takes 10 days,'' he said.
   In the game, Joseph played an investment banker advising Icahn,
who was cast as an investor with a small stake in the beleaguered
target company and was considering launching an alternative takeover
bid.
   The program was put on at a conference run by the World
Management Council, an international organization of management
groups.
   The simulation went a step further than recent exercises in which
prominent people in various fields are brought together for a
moderator-led discussion about a hypothetical case.
   In this corporate war game, the directors of the imaginary Main
Street Industries Inc., a Southern retailing company, met in one
room to mourn the death of their chairman and to assess their
options should the swirl of takeover rumors produce an offer.
   At the same time, Icahn was closeted in a room across the hall,
talking one-by-one with with financial advisers, union officials and
representatives of a foundation that had an 18 percent stake in the
company about his plans to make a bid for the company.
   Several hundred people attending the conference were invited to
walk back and forth between the rooms as they wished as the scenario
unfolded through a series of twists and turns.
   Conference staffers added to the atmosphere with periodic updates
on the company's stock price and news headlines, such as Icahn's
notice that he bought an 8 percent stake in the firm.
   Observers got to watch Icahn court the unions and the foundation
for support before going to the board. They saw him needle his
investment bankers about the fees they wanted to finance the bid and
get so swept up in the franctic pace of activity that he chided an
inattentive assistant by blurting out, ``Come on, you're not at
Smith College.''
   When Icahn finally got in to see the board, he found they had
been doing their homework as well and felt that neither his offer
nor a competing bid was worth accepting.
   Board members said they would investigate a recapitalization
instead.
   The real-life power outage cut short any additional countermoves,
and the game was declared finished.
   ``I enjoyed it,'' Anderson said. Icahn concurred, saying ``It was
entertaining. It was fun.''
   Jackson, the civil rights activist who played a foundation
representative interested in protecting the communities and workers
served by the stores, said the game created a ``healthy
environment'' for discussion of tough issues.
   ``I hope it increases all of our sensitivity,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
