<FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 0046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AmericanHome-Generics     09-21 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-American Home-Generics,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Home Products Halts Generic Drug Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Home Products Corp. is halting
production and distribution of all its generic drugs after federal
inspectors found discrepancies and possible misrepresentation in
some of the firm's records, according to a report published Thursday.
   Quantum Pharmics Ltd., a subsidiary of New York-based American
Home, took the action after an investigation by the parent company
and an inspection by the Food and Drug Administration, The
Washington Post reported.
   The FDA said it ``uncovered some discrepancies in records
associated with three of their products. In those three instances,
some data appears to have been misrepresented to the agency during
the approval process.''
   Quantum is one of 20 generic drug companies being inspected as
part of a government investigation of the industry.
   The company manufactures 21 generic drugs that include a variety
of anti-hypertensive, anti-arthritic and anti-depressant drugs.
   American Home Products is a major brand-name drug maker and
consumer products manufacturer. Among its well-known
over-the-counter drugs are Anacin and Dristan. Its prescription drug
operations include Wyeth Labs, Whitehall Labs and Ayerst Labs.
</TEXT>
